<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marines Practice City Rescue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTEREY, Calif. (AP) -- Hundreds of Marines practiced rescuing a  
city threatened by chemical terrorism today outside the view of 
dozens of protesters who said the military exercise might harm 
Monterey Bay wildlife. 
</P>
<P>
	The controversial military exercise, known as Urban Warrior, was  
launched without the beachfront invasion originally planned. As an 
early morning fog cleared off Monterey Bay, helicopters transported 
troops in ships offshore to the airport, where they were whisked to 
exercise sites by bus. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything is on track and going well,'' Marine Lt. Col. Jenny  
Holbert said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, some 100 demonstrators lined Monterey's main waterfront  
street Saturday, dancing and banging bongo drums in front of the 
beach where an amphibious landing first was planned. 
</P>
<P>
	Another dozen gathered outside training sites where the Marine  
Corps had erected two mock villages, and others were bicycling 
around town chanting their protests. 
</P>
<P>
	Protesters said they were hoping to disrupt the controversial  
military war games, the largest of more than two dozen Urban 
Warrior exercises held around the country in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm out here to protest this madness. It's a waste of  
taxpayers' funds,'' said Ted Lorec of Santa Cruz, who held a sign 
reading: ``Marines Go Home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Plans for the $4.5 million experiment originally called for 250  
Marines to land at the beach and drive nearly 50 Humvees, 5-ton 
trucks and light armored vehicles to training sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Environmentalists and peace activists opposed the event, saying  
the invasion would harm fragile bay marine life. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, the California Coastal Commission agreed, rejecting  
Navy-Marine Corps claims that a seaborne assault would not disturb 
gray whales, snowy plovers and sea otters. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon then canceled the landing, focusing on exercises at  
the Naval Postgraduate School near downtown and the Defense 
Language Institute at the Presidio of Monterey. 
</P>
<P>
	Using a fictional scenario, Monterey was transformed into a city  
in a friendly foreign nation that had requested assistance from the 
United States. One setup replicated a Korean village in Korea and 
another tested the military's ability to neutralize weapons of mass 
destruction. 
</P>
<P>
	Cara West, a resident who came out to watch the helicopters,  
said she worried the exercises might harm the marine habitat and 
was glad to learn they were landing at the airport instead. The 
only military action visible in town were helicopters overhead and 
the occasional military vehicle passing by. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people in our town are against it but I think we need  
the practice,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
