<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Bomb Explodes at NC Abortion Clinic  
</P>
<P>
	ASHEVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- A bomb exploded outside an abortion  
clinic today, causing no injuries and little damage because the 
device only detonated partially. The clinic is less than 75 miles 
near the mountainous area where serial bombing suspect Eric Rudolph 
is believed to be hiding. A second device was also found at the 
clinic, authorities said. ``It appeared to be a very large 
device,'' Police Chief Will Annarino said. ``I really can't get 
into how large it is right now. But it appears it could have caused 
a lot of damage.'' Homes and business near the building were 
evacuated and police cordoned off the road around the clinic. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Urges More Police Training  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- President Clinton today proposed  
improved training and other steps to restore ``the bonds of trust'' 
between the public and law enforcement. Recent questionable 
shootings by police that took the lives of young blacks in New 
York, Pittsburgh and Riverside, Calif., have revived debates about 
how officers handle confrontations with minorities. In New Jersey, 
state troopers have come under fire for conducting traffic stops 
based on a driver's race -- so-called racial profiling. In his 
weekly radio address, Clinton proposed a $40 million funding 
increase to improve police training nationwide. 

</P>
<P>
	Bomb Kills 13 in Istanbul  
</P>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- At least 13 people were killed today  
after attackers set a crowded six-story department store on fire. 
It was one of Turkey's deadliest attacks in years. President 
Suleyman Demirel condemned the attack, and Prime Minister Bulent 
Ecevit said it was part of a campaign aimed at disrupting the April 
18 national elections. Police immediately beefed up security in 
this city of 12 million people, conducting identity checks on 
public transportation and warning people not to take parcels from 
strangers. 

</P>
<P>
	Ethnic Albanians Back Kosovo Accord  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Departing for peace talks in France,  
ethnic Albanian delegates said today they were ready to sign a 
U.S.-backed Kosovo peace plan if the Serb-led government backs down 
on its opposition to allowing NATO troops to enforce it. Meanwhile, 
three bombs went off this afternoon in two government-controlled 
cities, killing at least six people and injuring more than 60. In 
one of the cities, Kosovska Mitrovica, the blast occurred next to a 
mosque in a fruit and vegetable market packed with weekend 
shoppers. 

</P>
<P>
	Indonesia Closes 38 Private Banks  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- The Indonesian government closed 38  
private banks today and took over seven others in line with reforms 
required by the International Monetary Fund. Foreign lenders have 
required that Indonesia open up its shattered economy in exchange 
for billions of dollars of loans. ``This is a sweeping set of 
fundamental reforms designed to bring our banking system back to 
financial health,'' said Indonesian Senior Economics Minister 
Ginandjar Kartasasmita. 

</P>
<P>
	Balloonists Pass Halfway Point  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- An English-Swiss balloon team prepared to re-enter  
the jet stream after passing the halfway point in their bid to be 
the first to circle the globe nonstop, their control center said. 
Pilots Brian Jones of England and Bertrand Piccard of Switzerland 
floated across the Pacific Ocean today at a leisurely 35 mph. The 
balloon was cruising at 28,500 feet. By early tomorrow, the 
Breitling Orbiter 3 had traveled more than 13,670 miles since 
leaving the Swiss Alps on March 1. 

</P>
<P>
	Moya Wins, Earns No. 1 Ranking  
</P>
<P>
	INDIAN WELLS, Calif. (AP) -- Carlos Moya beat Gustavo Kuerten and  
become the first Spaniard to earn the world No. 1 men's tennis 
ranking. Moya defeated Kuerten 6-3, 1-6, 6-1 in their Champions Cup 
semifinal. The win assured Moya of jumping from No. 4 to the top 
spot when the ATP rankings are released Monday. He replaces Pete 
Sampras, who lost in the second round of the Champions Cup. 

</P>
<P>
	Mexico Clinches U.S. Cup Soccer  
</P>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Mexico benefited from an own goal by the U.S.  
defender Robin Fraser on a play that also resulted in an injury to 
U.S. goalkeeper Tony Meola, and won 2-1 today to clinch the U.S. 
Cup '99 title. The Americans suffered their first setback under 
coach Bruce Arena, whose record went to 3-1-2. Mexico remained 
unbeaten (3-0-4) in the last seven outings against the United 
States and improved to 4-3-6 in the series since 1991. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by STEPHANIE GASKELL  
</P>
</TEXT>
