<HEADLINE> McCain: GOP Must Get Back to Basics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Sen. John McCain of Arizona, trying to  
build support in a state where the Republican Party establishment 
has thrown its weight behind Texas Gov. George Bush and Elizabeth 
Dole, urged the party to unite once again behind the basics of less 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people of South Carolina are independent, they're  
patriotic,'' he said Friday at a fundraiser. ``They have a very 
significant veterans population and I intend to motivate them to 
support my candidacy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCain, a decorated Vietnam veteran, must topple Bush and former  
American Red Cross President Dole to win the South's earliest 
presidential primary. 
</P>
<P>
	Though McCain has not officially declared his candidacy, he  
repeated his promise not to ``stoop to negative personal attacks 
against fellow Republicans.'' He also urged South Carolina 
Republicans to unite behind the party basics of less government and 
lower taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans must ``remind voters that we are not simply the  
anti-Clinton party,'' McCain said. ``I believe people understand 
very well what we stand against. We need to remind them what we 
stand for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But as he talked of unity within the party on core issues, he  
spoke out against New York Gov. George Pataki's call for the 
removal of the anti-abortion plank from the GOP's national 
platform. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do not agree,'' McCain said, conceding that he might  
consider an abortion-rights running mate if that person had good 
``overall qualifications. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain faces an uphill battle in South Carolina, where Bush  
enjoys the support of key party officials, including Lt. Gov. Bob 
Peeler and House Speaker David Wilkins. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican Attorney General Charlie Condon is state chairman for  
Dole's presidential bid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
