<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drunken Driver Gets 10 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	POMONA, Calif. (AP) -- The family of a Jehovah's Witness who  
refused a blood transfusion after she was hit by a drunken driver 
scolded the man's defense for blaming the woman's death on her 
religious faith. 
</P>
<P>
	``You took the thing we loved most about my mom, her faith in  
God, and used it as an excuse,'' said Jeff Russell, the son of 
Jadine Russell, as he faced driver Keith Cook across the courtroom 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Cook, 32, listened intently then apologized before being  
sentenced to 10 years in prison for manslaughter. Mrs. Russell died 
after refusing a transfusion following the collision. 
</P>
<P>
	In courtroom statements punctuated by sobs from the audience,  
Mrs. Russell's family spoke of her noble life and the recklessness 
of Cook, who drove drunk while on probation for a previous 
conviction for driving under the influence. 
</P>
<P>
	Cook's sister told reporters he should not have received jail  
time because ``he's not a murderer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He was responsible for getting in his car and driving,'' Dodie  
Cook O'Keeffe said. ``But she made the decision she was going to 
die that night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Russell, 55, was standing on the side of the road with  
police after a minor car accident on the night of March 7, 1998, 
when Cook slammed his pickup truck into a stationary car, pushing 
the vehicle into the woman. 
</P>
<P>
	Her daughter, Jennifer, and two police officers also were hurt.  
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Russell suffered broken bones and severe bleeding, but she  
told emergency workers and doctors ``No blood!'' at least 10 times, 
and even tried to pull out an intravenous line, relatives said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jehovah's Witnesses believe there is a biblical basis for  
refusing other people's blood. 
</P>
<P>
	On the night of the accident, Cook's blood-alcohol level was  
0.17 percent, more than twice the legal limit. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Unger, the lawyer who based Cook's defense on the  
victim's religion, was scolded by Mrs. Russell's husband, James: 
``Shame on you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Unger made no apologies, saying outside court that it was  
his job to defend his client in the best way possible. 
</P>
<P>
	Cook said he felt ``sorrow and remorse'' and would try to atone  
with good works when he is released. 
</P>
<P>
	``If she had survived this accident, she would've been one of  
the people visiting you in jail,'' Jeff Russell said. ``She 
would've said, 'The man made a mistake.' She would've told us not 
to hate you. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most importantly, you've not affected our faith,'' he added.  
``We, as Jehovah's Witnesses, will not give you that power. You've 
bruised us but you haven't crushed us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A jury in December convicted Cook of manslaughter instead of  
murder, rejecting the prosecution's claim that the drunken driver 
was solely responsible for the death of Mrs. Russell. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
