<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> B-52 Bomber Will Fly 40 More Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- If the Air Force has figured right, its  
4-decade-old B-52 bombers will still be flying at 80 years old, 
meaning the oldest plane in the U.S. bomber fleet is only now in 
middle age. 
</P>
<P>
	The granddaddy of long-range bombers is nowhere near retiring.  
In fact, the Air Force said Friday, it will remain a mainstay of 
the strategic bomber fleet until a new generation arrives in about 
2037. 
</P>
<P>
	Most pilots who fly B-52s today were not yet born when their  
planes entered service in the early 1960s. And those same planes 
will be flying well into the 21st century with pilots of a 
generation yet to come. 
</P>
<P>
	That speaks highly of an airplane that already has more than  
tripled its original life expectancy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Structurally, they are in great shape,'' Lt. Gen. Ron Marcotte  
said in an interview. As commander of the 8th Air Force at 
Barksdale Air Force Base, La. -- home to 47 B-52s -- Marcotte flies 
the bombers regularly and said that with the help of exceptionally 
good maintenance the planes are ``doing extremely well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the 8th Air Force's B-52s are standing by in England for  
possible use in NATO-led airstrikes in Yugoslavia, and others are 
on the Indian Ocean island of Diego Garcia, poised to act against 
Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	The first B-52s began their Air Force duty in June 1955; the  
ones flying now were built in 1961. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's amazing,'' said Glenn Buchan, a Rand Corp. expert on  
strategic bombers. ``The B-52 is one of the most remarkably 
successful airplanes every built.'' Indeed, Buchan said in an 
interview, the B-52 might be the best model on which to develop the 
next generation of long-range bombers -- a large plane capable of 
carrying a wide array of modern weapons and firing them from a 
great distance. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force is not ready to invest in a new generation of  
bombers, however. Over the next decade or so, the service will 
devote most of its aircraft development dollars to the F-22 stealth 
fighter to replace the F-15 Strike Eagle and the so-called Joint 
Strike Fighter to replace the F-16 Fighting Falcon. 
</P>
<P>
	``Preserve what we have'' in bombers is the way Air Force  
Secretary F. Whitten Peters described the strategy Friday. He and 
Gen. Michael Ryan, the Air Force chief of staff, briefed reporters 
on a congressionally ordered ``white paper'' on the future of the 
long-range bomber fleet. 
</P>
<P>
	The upshot is that the B-52, along with the younger B-1B Lancer  
and the new, stealthy B-2 Spirit, will be kept around until about 
2037. By that time, the Air Force calculates that attrition will 
have reduced the fleet below the minimum 170 aircraft. The B-52s 
may fly to 2045, and planning for a replacement bomber might start 
in 2013. 
</P>
<P>
	There are 190 long-range bombers in the active fleet: 93 B-1s,  
76 B-52s and 21 B-2s. Only 130 of those planes are fully 
combat-ready, however. The rest are in various states of backup 
readiness. 
</P>
<P>
	The B-52s' home bases are Barksdale Air Force Base, La., and  
Minot Air Force Base, N.D.; the B-1s are mainly at Ellsworth Air 
Force Base, S.D., and Dyess Air Force Base, Texas, and the B-2s are 
at Whiteman Air Force Base, Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	Known officially as the Stratofortress, the B-52 is  
affectionately called the BUFF (for Big Ugly Fat Fellow) by its 
aircrews. Its wingspan of 185 feet makes it wider than it is long 
(159 feet), and it stands 40 feet high. With eight turbofan jet 
engines, it can carry 70,000 pounds of bombs, missiles and other 
weapons and fly 8,800 miles before refueling. 
</P>
<P>
	The H model of the B-52 rolled off the Boeing Co. assembly lines  
at a cost of $9 million per plane, and the first one entered 
service May 9, 1961, with the 379th Bomb Wing at Wurtsmith Air 
Force Base, Mich. Even taking decades of inflation into account, 
that is a far cry from the $2 billion it cost to field each B-2. 
</P>
<P>
	All these years later, the B-52 still carries the most diverse  
assortment of weapons in the bomber fleet. It is equipped to drop 
either nuclear or conventional munitions. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
