<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Accused of Hijacking Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Touching on a partisan sticking point in the  
education debate, Republican Gov. Ed Schafer of North Dakota 
derided President Clinton today for trying to ``hijack'' recently 
passed legislation to pay for his proposal to hire teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	In the weekly GOP radio address, Schafer praised the so-called  
ed-flex bills, which passed in both the House and Senate on 
Thursday, for increasing states' flexibility in spending federal 
education money. He said the measures recognize the distinct 
challenges each state faces in educating its children. 
</P>
<P>
	But he accused the administration of injecting partisan politics  
into the education debate. Democratic lawmakers and the president 
protested a provision in the Senate version of the bill that shifts 
to special education programs the money that was supposed to help 
pay for Clinton's new-teachers plan this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The president and his Democrat allies in the Senate should not  
have tried to hijack this important bill for his poll-driven plan 
to have the federal government pay for 100,000 new teachers in 
local schools,'' said Schafer, who is vice chairman of the 
Republican Governors Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Schafer said the goal of Clinton's proposal -- to reduce average  
class sizes to 18 pupils in early elementary grades -- is already 
being realized in some states, including his own. 
</P>
<P>
	The governor asked rhetorically whether the federal government  
would fund extra classrooms and extra support staff along with the 
teachers. ``You know the answer to that: Of course not,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He insisted that teachers and schools would prefer to have the  
money to spend on special education. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans complain that the federal government, while  
dictating the rules that states must follow on special education, 
provides only 7 percent to 12 percent of the costs of those 
programs. Current law allows the federal government to contribute a 
maximum of 40 percent of a state's special education budget. 
</P>
<P>
	``Republicans believe it is irresponsible to launch new,  
expensive federal programs without adequately funding existing 
programs first,'' Schafer said. 
</P>
<P>
	He called the administration's plan endemic of the very problem  
that the ed-flex measures try to eliminate: Washington's simplistic 
approach to education. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't take into account the day-to-day realities of how  
schools really operate,'' the North Dakota governor said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton did not immediately threaten a veto this week, but he  
said he would try to eliminate the special education funding 
provision. ``The Senate used this bill to undermine one of our most 
important educational achievements,'' he said in a statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
