<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NCAA West Regional Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- New Mexico center Kenny Thomas' final college game  
turned out to be his longest and most forgettable. 
</P>
<P>
	Mighty Connecticut and its suffocating defensive pressure held  
the 6-foot-8, 250-pound Thomas to a single free throw, a career low 
for the player who finished as the school's No. 2 scorer with 1,931 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	In four seasons, Thomas led the Lobos to 102 victories, the most  
successful four years in the program's history. But it was in the 
NCAA tournament that Thomas repeatedly came up with some of his 
worst games. 
</P>
<P>
	Going into this week's West Regional, Thomas had averaged just  
8.5 points and 6.5 rebounds in six NCAA games. Frequently in foul 
trouble, Thomas failed to come up with the kind of game that could 
have lifted his stock with NBA scouts. 
</P>
<P>
	In New Mexico's 61-59 victory over Missouri in Thursday's first  
round, Thomas finally shook the post-season slump. He had 20 
points, 10 rebounds and four blocks before fouling out late in the 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	But against Connecticut, Thomas wasn't a factor. The Huskies'  
duo of 6-foot-11 center Jake Voskuhl and 6-7, 235-pound forward 
Kevin Freeman, manhandled him inside and kept him away from the 
basket. Thomas had 11 rebounds, but was 0-for-6 shooting, including 
0-for-3 on 3-pointers. 
</P>
<P>
	Connecticut coach Jim Calhoun said the Huskies' defensive plan  
was to frustrate Thomas. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people say play him smart. We tried to play him big,''  
Calhoun said. ``If he is going to make 3-point shots, we can live 
with that. We didn't want him in the post making shots inside.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the 30 minutes he was on the floor, Thomas never got a good  
look inside, but denied later he was frustrated. 
</P>
<P>
	``They double-teamed me and I wasn't expecting it,'' he said.  
``It's UConn and playing New Mexico. I didn't think they'd 
double-team me right away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas now will wait for the NBA draft this summer. There is no  
consensus on how high he will go. At his best, he has uncommon 
quickness and a deft shooting touch for someone of his size. 
</P>
<P>
	But the pros will also look at how he struggled in the NCAA. He  
had four points and four rebounds against Kansas State his freshman 
season, eight points and three rebounds against Louisville two 
years ago and three points and five rebounds against Butler in 
1998. And finally, his nightmarish afternoon against Connecticut. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DAVIS STILL THERE:* Like a relative who comes to visit for a  
couple of days and stays two weeks, Iowa coach Tom Davis is 
determined to party as long as he can in the NCAA tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going back home, getting our sunglasses and shorts and  
do it again,'' the lame-duck Iowa coach said Saturday after the 
fifth-seeded Hawkeyes beat fourth-seeded Arkansas 82-72 to advance 
to the round of 16 next week in Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa told Davis last year his contract would not be renewed  
after this season. Davis is being forced out despite being the 
winningest coach in school history (269-139). The victory over 
Arkansas also gave him his 10th 20-win season in Iowa City. 
</P>
<P>
	After the win over Arkansas, Davis was embraced individually by  
his players. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MESSAGE TO DUKE?:* Connecticut point guard Khalid El-Amin said  
the Huskies weren't thinking of No. 1 Duke as they put away New 
Mexico in the game's first seven minutes with a 17-0 run. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we tried to send a message to them,'' El-Amin  
said after the 78-56 victory over the Lobos. ``We wanted to come 
out and play Connecticut basketball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	El-Amin did make it clear Connecticut is building momentum and  
looking forward to a possible meeting with the Blue Devils in the 
national finals. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as we play hard like this and be so aggressive on  
defense and take our shot on offense, we are one of the best teams 
in the nation,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TURNOVER TURNAROUND:* With an extended pressure defense that  
springs traps without warning, Arkansas usually thrives on 
turnovers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Razorbacks held true to form in the first half against Iowa,  
forcing 16 turnovers that led to 14 points, but the Hawkeyes turned 
the tables in the second half with their own full-court press. 
</P>
<P>
	Frazzled by the unexpected pressure, Arkansas had 12 second-half  
turnovers -- including three straight during a 16-0 Iowa run -- that 
led to 16 points for the Hawkeyes. 
</P>
<P>
	``The press did exactly for them what it had done for us in the  
first half when they jumped on us and we came back,'' Arkansas 
coach Nolan Richardson said. ``It stopped our momentum.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990313.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 01:23:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blue Devils March On </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- It didn't take Florida A&AMP;M coach Mickey  
Clayton long to figure out what some of the nation's best teams 
will have to do to knock off No. 1 Duke in the NCAA tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``You would have to bring your `A' game. You couldn't do it with  
your `B' or your `C,''' Clayton said following his team's 99-58 
loss Friday night to the top-seeded Blue Devils in the first round 
of the East Regional. 
</P>
<P>
	Like most of the regular season, the Blue Devils (33-1) left  
little drama for the second half. Duke sank 11 of its first 14 
shots en route to shooting 66 percent in the first half, and went 
on to extend its school-record winning streak to 28. 
</P>
<P>
	``They played hard. They didn't get the win, but at the same  
time I didn't think they expected to,'' Duke's Chris Burgess said 
of the Rattlers (12-19), the only team in the 64-team NCAA field 
with a losing record. ``I think they just wanted to make sure they 
had a nice experience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clayton and his players said they enjoyed Thursday's news  
conference, when they dreamed of beating the nation's most dominant 
team. Then, Friday's game unfolded. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reality of it is we got whipped. It is never fun getting a  
whipping,'' Clayton said. ``When your daddy spanked you, even if 
you did wrong, you didn't enjoy it. They handed it to us in a lot 
of different ways.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duke's only question mark for Sunday's second-round game against  
ninth-seeded Tulsa is the health of Trajan Langdon, who missed his 
third straight game with a foot injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very important we get him back. He's our emotional  
leader, he's our team leader and he's the best shooter in the 
country,'' Burgess said. 
</P>
<P>
	While the nation's longest winning streak survived the first  
round of the tournament, College of Charleston saw its 25-game 
winning streak snapped on the same court where it began -- the 
Charlotte Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	Tulsa blew most of a 26-point lead, but steadied itself in the  
final minutes and held on for a 62-53 victory over the Cougars. 
</P>
<P>
	The Golden Hurricane (23-9) turned it over on six consecutive  
possessions, helping fuel a 25-1 run by Charleston that cut the 
Cougars' deficit to 53-51 with 3:20 left before Tulsa steadied 
itself. 
</P>
<P>
	In the opener, Brandon Wharton pulled Tennessee out of its  
shooting woes with 16 second-half points in a 62-52 over Delaware. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vols will meet Southwest Missouri State in the second game  
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Fourth-seeded Tennessee (21-8) overcame a miserable offensive  
start to win its first NCAA tournament game in 16 years. The Vols 
also snapped Delaware's 13-game winning streak. 
</P>
<P>
	The game was an offensive nightmare for both clubs. Neither team  
shot better than 33 percent and they combined for 37 turnovers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Survive and advance, that's what we call it,'' Tennessee coach  
Jerry Green said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee missed 17 of its first 20 shots, but managed to win  
its first NCAA tourney game since 1983 because 13th-seeded Delaware 
shot a season-low 29.8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blue Hens (25-6) entered the postseason with 10 straight  
double-digit wins and the nation's fifth-longest winning streak, 
but couldn't handle Tennessee's athletic front line as the game 
wore on. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, there was an upset in the day's second game as the  
12th-seeded Southwest Missouri State Bears held No. 5 seed 
Wisconsin to 12 first-half points and went on to a 43-32 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Wisconsin's scoring output was the lowest by any team in a  
first- or second-round game in the history of the tournament. It 
also was the lowest output in any NCAA tourney game since the 
introduction of the shot clock in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	``Teams did a better job of defending us starting in February,''  
said Wisconsin coach Dick Bennett, whose Badgers (22-10) wound up 
with their lowest point total since 1948-49. ``I take a lion's 
share of the responsibility or not finding ways for us to play 
better and score more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The defensive gem gave Southwest Missouri State (21-10) its  
first victory ever against a Big Ten team and its first NCAA 
tournament victory since 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm upset because I felt our guards immediately took us out of  
our game plan,'' Bennett said. ``We came out and started jacking 3s 
the first four or five possessions.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
