<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Americans Claim Torture in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Security police tortured three Americans  
charged with espionage, terrorism and sabotage in Zimbabwe, their 
lawyer said Saturday during the suspects' first appearance in 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	The men, accused of being mercenaries and arms dealers, are  
missionaries for an Indianapolis-based Protestant group, defense 
attorney Jeremy Callow said. 
</P>
<P>
	The three were arrested when a hand gun carried by one of them  
activated an airport metal detector on Sunday. The men were 
attempting to board a flight to the United States via Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	Zimbabwe police said -- and Callow admitted in court -- that the  
Americans owned a truck found the same day at the airport. The 
vehicle contained assault and sniper rifles, shotguns, a light 
machine gun, hand guns, firearms, telescopic sights, knives, 
camouflage cream, two-way radios and ammunition. 
</P>
<P>
	Callow claimed police beat the men and applied electric shocks  
to their genitals last week while they were in custody, the 
state-run news agency Ziana reported. 
</P>
<P>
	A judge granted Callow's request for a physical examination and  
a private physician for John Lamonte Dixon, 39, Gary George 
Blanchard, 34, and Joseph Wendell Pettyjohn, 35, all of 
Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	Magistrate Alpheus Chitakunya also ordered prison staff to  
ensure that any further police interrogation take place in the 
presence of their lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	But Chitakunya turned down a bail request and ordered the men  
held until March 26. They face life imprisonment if they are 
convicted on the weapons charges alone. 
</P>
<P>
	Looking disheveled but alert, the suspects shuffled into court  
with their feet in leg irons and shackled to plain clothes 
policemen. 
</P>
<P>
	In a quick interview with journalists, Blanchard indicated that  
security police had hurt him. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are walking a bit better now than we were,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	State prosecutor John Musakwa told the court that a diagram of  
Zimbabwe's presidential offices -- across the road from President 
Robert Mugabe's official residence -- was also found in the 
suspects' truck. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are mercenaries belonging to a group called Harvest Field  
Ministries of USA,'' said Musakwa. 
</P>
<P>
	Mercenaries in Africa often pose as missionaries in order to  
mask arms shipments and travel unhindered. 
</P>
<P>
	Musakwa said the men arrived in Harare by truck from Congo last  
week, where Zimbabwe is supporting Congolese President Laurent 
Kabila with troops and weapons in an eight-month old civil war. The 
men had been flying in and out of Zimbabwe since 1997, when they 
arranged for arms to be shipped to Congo via Tanzania, Musakwa 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspects provided a phone number for the Indianapolis  
organization, based in the home of Jonathon Wallace, who identified 
himself as the president of the group, Harvest Field Ministries. 
</P>
<P>
	Wallace said the men worked for his organization, which he  
described as an independent Protestant missionary group. 
</P>
<P>
	``We help the poor. We were drilling wells in the Congo to help  
the people,'' Wallace said, adding that Pettyjohn is his 
son-in-law. He said the weapons were for hunting and the camouflage 
cream was for paintball war games. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the missionaries had distributed seeds, clothing,  
medicine, Bibles and other books in Congo. He denied his group had 
anything to do with weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	``Them charges are so ridiculous it's unbelievable,'' Wallace  
said. ``They had just went over to pay all of our bills there in 
the Congo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wallace expressed disappointment with the U.S. Embassy in  
Harare: ``The embassy is kind of standing back. I don't understand 
why they haven't pursued more in this matter. Is someone going to 
address the beatings and these men's lives?'' 
</P>
<P>
	No U.S. diplomats were in court Saturday and the U.S. Embassy  
has denied the men were connected to the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
