<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexico City's mayor, an icon to the nation's  
left, says he will launch a third bid for the presidency by running 
in the 2000 elections, according to an interview published 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am ready for the presidential candidacy,'' Cuauhtemoc  
Cardenas was quoted as saying in the daily Reforma. 
</P>
<P>
	He also repeated a proposal that Mexico's opposition parties  
form an alliance to topple the Institutional Revolutionary Party, 
which has ruled Mexico for 60 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Cardenas is the dominant figure of his Democratic Revolution  
Party and one of Mexico's most respected -- if not always successful 
-- politicians. 
</P>
<P>
	The son of revered President Lazaro Cardenas, who served in the  
1930s, Cardenas lost a fraud-marred presidential election in 1988 
and finished third in 1994. In 1997, he became the first elected 
mayor of Mexico City in about 60 years. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Federal officials have found 17 paintings  
owned by a noted writer whose death is surrounded by mystery, the 
attorney general's office said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The find may lift some of the confusion surrounding the death of  
writer and dancer Nelly Campobello. 
</P>
<P>
	Campobello was rarely seen in the years before her death.  
Eventually, Mexican intellectuals persuaded the government to look 
into her whereabouts. 
</P>
<P>
	In February, a judge ordered a suspect held for trial on charges  
he kept Campobello captive for years. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a death certificate that the suspect, Claudio  
Fuentes, signed as a witness, Campobello died of a heart ailment at 
the age of 86 in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	When police exhumed her grave, they found three bodies.  
Investigators say one of the bodies matches Campobello's 
description, but the other two remain unidentified. 
</P>
<P>
	The attorney general's office said it uncovered 17 missing  
paintings belonging to Campobello, including works by Jose Clemente 
Orozco and Carlos Merida, at a house in Mexico City on Wednesday. 
It gave no further details. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Federal officials said Saturday they have  
seized more than 25,000 counterfeit recordings from street markets 
in the northern state of Coahuila. 
</P>
<P>
	In a news release, the federal attorney general's office said it  
had seized 24,697 audio tapes, 552 videocassettes and 340 compact 
discs during raids. 
</P>
<P>
	It said there were no arrests.  
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials have long pressed Mexico to crackdown on  
widespread counterfeiting of music and video recordings, as well as 
of computer software. 
</P>
<P>
	Street stalls throughout the country openly sell obviously  
counterfeited works, and many computer dealers offer unlicensed 
software with their computers. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES (AP) -- Argentina's opposition coalition called  
Saturday for a referendum on the whether the country's president 
could run for a third consecutive term. 
</P>
<P>
	Carlos Alvarez, a spokesman for the Alliance coalition, did not  
propose a date for the vote, but said he wanted it to be held 
within three months. 
</P>
<P>
	The Alliance and other opposition parties held a forum Friday to  
find ways to block President Carlos Menem from trying to seek 
re-election Oct. 24. Menem has hinted that he might be interested 
in seeking a third term if his supporters could find a legal way 
for him to run. 
</P>
<P>
	Argentina's constitution does not allow presidents to serve  
three consecutive terms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
