<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Releases Audit of Bell Cos. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Communications Commission released  
an audit of the five regional Bell telephone companies Friday 
reporting that $5 billion in equipment can't be accounted for. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bells contend the audit, conducted in 1997, is flawed and  
overestimates missing equipment. FCC auditors have disputed this 
but one commissioner raised questions about the accuracy of the 
process. 
</P>
<P>
	Audit results, the Bells say, won't affect rates directly. But  
consumer groups, AT&AMP;T and MCI WorldCom are already using the audit 
to press for lower local and long-distance rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC intends to seek public comments on the audit, its  
ramifications and what action, if any, the commission should take. 
FCC staff recommended, however, that the Bells be required to take 
write-offs and making accounting corrections. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the FCC agreed to release the audit, but the results  
-- covering hundreds of pages -- did not come out until late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The staff report recommends, for example, that BellSouth write  
off $430 million in equipment. BellSouth said the recommendation is 
inappropriate because many items the FCC auditors claim don't exist 
in fact do exist. It also said a write-off wouldn't affect rates. 
</P>
<P>
	FCC Commissioner Harold Furchtgott-Roth also said there appeared  
to be problems with the audit's methodology. ``I believe that this 
agency and its commissioners may never be capable of judging the 
accuracy and authenticity of the current set of audit results,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	And, he raised concerns that the auditors may have turned a  
``blind eye'' to equipment they classified as missing but was 
subsequently found by telephone companies. 
</P>
<P>
	But Commissioner Gloria Tristani said the FCC's staff ``has been  
very thorough and careful in performing these audits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	BellSouth said: ``While we dispute the methodology and the  
results of the FCC's audit, it must be understood that the accuracy 
of records of our equipment inventory has no impact on our rates. 
None.'' 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T said the audit results could have serious implications for  
consumers. ``The Bell companies use their self-reported investments 
in various regulatory contexts to justify higher rates,'' AT&AMP;T 
said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
