<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NCAA Tournament Ratings Dip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- With fewer buzzer-beaters and a lack of  
competitive games, CBS' ratings have slipped for the first two days 
of the NCAA tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS averaged averaged a 4.7 preliminary national rating in the  
two-day period, down 2 percent from last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The network's coverage of Friday's four games posted a 4.8  
rating and a 12 share, which was even from the second day of last 
year's tournament. But on Thursday, it had a 4.7/12 mark -- down 2 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the reasons for Thursday's dropoff was that much of the  
East coast was asleep when North Carolina and UCLA were upset late 
that night. 
</P>
<P>
	Another was the abundance of blowouts. Only eight of the 32  
first-round matchups were decided by fewer than five points. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the tournament numbers may be down, CBS' final regular  
season ratings were up 5 percent from last season -- the first time 
in six years its numbers haven't decreased. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anytime you're up in today's world, you're ahead of the  
game,'' said CBS Sports President Sean McManus. ``There's so much 
college basketball on, thousands of games, and so many different 
places to watch games that it makes it difficult.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The network averaged a 2.1/5 in a year in which the college game  
didn't have to go up against the NBA for much of the season because 
of the lockout. CBS posted a 2.0/5 last year. 
</P>
<P>
	ESPN also capitalized on the NBA lockout, with a rating increase  
of 13 percent on its primary channel and an 8 percent increase on 
ESPN2. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC's ratings dropped 6 percent from a 1.8 to a 1.7.  
</P>
<P>
	The rating is the percentage of TV households in the nation  
tuned to a program, and each point represents 994,000 homes. The 
share is the percentage tuned to a program among those televisions 
on at the time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
