<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 18:11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Several NHL Stars Out With Injuries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	When the Washington Capitals had injuries to key players earlier  
this season, general manager George McPhee joked that he had an 
all-star team in the press box. 
</P>
<P>
	Now many other NHL teams know exactly how he felt. There are  
several all-stars sidelined by injury, including forwards Wayne 
Gretzky, Mark Messier, Brett Hull, Theo Fleury and Pavel Bure. 
</P>
<P>
	Big-name goaltenders haven't been spared, either. Dominik Hasek,  
Tom Barrasso and Grant Fuhr all have missed lengthy periods with 
injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	Want to talk all-star defensemen? How about Kevin Hatcher?  
</P>
<P>
	``We lost very good players and it's a big loss,'' said  
Pittsburgh's Jaromir Jagr, referring to Barrasso, Hatcher and 
defenseman Darius Kasparaitis. ``We have to battle through this and 
start winning again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barrasso has a broken hand, Hatcher a broken foot and  
Kasparaitis a knee strain, and none is expected to be back soon. 
Without them, the Penguins recently had a six-game losing streak. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek's absence from the Buffalo lineup also has had a negative  
effect on the Sabres. In 10 games without the league's two-time 
MVP, the Sabres were 3-4-3 before Saturday's game against Boston. 
Hasek has been out with a strained groin since Feb. 17 and is in a 
day-to-day situation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres are in no hurry to rush him back, fearing further  
injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the type of injury that can keep you on the sidelines for  
a while, so he's doing the right thing staying out,'' Sabres 
captain Mike Peca said. ``We're getting close to the playoffs. 
That's where we want him to be 100 percent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Florida Panthers don't have that luxury. In a five-team  
fight for a playoff berth in the Eastern Conference, the Panthers 
need Bure now. 
</P>
<P>
	But Bure has a torn cartilage in his right knee and is expected  
to be out two to three weeks. Bure, acquired in a blockbuster trade 
with Vancouver this season, had 13 goals in 11 games with the 
Panthers. 
</P>
<P>
	Fuhr returned to the Blues' lineup on Saturday after missing 16  
games because of arthroscopic surgery on his right knee, and won 
his 100th game for St. Louis in a 6-4 victory over Edmonton. His 
absence had thrown the Blues' goaltending situation into disarray. 
St. Louis has used a total of five goaltenders so far, and has been 
struggling as the NHL heads into the final weeks of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vancouver Canucks weren't an NHL power when Messier went  
down with a knee injury Feb. 11. But his absence hasn't helped the 
Canucks. There's still no word when he'll be back. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss of a star player hasn't hurt everyone.  
</P>
<P>
	The Colorado Avalanche haven't missed a beat with Fleury  
sidelined by a sprained right knee and the Dallas Stars' depth has 
overcome the loss of Hull to a hamstring injury and defenseman 
Darryl Sydor to a knee sprain. 
</P>
<P>
	In some cases, teams played better in the immediate aftermath of  
a star's absence as other players picked up their games to 
compensate. Such a team was the New York Rangers, who went 5-0-1 
right after Gretzky was sidelined by a neck injury Feb. 26. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Rangers have since lost two straight.  
</P>
<P>
	``When you are missing a star player (it is tough) because  
they're the key,'' Ottawa coach Jacques Martin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
