<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Thanks His Defenders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- It's payback time for the president's  
defenders. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton, careful to express contrition and avoid  
gloating after his acquittal in the Senate impeachment trial, began 
this weekend to publicly show his gratitude to those who stood up 
for him throughout the impeachment process. 
</P>
<P>
	In remarks at a pair of fund-raisers for Democratic Rep. Max  
Sandlin in Texarkana, Texas, on Friday, Clinton directly linked his 
appearance to Sandlin's support when the House voted to impeach a 
president for the first time in 130 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``At a time in the last year when a lot of people were just  
worried which way the political winds were blowing, that guy was 
telling people to read the Constitution of the United States of 
America,'' he told a $1,000-a-plate dinner for Sandlin. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday night, Clinton was the featured guest at an Arkansas  
state Democratic party salute to Dale Bumpers, who delivered the 
defense summation to the Senate impeachment trial. 
</P>
<P>
	He mentioned that they had been through ``all kinds of  
adversity'' together, and saluted Bumpers for never forgetting 
``the lessons of the past, beginning with the Constitution'' during 
his long Senate career. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also presented Bumpers as the antithesis of the kind of  
politician who relies on personal attacks to further his career, 
saying that ``all the complexities, and all of the problems I've 
faced'' in politics might have vanished if egos had been set aside. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ninety percent of them would go away tomorrow if people could  
just understand that they don't have to define their lives in terms 
of putting someone else down, defeating someone else, thinking 
they're better than someone else, ignoring their common humanity,'' 
Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	At a $200,000 Democratic National Committee reception prior to  
the Bumpers event, Clinton found himself in the company of folks 
whose confidence in him was never shaken. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's done a wonderful job,'' said Mary Ann Bowman, who  
made no secret of her distaste for Independent Counsel Kenneth 
Starr's $40 million investigation of Clinton. ``To spend the money 
they spent is absolutely ridiculous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton spent Saturday afternoon at the home of his  
mother-in-law, Dorothy Rodham, watching Arkansas fall to Iowa in 
the NCAA tournament. First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton remained in 
Washington, where she had been nursing a bad back. 
</P>
<P>
	Sandlin, first elected to Congress in 1996, had been asking  
Clinton for two years to attend a fund-raiser, a Sandlin aide said. 
The cocktail reception and dinner raised more than a half-million 
dollars to help Sandlin pay some $700,000 in campaign debts. 
</P>
<P>
	Without directly referring to the Monica Lewinsky scandal, or  
even saying ``impeachment,'' Clinton cast Sandlin's opposition to 
the House charges as a stand ``to protect the kind of government 
that we have preserved for more than 220 years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Even though he is a very junior member,'' Clinton said, ``he  
was one of the most serious, substantive, thoughtful and effective 
advocates, asking all the members of the Congress to read the 
Constitution, read the history, and uphold their oath.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After a Democratic National Committee reception in Little Rock  
on Saturday, Clinton was the featured guest at a $200,000 state 
party fund-raiser in honor of Bumpers. 
</P>
<P>
	Bumpers, who retired after the previous session of Congress,  
delivered a widely praised speech to the Senate that was part 
constitutional analysis, part collegial appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	He told senators weighing the president's fate in February that  
Clinton was guilty of a ``terrible moral lapse,'' but he insisted 
that Clinton's conduct did not warrant removal from office. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can censure Bill Clinton. You can hand him over to  
prosecutors. But you cannot convict,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Though he and Clinton have long known each other, the two men  
were never considered extremely close. During his first 
presidential term, Clinton went to then Sen. David Pryor, another 
now-retired Arkansas Democrat, when he wanted advice on Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	In his first Senate primary in 1974, Bumpers defeated Clinton's  
mentor, Sen. William Fulbright. Like Clinton, Bumpers is a former 
Arkansas governor. 
</P>
<P>
	His remarks to the Senate also excoriated House prosecutors for  
insensitivity to the Clinton family, which he said ``has already 
been about as decimated as a family can get.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
