<DOCNO> APW19990313.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 11:11:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Espy Criticizes Independent Counsel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy, whose  
run-in with an independent counsel cost him $1.5 million in legal 
bills, says his experience casts doubt on the whole institution. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's almost like someone would put out a want ad for  
independent counsels: good pay, good benefits ... good judgment is 
not required,'' Espy said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Espy, President Clinton's first Agriculture Secretary, was  
acquitted in December on 30 charges that he accepted gifts and 
entertainment from companies or organizations regulated by the 
agency. He was forced to resign in 1994 after an independent 
counsel was appointed to investigate him. 
</P>
<P>
	Now a private attorney in Jackson, Miss., Espy was one of  
several speakers on a panel examining the fate of the independent 
counsel law, which will expire June 30 unless Congress and the 
president approve its reauthorization. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers from both parties have said they see almost no chance  
for survival of the Independent Counsel Act, although some House 
Republicans have floated the idea of having an assistant attorney 
general handle investigations of high-level government officials. 
Congress is scheduled to hold hearings in the coming weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Espy said he would be willing to testify about the matter on  
Capitol Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	The former secretary described his 4 1/2-year investigation by  
independent prosecutor Donald Smaltz as one with ``high tangible 
costs, high intangible costs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Espy said he owes $1.5 million in legal bills and is trying to  
recover professionally. 
</P>
<P>
	Joseph diGenova, a former independent counsel who conducted a  
3-year, $2.8 million investigation into the State Department's 1992 
search of Bill Clinton's passport file, agreed that changes are 
needed. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a long distance between Mike Espy and Richard Nixon.  
Having a statute that doesn't differentiate is a dumb idea,'' he 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990313.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 14:42:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NCAA East Regional Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- To many people, asking your father to be  
your employee might seem strange. To Steve and Sam Alford, it made 
all the sense in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	When Tennessee's Volunteers play Southwest Missouri State in  
Sunday's East Regional second-round game, one of the attractions 
will be the Bears' coaching staff. Steve Alford is the head coach 
and his father, Sam, is one of his assistants. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a head coach, you always want someone covering your back.  
If you can't appreciate or think your father's going to do that, 
nobody will do it,'' the younger Alford said. ``It's just a great 
opportunity. We had always thought about coaching together. We 
probably thought it would be a different role reversal. But it's 
been a lot of fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After Steve got the Southwest Missouri State job four years ago,  
one of the first things he did was call his father, who was just 
finishing his 20th season as the head coach at Chrysler High School 
in New Castle, Ind. 
</P>
<P>
	``He kind of caught me by surprise,'' said the elder Alford, 56,  
whose Chrysler teams went 300-188 and won sectional titles in each 
of his last six seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Sam said he and his son have always been close, and their  
relationship blossomed when Steve was a high school sophomore and 
the two began traveling the state to conduct basketball clinics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would do the talking and he would do the demonstrating,''  
Sam said. ``Then, slowly, as his name grew and he took off, he 
started doing the talking and the demonstrating, and it was very 
evident that he was very good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After Alford led Indiana to the 1987 NCAA championship and spent  
four years playing in the NBA, he went into coaching, a move that 
produced immediate success at Division III Manchester. By the time 
Southwest Missouri State called in 1995, Alford had a trump card he 
could use on his father. 
</P>
<P>
	``He knew that if he wanted to be around his grand kids,it was  
probably going to be hard to do it from New Castle,'' Steve said. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *O'NEILL'S LEGACY:* Jerry Green is in just his second season  
coaching Tennessee, and he has a team made up mostly of players 
recruited by Kevin O'Neill, who is currently coaching at 
Northwestern. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though O'Neill is no longer with the Vols, his former  
players still remember him, especially when they're asked about how 
he recruited them. 
</P>
<P>
	Guard Tony Harris said O'Neill sent him ``about 1,000'' letters  
and postcards. Some of them were signed in jest by the likes of 
Abraham Lincoln and Tyra Banks, and all of them told Harris that 
the Vols really needed him to play for Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	Fellow guard Brandon Wharton recalled a similar experience.  
</P>
<P>
	``He made you feel like you were the only person he was  
recruiting,'' Wharton said. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *HORROR FLICK:* Tulsa coach Bill Self spent some time Saturday  
reviewing tape of the Golden Hurricane's first-round victory over 
the College of Charleston on Friday night, and he didn't like what 
he saw. 
</P>
<P>
	The Golden Hurricane's 26-point lead was cut to two in the  
closing minutes before Tulsa steadied itself and regrouped in the 
final seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	``That right there was really borderline nightmarish material,''  
Self said. ``We could have been talked about for a really long time 
if we would have squandered that lead.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *LARGER THAN LIFE:* Duke sophomore forward Shane Battier  
admitted to being more than a little overwhelmed when Mike 
Krzyzewski began recruiting him. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a pretty mind-blowing experience,'' Battier said. ``I  
mean, here was this man who has a video game named after him, and 
he's calling my house and he wants me to play for him. It took me a 
while to get over that.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
