<DOCNO> APW19990313.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 03:23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Members Escape With Warnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The IOC's chief investigator knows there's a  
fine line between action that gets a member kicked out of the club 
and action that brings a heavy slap on the wrist. 
</P>
<P>
	Sounding at times like an umpire explaining his strike zone,  
International Olympic Committee vice president Dick Pound defended 
the latest recommendations from his internal investigation of the 
Olympics' worst scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	The six-member panel recommended stern warnings for two IOC  
leaders, executive committee member Kim Un-yong of South Korea and 
Phil Coles, who helped win the 2000 Summer Games for Sydney. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no regulation about `severe censure' in the IOC  
charter. I understand I will get a very serious warning,'' Kim told 
The Associated Press before leaving for a special IOC general 
assembly in Lausanne, Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unless they provoke me further, I am not going to fight the  
warning,'' Kim added. ``I am, have always been, committed to IOC 
work. I will continue to work with the Olympic family to promote 
the Olympic goals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It gave lesser rebukes to seven others, including former IOC  
vice president Vitaly Smirnov of Russia, and cleared three members 
implicated in the million-dollar gifts-and-favors scheme that Salt 
Lake City waged as it won the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel's only recommendation for expulsion in the latest  
batch of cases was saved for a minor member from the South Pacific 
island of Samoa. 
</P>
<P>
	Seiuli Paul Wallwork, an IOC member since 1987 but never a  
member of the leadership, was targeted for ouster because of a 
$30,000 loan his wife received from Salt Lake's top bidder, which 
was later paid in full. Wallwork denied knowing about the loan. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC leaders said for several weeks that the latest batch of  
alleged infractions were minor compared with the earlier ones, in 
which nine members were expelled or resigned. 
</P>
<P>
	But big money -- and big names -- are still involved, and Pound  
had to repeatedly defend the report against charges of whitewash. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a judgment call,'' the Montreal lawyer said.  
</P>
<P>
	He said his panel tried to distinguish between members who  
sought to enrich themselves and those ``who were careless about 
what they should do and not attentive to what people might think.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report accused Kim and Coles of serious conflicts of  
interest or lapses in judgment. 
</P>
<P>
	It warned that they could be expelled if misconduct recurred.  
And Pound said he suspected that there was evidence, yet uncovered, 
that would call for Kim's ouster. 
</P>
<P>
	``The commission believes there is additional evidence still out  
there,'' Pound said. He added, however, that it was time to close 
the file and get ready for the IOC's watershed session in 
Switzerland next Wednesday and Thursday, changes stemming from the 
Salt Lake scandal will be debated. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has always been a work in progress,'' he said. ``There  
are times when you have to take a photograph and make a report.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kim, president of both the international Taekwondo federation  
and the confederation of Olympic sports bodies, allegedly used his 
Olympic position to help land lucrative jobs in telecommunications 
and music for his two children -- daughter Kim Hae-jung, a concert 
pianist, and son Kim Jung-hoon, a satellite TV executive also known 
as John Kim. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC commission concluded its work on allegations involving  
concert dates and recording contracts for Kim Hae-jung, which it 
said ``created at least a very serious appearance of conflict of 
interest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the investigation remained open on allegations that Kim  
Un-yong knew that Salt Lake City bidders helped pay for a job for 
his son at Keystone Communications in Utah. 
</P>
<P>
	It said it was ``highly unlikely'' that Kim Un-yong did not know  
of the arrangement, although ``evidence available as of this day is 
not entirely conclusive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Should the allegations be fully established, which is not the  
case, the commission would consider that such behavior by an IOC 
member would justify expulsion from the IOC,'' the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim, in a statement released by his New York-based publicist,  
said he was ``carefully reviewing the report, and I look forward to 
continuing to work with my colleagues in the IOC and the Olympic 
family toward advancing the goals of the Olympic movement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coles, one of the best-liked members of the clubby IOC, was  
accused of accepting some $60,000 in travel benefits from Salt Lake 
bidders, including trips to ski resorts and the Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	His case was similar to that of Agustin Arroyo, the IOC member  
from Ecuador who has been ousted, but Pound said there were 
differences that made Coles' case less severe, most notably the 
fact that the Australian was legitimately in the United States when 
the Salt Lake City-paid travel began. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Pound said, ``alarm bells'' should have sounded for Coles  
when offers of trips kept coming. 
</P>
<P>
	``At least a warning light should have gone off in his head,''  
the investigator said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wallwork's wife, Julia, borrowed the money from Tom Welch, the  
former head of Salt Lake's Olympic efforts. A Salt Lake ethics 
report said Welch had to withdraw the money from his children's 
trust funds, and the loan was repaid. 
</P>
<P>
	Wallwork told the IOC that he knew nothing about the loan and  
that he and his wife were separated at the time. But the Pound 
commission said faxes about the loan were sent from Welch to 
Wallwork's office, and that the Wallwork family received $67,585 in 
travel benefits from Salt Lake bidders. 
</P>
<P>
	Pound said his commission found nothing to call for more  
expulsions in the responses from 37 cities that bid for the games 
from 1996 onward. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said all of that information should be turned over to a  
standing ethics panel, part of the reform package due for adoption 
next week. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that panel might also consider the case of Anita  
DeFrantz, a vice president from the United States. While DeFrantz 
has repeatedly denied any knowledge of wrongdoing, reports this 
week quoted Welch and former Salt Lake Olympic vice president Dave 
Johnson as saying they discussed everything about the gift program 
with her. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have always said that if there are facts to back up the  
allegations, we will look at it,'' Pound said. ``But so far, she 
says she did not know. We'll give the benefit of the doubt to Anita 
at this time.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
