<DOCNO> APW19990313.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 13:51:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP, Dems To Lock Up on Medicare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton and Republicans have rival  
plans for shoring up Social Security and Medicare. But, like 
opposing armies mired in their trenches, each is on the defensive, 
far from a historic agreement to overhaul the massive entitlement 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Factor in their long-running suspicions and animosity --  
exacerbated by the president's impeachment and trial -- and the 
prospects for a year of political positioning far outweigh the 
chances for a dramatic deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``It always was a long shot'' for Social Security or Medicare  
reform in 1999, says Robert Reischauer, a former Congressional 
Budget Office director who now is a senior fellow with the 
liberal-leaning Brookings Institution. 
</P>
<P>
	At stake is the future of two of the government's most popular  
programs. Social Security provides pensions to 45 million mostly 
elderly and disabled Americans, while Medicare supplies health 
insurance for 39 million elderly and disabled people. The impending 
retirement of the baby boomers, beginning in a decade, threatens 
both. 
</P>
<P>
	Medicare already is spending more money each year than it  
collects in revenue. Its trust fund financing hospital coverage is 
projected for insolvency by 2008. 
</P>
<P>
	Social Security will begin spending more than it collects in  
2013. Its trust would be depleted by 2032. 
</P>
<P>
	The bankruptcy of either fund is politically unthinkable. The  
question is not whether something will happen, but what and when. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and Republicans talk about fixing both programs by using  
the large projected federal surpluses, without the cuts in benefits 
or tax increases many analysts say are needed. 
</P>
<P>
	Their solutions are painless approaches to very real problems,  
designed to let each side claim it is protecting Social Security 
and Medicare. Yet the very act of offering pain-free prescriptions 
makes it harder for each side to swallow the more onerous medicine 
that is probably inevitable. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has proposed using $2.8 trillion in expected federal  
surpluses over the next 15 years to reduce the national debt. That 
would strengthen the economy, thus making it easier for the 
government to generate revenue to pay benefits to future retirees. 
</P>
<P>
	He also would put an equal amount of Treasury bonds into the  
Social Security trust fund. The president says that would ensure 
payment of benefits; Republicans contend it amounts to 
double-counting. 
</P>
<P>
	By investing some of the money in financial markets, Clinton  
says his plan would keep Social Security solvent until 2055. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans have pledged to use the $1.8 trillion in projected  
Social Security surpluses over the next decade only to reduce the 
debt, or for any Social Security or Medicare reforms that are 
enacted. 
</P>
<P>
	But they have not said how they would extend the life of either  
program. Behind the scenes, Reps. Bill Archer, R-Texas, and Clay 
Shaw, R-Fla., are writing a plan to create federally subsidized 
personal retirement accounts for Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been secret contacts between emissaries of both sides  
-- White House economic adviser Gene Sperling and Kenneth Kies, a 
former top aide to Archer, the House Ways and Means Committee 
chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	But congressional Democrats, worried about a Social Security  
overhaul that might reduce benefits and deprive them of a potent 
campaign issue, are unhappy. Some say those contacts have 
diminished. 
</P>
<P>
	All of that leaves little prospect for major progress.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to take an act of courage on the part of the  
president to keep the ball moving forward,'' Reischauer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Why the president? Because it is easier for Clinton to craft a  
proposal than for Congress' 277 Republicans to agree on one. And 
because ever since Democrats attacked Republicans in the 1980s for 
considering trimming Social Security benefits -- which may have won 
Democrats the Senate in 1986 -- GOP lawmakers have been wary. 
</P>
<P>
	Their wariness has been sharpened by years of losing budget  
battles with Clinton, and by the bitterness the recently ended 
impeachment fight engendered. Recent comments by GOP leaders 
underline how low their level of trust is. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked how Republicans count on avoiding another year-end budget  
clash this year with the White House, House Majority Whip Tom 
DeLay, R-Texas, said, ``You can't with this administration. They're 
shameless. If you could deal with somebody you could count on'' it 
would be different. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., in a brief  
interview, said of Clinton: ``I can't determine if he's serious or 
not about working with us.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
