<DOCNO> APW19990313.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 05:42:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Loses CIA Confirmation Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Chilean resident who wanted the CIA to  
confirm that he once worked as a ``covert employee'' lost his 
appeal Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	A three-member panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for  
the District of Columbia affirmed a lower court's decision to throw 
out a lawsuit filed by Eduardo Frugone, who contended he worked for 
the CIA for 15 years. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1990, Frugone tried to obtain retirement benefits from the  
Office of Personnel Management, which oversees federal health 
benefits. That office suggested Frugone contact the CIA because the 
agency had all of his records. 
</P>
<P>
	He did. Frugone then received a letter from the Office of  
Independent Contractor Programs telling him that he had not paid 
enough Social Security taxes to make him eligible for benefits. The 
letter did not identify the job Frugone had worked. 
</P>
<P>
	Furgone then asked the CIA to turn over his records under the  
Freedom of Information Act. When the CIA told him it could not 
respond within the 10-day period required by law, Furgone sued. The 
agency formally denied his request a short time later. 
</P>
<P>
	In the CIA's summary judgment request to a lower district court,  
the agency claimed it could refuse to confirm or deny Frugone's 
employment because the FOIA does not apply to matters kept secret 
by executive order because of national security or foreign policy. 
</P>
<P>
	The lower court agreed and threw out the lawsuit. Frugone  
appealed. 
</P>
<P>
	However, he narrowed his appeals claim to seek only employment  
information from the CIA and his personnel file. 
</P>
<P>
	Frugone claimed that because the Office of Personnel Management  
acknowledges the existence of his relationship with the CIA, the 
CIA must as well. The federal appellate panel disagreed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
