<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 11:11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thompson Sick of Being 'Good Girl' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Lea Thompson is sick of being seen as a  
goody-goody. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's frustrating for me artistically because it's easy for  
people -- critics or whoever -- to dismiss me as a nice girl,'' 
Thompson says in the April issue of Redbook. ``That makes me angry. 
Just because you're nice and you're not tearing up the town, dating 
all kinds of people and trying to destroy yourself, doesn't mean 
your work doesn't have depth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 37-year-old star of ``Caroline in the City'' and longtime  
husband Howard Deutch, her director for ``Some Kind of Wonderful,'' 
have two children. Growing up with a less-than-perfect mother made 
her want to lavish extra attention on her kids. 
</P>
<P>
	``My mother really fought a battle with alcoholism,'' Thompson  
says. ``She finally quit when I was about 8.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Being the child of an alcoholic fostered independence at an  
early age, and some hard feelings. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't remember my mother ever driving me to school or to my  
dance class or whatever,'' she says. ``I resented that she wasn't 
Donna Reed.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
