<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 03:23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Korean IOC Member Discusses Penalty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The highest-ranking official  
implicated in the Olympic scandal said today he would not contest a 
serious warning about his conduct recommended by International 
Olympic Committee investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim Un-yong, a powerful IOC executive board member from South  
Korea, barely escaped expulsion when IOC investigators recommended 
Friday that he be severely censured. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no regulation about `severe censure' in the IOC  
charter. I understand I will get a very serious warning,'' Kim told 
The Associated Press before leaving for a special IOC general 
assembly in Lausanne, Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unless they provoke me further, I am not going to fight the  
warning,'' Kim added. ``I am, have always been, committed to IOC 
work. I will continue to work with the Olympic family to promote 
the Olympic goals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, investigators of the Olympic bribery scandal  
recommended that Seiuli Paul Wallwork, an IOC delegate from Western 
Samoa, be thrown off the IOC. 
</P>
<P>
	They said they recommended that Kim and Phil Coles, a longtime  
IOC member from Australia, be censured. Seven others, including 
Vitaly Smirnov, a former IOC vice president from Russia, will 
receive warnings. 
</P>
<P>
	While the panel issued a recommendation on Kim, his case  
remained open and could lead to a recommendation for expulsion, the 
report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim is president of both the International Taekwondo Federation  
and the Confederation of Olympic Sports Bodies, and had been 
considered a possible successor to IOC president Juan Antonio 
Samaranch. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990313.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 07:32:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Athletes: Don't Blame Us </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	From running tracks to balance beams, Olympic athletes make it  
clear: 
</P>
<P>
	This scandal is not about us!  
</P>
<P>
	While they say they're shocked and saddened by accusations that  
Salt Lake bribes fattened IOC members by millions of dollars, the 
men and women who compete for medals insist the games still shine. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we should let it hang over the Olympics,'' said  
Shannon Miller, who's won more Olympic and world-championship 
medals than any other U.S. gymnast. ``The Olympics is still about 
the athletes and competing with other nations and doing your best. 
It's still about that, no matter what happens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No athletes have been implicated in the half-dozen  
investigations into the case, in which leaders of the Utah bid for 
the 2002 Winter Games are accused of using cash, travel and medical 
expenses, gifts and other lavish inducements to try to win the 
votes of IOC members. 
</P>
<P>
	And officials of the International Olympic Committee, the U.S.  
Olympic Committee and the Salt Lake Organizing Committee all have 
pledged that athletes would not suffer as a result of any backlash 
from the scandal, such as sponsor pullouts or revenue shortfalls. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must return the games and the attention to the athletes,  
the most important members of the Olympic family,'' USOC president 
Bill Hybl said. ``It is their dreams that we must make possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Tewksbury, a 1992 swimming gold medalist from Canada,  
returned his medal to the IOC because he said he was ashamed about 
the scandal. But his reaction was unique, and athletes generally 
have taken a low profile as their sports' leaders search for 
culprits and reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	Surveys have found that public support for the Olympics, and  
especially Olympic competitors, remains extremely high despite the 
alleged wrongdoing among the leadership in limousines and hotel 
suites. 
</P>
<P>
	The athletes say that's the way it should be.  
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing can tarnish my medals,'' said Amy Van Dyken, who won a  
record four golds for swimming for the United States in the 1996 
Atlanta Games. ``The Olympics are such a pure thing. You are there 
for your country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What happened in Salt Lake and other Olympic bid cities was not  
so pure, and the idea that the rings could be damaged and the flame 
snuffed out by greed makes the athletes mad. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let me emphasize that athletes did not have a damn thing to do  
with this whole mess,'' said Willie Davenport, a hurdler and 
bobsledder on five U.S. Olympic teams. ``It's the people in the 
high chairs who did it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Naber, a four-time Olympic champion swimmer and now  
president of U.S. Olympians, an alumni group, said the athletes 
were concerned with fair play, whether on the field or in the 
boardroom. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not a win-at-any-cost philosophy, the athletes only want to  
win when they're entitled to win,'' he said. ``Consequently, 
something like this strikes at the very core of the athlete's 
being.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, a member of the gold-medal women's gymnastics team at  
Atlanta, said she probably has not paid as much attention to news 
of the scandal as she should, ``but when you've worked your whole 
life for something, you hate to think about it like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most Olympians don't know the difference between the IOC, the  
USOC and the various federations and organizing committees who put 
on the games, nor do they care to, Naber said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're just concentrating, working their sport to the best of  
their ability,'' he said. ``Yet they are stakeholders in this 
debacle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackie Joyner-Kersee, who won three golds and six medals overall  
as one of the most-storied track stars in Olympic history, said 
athletes can understand the crisis because they face something 
similar every time they compete. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just like dealing with drug testing,'' she said. ``You're  
guilty until the results come back clean.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kurt Thomas, a world champion gymnast and two-time Olympian who  
now works for Dallas' bid for the 2012 Games, said the scandal 
already had changed the public's perception. 
</P>
<P>
	``That clean, fresh image of the Olympics and bringing the games  
here has been tainted,'' he said. ``Let's face it, you hear the 
jokes on the radio. (The scandal) is not something to be taken 
lightly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC and USOC intend to bring more current athletes into  
their decision-making, and the athletes think that could help avert 
similar scandals in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	``Athletes have come up through the ranks, they know the sports,  
they know what the Olympic movement means,'' said Miller, an 
athlete representative for USA Gymnastics. ``That's their life, 
that's what they've grown up doing, and I think having them in the 
position to make decisions for the athletes that are coming up now 
would be good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And just as when they set out to compete, the athletes said they  
were optimistic that the games that form their dreams would emerge 
from the scandal stronger and better. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it can crush the Olympic movement, it's too  
strong,'' Thomas said. ``It's going to get cleaned up and we're 
going to move on from there.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990313.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 15:11:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Purdue Pleased With Indiana Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Purdue's chance to stay alive in the NCAA  
tournament comes Sunday against Miami. But the Boilermakers could 
smile Saturday because their fierce in-state rival, Indiana, was 
eliminated. 
</P>
<P>
	Down in Orlando, the Hoosiers were routed by St. John's 86-61.  
</P>
<P>
	``Personally, I would have liked to have seen Indiana win just  
because of the fact that they're part of the Big Ten,'' Purdue's 
Brian Cardinal said. ``But I think from a university standpoint, 
I'm kind of glad they got beat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not sure we should be concentrating on Indiana and the  
games that they're playing,'' forward Jaraan Cornell said, but ``in 
our hearts, we're kind of happy that they were defeated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Purdue won Big Ten titles in 1994, 1995 and 1996, it  
doesn't get the publicity that Indiana receives. Perhaps that's 
because the Boilermakers have never made it to the Final Four. 
</P>
<P>
	``We get as much recognition as we deserve,'' coach Gene Keady  
said. ``If you want to get more, win bigger.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *GETTING PHYSICAL:* Coaches Bob Huggins of Cincinnati and John  
Chaney of Temple worked hard Saturday trying to lay claim to the 
distinction of being the wimpier team in their game Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not near as physical as Temple is,'' said Huggins, whose  
teams have had a reputation for relishing contact. ``We're a little 
more athletic, a little quicker now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chaney wasn't buying any of that. And with two centers weighing  
240 pounds (Kevin Lyde) and 290 (Ron Rollerson), he still said his 
team needs to be tougher. 
</P>
<P>
	``My players are very, very meek and young,'' Chaney said with a  
laugh. ``There are times when I will challenge them and use 
whatever blaspheme words I can, but I can't seem to get them off 
the mark.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BUILDING TRADITION:* Perhaps a win over Purdue in Sunday's NCAA  
East subregional will drum up more interest in Miami. Hurricanes 
coach Leonard Hamilton understands why that's been lacking. 
</P>
<P>
	From 1971 through 1985, Miami did not have a basketball program  
and a whole generation of youngsters in that city had no local team 
to root for. So when the program resumed, a new fan base had to be 
built. 
</P>
<P>
	``You just don't build tradition in three, four, five, six  
years,'' Hamilton said. Teams that are ``consistently at the top 
for the most part have been there for 20, 30 years.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FORGET DUKE:* Back on Nov. 28, Cincinnati handed Duke its only  
loss of the season, 77-75. That doesn't shake the confidence of 
Temple players as they prepare to face the Bearcats on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it plays a part in our mind,'' Quincy Wadley  
said. ``We know they're a good basketball team and they were 
capable of beating Duke.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They beat Duke, a great team,'' said Mark Karcher, ``but I  
think we can come out and beat anybody on any given night. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *HISTORY LESSON:* Keady likes to take his players sightseeing on  
road trips and their visit to historic Boston was a wonderful 
opportunity. Unless your foot hurts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just took a trip to the JFK museum,'' Cornell said. ``It  
was very interesting, even though I didn't feel like walking around 
because I had a blister on my foot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Keady's reasons for such trips go beyond educating his players.  
</P>
<P>
	``For me,'' he said, ``it's fun to get away from watching tapes  
in the hotel room.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *CONFERENCE CALLS:* Smaller conferences, known as mid-majors,  
don't always get the recognition they deserve. And Chaney thinks 
that may motivate players from those leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	The lack of renown could come from ``talking heads'' who dwell  
on major conferences, Chaney said. That slight could spur players 
from smaller schools even more. 
</P>
<P>
	``They work with a different kind of fuel and it's always  
high-test,'' Chaney said. ``They're saying, `Hey, we can do it' 
when somebody else is saying they can't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Temple beat one of those schools, Kent of the Mid-American  
Conference, 61-54 in Friday's first round. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990313.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 01:40:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nebraska Faces E. Coli Outbreak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- The largest E. coli outbreak in Nebraska  
history grew to 49 cases, and state health officials warned there 
could be more. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know there are at least half a dozen potential cases that  
we're looking into in addition to the 49 already found,'' Marla 
Augustine, spokeswoman for Nebraska Health and Human Services, said 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The outbreak has been traced to a restaurant in Kearney where  
investigators suspect contaminated lettuce may have been the 
source. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven people have been hospitalized for the potentially fatal  
bacteria, including an 8-year-old girl who was in serious 
condition. 
</P>
<P>
	The strain of E. coli in the 49 cases attacks the digestive  
tract. Symptoms include fever and bloody diarrhea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
