<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles Step Up To Defend Belle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- The Baltimore Orioles leaped to the  
defense of Albert Belle on Saturday, insisting that his recent 
clubhouse tirade should never have been reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Belle made headlines when he angrily threw his glove, helmet and  
two bats into his locker Thursday after striking out in the sixth 
inning of an exhibition game. He also whisked aside several letters 
that were sitting on his chair before showering and quickly exiting 
the clubhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	The eruption occurred in a near-empty room filled with a handful  
of reporters and a few players. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking in an impromptu press conference in the Oriole dugout  
before an exhibition game against Montreal, Orioles general manager 
Frank Wren said, ``I think the whole situation is unjust. I think 
some confidences were violated (because) the clubhouse is sanctuary 
of the players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During the regular season, the clubhouse is closed to the media  
for 15 minutes after a game. But the Orioles opened the locker room 
during games in the spring because players often leave well before 
the ninth inning. 
</P>
<P>
	After Belle's tirade was reported, the Orioles abruptly changed  
their policy and now keep the clubhouse closed during exhibition 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	But according to the team, the damage had been done.  
</P>
<P>
	``This hurt a lot of people. It hurt our franchise and it hurt  
Albert because Albert has done nothing wrong,'' Wren said. ``I 
would say there's 55 players in that clubhouse, and if 54 others 
did what he did it wouldn't have been a story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Belle, however, is no ordinary player. He has been suspended for  
destroying part of a bathroom, hitting a taunting fan in the chest 
with a thrown baseball, twice charging the mound, using a corked 
bat and hitting an infielder with his forearm. 
</P>
<P>
	Belle talked of changing his controversial image upon signing a  
five-year, $65 million contract with Baltimore in December, and the 
Orioles were eager to stress that Thursday's incident was not a 
digression. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you sit in that clubhouse, every single game of every  
single season, somebody's going to walk in there and throw 
something,'' Orioles manager Ray Miller said. ``That's why we keep 
the press out during the season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Wren: ``It's a pimple on an elephant. This isn't right.''  
</P>
<P>
	Belle, approached by three Orioles beat writers seeking comment  
Friday, said, ``I'm done. I'm done with you guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wren, who planned to talk to Belle about the coverage of the  
incident, said, ``I can see why he's upset and wouldn't speak.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990313.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 00:41:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> America's Cup TV Row Cools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The America's Cup seems safe at ESPN -- at least  
for now. 
</P>
<P>
	The network had threatened to pull out of its contract to  
televise the event because rival Fox Sports Net signed a contract 
to have its logos plastered on Young America's yachts. 
</P>
<P>
	But Fox Sports Net reached an agreement to let the New York  
Yacht club syndicate the sponsorship deal so that the event's TV 
status wouldn't be placed in jeopardy. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we gave money to help build a winning U.S. entrant, we  
did it to bring the Cup back to America, and it was a good 
marketing opportunity,'' Fox Sports Net spokesman Vince Wladika 
said. ``When it became apparent the televising network was willing 
to sacrifice the event along with America's chances of reclaiming 
the Cup, we felt it was our duty to put our own interest behind 
that of America's reclamation of the Cup.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ESPN contract stated that Fox Sports Net ads would appear on  
the sails and hulls of two of Young America's yachts during 
America's Cup races. 
</P>
<P>
	``Out of respect for the America's Cup, Fox Sports has  
generously agreed to release us from the contractual obligations 
that ESPN objected to,'' said John Marshall, president of Young 
America. ``Fox Sports Net agrees with us that our partnership has 
fueled a dispute that has become a distraction from our mission of 
winning the Cup.'' 
</P>
<P>
	ESPN signed the final contract to air the event last week, and  
the syndicates had a 30-day window to agree to the terms, which 
stipulated that the telecast was clear of competing network logos. 
</P>
<P>
	ESPN said it would pull out of the event unless those terms were  
met. 
</P>
<P>
	It already had agreements from America's Cup 2000, the event  
organizer in New Zealand, and the America's Cup Challenge 
Association, which represents the competition's 15 teams. 
</P>
<P>
	But final approval hinged on a unanimous decision by the 15  
challenge teams -- including Young America. 
</P>
<P>
	But Fox Sports Net didn't wait until the 30 days expired before  
ending the controversy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990313.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 06:28:42 </DATE_TIME>
