<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> School Desegregation Deal Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- A settlement approved in a long-standing school  
desegregation case will allow busing to continue but frees the St. 
Louis school district from court supervision. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Stephen N. Limbaugh Sr., who approved the  
settlement Friday, said it represents ``a fair, reasonable and 
adequate resolution to this historic case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers representing 21 parties have been quarreling since 1972  
when the original lawsuit was filed by Minnie Liddell, a black 
mother who alleged that St. Louis Public Schools and the state of 
Missouri were responsible for a segregated school system. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement scales back busing between the city and county  
school districts, maintains the city's magnet school program, 
provides about $180 million for new schools and sets student 
achievement goals for city schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Missouri Attorney General Jay Nixon apologized again Friday to  
past generations for once supporting a system that allowed skin 
color to determine where children attended school. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's my opinion that the state of Missouri has learned its  
lesson,'' Nixon said. 
</P>
<P>
	Acceptance of the St. Louis settlement brings an end to the last  
of Missouri's two court-ordered school desegregation programs, 
which have been among the most costly and ambitious approaches in 
the country. 
</P>
<P>
	But not everyone was happy with the settlement.  
</P>
<P>
	St. Louis Mayor Clarence Harmon had complained that it left out  
an earlier agreement for an oversight board to monitor the school 
district. 
</P>
<P>
	``We intend to carefully monitor the school district's progress  
toward improving the quality of education our children receive ... 
and will not hesitate to speak out when we feel their effort is 
falling short,'' Harmon said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
