<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indiana H.S. Hoops Player Mourned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Hundreds of students exchanged hugs and  
shared tears Saturday as they remembered John Stewart, a star 
basketball player who died during a regional championship game. 
</P>
<P>
	An autopsy performed Saturday morning revealed that Stewart, 18,  
a senior center for Lawrence North High School, died from heart 
complications stemming from a disease known as hypertrophic 
cardiomyopathy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a disease of the heart that causes the heart to become  
enlarged,'' said Joyce Fisher, Bartholomew County coroner. ``And 
when that happens, the pump system in the heart doesn't work hard 
enough to sustain life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher said Stewart probably wasn't born with the disease, but  
it's a condition that progressed over time. She said less than 1 
percent of the population has the condition. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes there are some symptoms, but it's not unusual on  
young adults to cause sudden death,'' Fisher said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart died Friday after collapsing at Columbus North High  
School during the regional championship game between Class 4A No. 2 
Lawrence North and No. 1 Bloomington South. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lawrence North star, who had already signed to play with  
Kentucky in the fall, was at the top of his game, scoring 22 
points, including 10 in a row to start the second half. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was having the game of his life,'' said Tal Short, senior  
guard for Lawrence North and co-captain with Stewart. 
</P>
<P>
	With two minutes to play in the third quarter, he asked to be  
taken out because he was feeling dizzy and having trouble 
breathing. He collapsed on the bench and was taken to Columbus 
Regional Hospital, where he died. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher said Stewart's 7-foot, nearly 300-pound body needed a  
strong heart to keep it going. 
</P>
<P>
	``It takes a good heart to pump a lot of blood and oxygen  
through (the body) and when you are strenuously exercising, at some 
point it just can't keep up anymore,'' Fisher said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher said that Stewart's mother, Felicia Stewart, had noticed  
her son was experiencing some shortness of breath during games in 
the past few weeks. But the basketball player thought his asthma 
was causing his difficulty in breathing, so he had been using his 
inhaler a little more than usual. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Fisher said, it's safe to say that Stewart's heart  
condition, not his asthma, was making it difficult for him to 
breathe. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart's teammates, Fred Long and Andy Means, said they didn't  
even realize that Stewart had asthma until the second North Central 
game this season, when Stewart said he was dizzy and used an 
inhaler in the locker room. 
</P>
<P>
	``It didn't happen during the rest of the season,'' Means said.  
``So it just kind of got out of my head.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant superintendent Duane Hodgin said Stewart had had a  
physical and was cleared to play. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday, several of the school's 1,200 students packed into the  
auditorium to remember their friend and support one another. 
</P>
<P>
	Lana Klene, a school counselor, said that many students were  
getting over the initial shock and just felt numb Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're walking around, checking out groups of students,'' she  
said. ``If one of them seems to be having a hard time coping, we 
get them out of the auditorium and talk to them one on one. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're giving lots of hugs.''  
</P>
<P>
	A crisis team also assembled at the school Friday night. As many  
as 500 students, parents and school officials waited in the 
gymnasium and cafeteria for the buses to return from the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Gathered in small groups, students talked in hushed tones.  
Others walked around with dazed looks on their faces. 
</P>
<P>
	The team's cheerleaders sat in a circle, and fans still dressed  
for the game walked around crying, many saying they couldn't 
believe what had happened. 
</P>
<P>
	Others held hands and formed a circle around Stewart's Lawrence  
North jersey, which someone had placed in the center of the 
gymnasium floor. 
</P>
<P>
	Long, a junior center, said he'll miss his friend and will think  
about him every time he suits up next year. He said if he could, 
he'd tell Stewart: ``Thanks for beating up on me in practice. You 
are one of the best friends I've ever had. I love you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other teammates said it helps to know that Stewart died while  
playing the game he liked. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it had to go like that, I don't know if there could've been  
a better time or a better game for that,'' sophomore guard Chris 
Hill said. ``If there was any way he would've wanted to go out, 
that was it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
