<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oklahoma, UNCC Are Similar Teams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Neither Oklahoma coach Kelvin Sampson nor North  
Carolina-Charlotte coach Bobby Lutz had to study much film for 
their showdown Sunday in the second round of the NCAA tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sooners (21-10) and 49ers (23-10) share too many  
similarities. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither team has great post play, and so relies heavily on the  
3-point shot. 
</P>
<P>
	Both teams use superior speed to make up for a lack of size and  
are led by demonstrative coaches who honed their talents at tiny 
NAIA schools and who got their first NCAA tournament victories 
Friday at the Bradley Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Lutz ``kind of looks like that crazy coach from Oklahoma  
sometimes,'' Sooners coach Kelvin Sampson said Saturday in what 
seemed like a meeting of the Mutual Admiration Society. 
</P>
<P>
	Both schools survived down-to-the-wire games in the first round  
thanks to dizzying displays of defensive switches. The 49ers 
dispatched Lamar Odom and Rhode Island and Oklahoma cut short the 
college careers of Arizona's A.J. Bramlett and Jason Terry. 
</P>
<P>
	The 49ers and Sooners each boast a key starter from Latin  
America who had to master English along with the jump shot. The 
49ers have kiss-blowing guard Diego Geuvara of Venezuela and 
Oklahoma has Eduardo Najera of Mexico, a forward who plays more 
like a guard. 
</P>
<P>
	These teams are mirror images.  
</P>
<P>
	``Oklahoma, they have real good shooters. They led the Big 12 in  
3-point shooting; we led Conference USA in 3-point shooting,'' 
49ers senior forward Galen Young said. ``They're not a real big 
team. We're not a real big team. 
</P>
<P>
	``But we both make up for that with aggressiveness and just the  
will to win. So, that's going to make for a real good game come 
Sunday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The game between the fifth-seeded 49ers, who upset 12th-seeded  
but slightly favored Rhode Island in overtime, and the 13th-seeded 
Sooners, who upset the Wildcats 61-60, precedes the Ole 
Miss-Michigan State matchup. 
</P>
<P>
	Oklahoma senior guard Michael Johnson said the resemblances  
might have made for easier preparation but will present a tougher 
task on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``They play hard. They execute their offense. I think it's going  
to be a challenge to play a team similar to ourselves,'' Johnson 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Najera said another similarity is the underdog mentality that  
has fueled both teams all season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're very similar,'' Najera said. ``We haven't gotten  
a lot of respect, but that's why we're here. We're going to try to 
get it. And I'm sure Charlotte feels the same way. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are very similar. We run our sets and execute. We don't  
have an NBA player that's going to take over the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We're kind of like in the same boat as far as respect,'' 49ers  
senior guard Marlon Thomas agreed. ``They're coming in here with 
nothing to lose. We're coming in here with nothing to lose. ... So, 
it's going to be a dogfight from start to finish.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lutz knows just what kind of sharpshooters he'll face Sunday.  
</P>
<P>
	``They shoot the 3 so well, that's kind of like us,'' Lutz said.  
``And we know how tough we can be to defend when we're shooting the 
basketball well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sampson said he didn't anticipate any surprises from either  
team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that we're not going to get to tomorrow and all of a  
sudden get bad at the things we do good,'' Sampson said. ``The 
things that we've emphasized to our guys on a daily basis has been 
our old standbys. That's defending and rebounding.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both teams are known for their hustle: rebounding, drawing  
charges, diving after loose balls. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got a feeling they're going to balance out,'' Lutz said.  
</P>
<P>
	So, just what will be the difference in advancing to the round  
of 16 and going home? 
</P>
<P>
	Both coaches had similar takes on that, too.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's going to boil down to who shoots the basketball  
the best,'' Lutz said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Making shots,'' Sampson agreed. ``It comes down to that.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
