<DOCNO> APW19990313.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 00:22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trump, NASCAR Plan N.Y. Metro Track </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Donald Trump and Bill France figure the old  
Field of Dreams line is true: If you build it, they will come. 
</P>
<P>
	So Trump, the real estate developer, and France, chairman and  
chief executive officer of the International Speedway Corporation, 
plan to construct a superspeedway in the metropolitan New York area 
where, until now, motorsports rarely has been seen. 
</P>
<P>
	The track will be in either New York, New Jersey or Connecticut.  
Except for Watkins Glen and Pocono -- both well-removed from the 
area -- auto racing has been in short supply in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	France, whose family owns NASCAR and controls valuable Winston  
Cup racing dates, said the expansion makes sense. 
</P>
<P>
	``ISC looks for growth opportunities and the New York market  
offers that,'' France said. ``We are excited about the prospects. 
We plan a track with the highest standards and new and unique 
features.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trump said five sites were under consideration with five more to  
be added before a final decision is made. He said the facility 
would cost between $200 and $250 million, ``maybe more.' 
</P>
<P>
	One problem could be finding a race for the facility once it is  
completed. The current NASCAR schedule includes 34 races -- one up 
from last year with the new Homestead, Fla. track, in which ISC has 
part ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	France's company is also constructing new tracks in Kansas City,  
and Joliet, Ill., and another facility is being built in Denver by 
Penske Motorsports. That could raise the calendar to 37 races and 
other tracks -- Texas, Phoenix, Fontana, Calif., and Las Vegas -- 
desperately want second Winston Cup races. 
</P>
<P>
	ISC would own the new track, adding it to five other motorsports  
facilities under its control. That list includes Daytona 
International Speedway, home of the Daytona 500; and tracks in 
Talladega, Ala.; Phoenix; Darlington, S.C.; and Watkins Glen, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	France said the layout in the New York area would be at least a  
one-mile track to qualify for the superspeedway designation and 
would probably have a road course to maximize usage. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be 750 acres, up or down a little, with a minimum of  
75,000 seats to start,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new track will be called Trump Superspeedway. Future naming  
rights, however, will be retained by ISC. 
</P>
<P>
	Trump said politicians from all three states had contacted him  
about the track. 
</P>
<P>
	``They all want it,'' he said. ``Any good politician would want  
it in his area. It means huge economic development for the 
community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One site on the preliminary list is in Riverhead, N.Y., on Long  
Island, about 75 miles from New York City. A town official last 
month said Trump has bid $55 million to develop a 2,900-acre site 
that once housed an aircraft test flight facility. 
</P>
<P>
	``Riverhead is a little far out,'' Trump said. ``It's a  
wonderful site. It's one of our sites. But it's tough out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then the developer looked around Trump Tower, one of his  
buildings in the heart of Manhattan, where the speedway 
announcement was made. 
</P>
<P>
	``The key,'' he said, ``is to be as close to Fifth Avenue and  
57th Street as possible.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990313.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 01:23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Purdue Comes Up Big </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Purdue had a big shot to take in its biggest game  
of the season, and the guy who took it, and made it, wasn't the 
player most people expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Cameron Stephens hit a 15-footer jumper with 25 seconds left to  
break the game's final tie Friday night, and the Boilermakers went 
on to a 58-54 victory over Texas in the opening round of the East 
Regional. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephens, who came in averaging 3.3 points, hit the game-winner  
on a nice pass from a driving Tony Mayfield. The most logical 
shooter would have been Jaraan Cornell, the Boilermakers' leading 
scorer, or Brian Cardinal, the workhorse forward, who is second on 
the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``We practice that when the big man steps out,'' said Cornell,  
who finished with 18 points. ``Tony gave him a great pass. His form 
looked good and he knocked it down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Purdue (20-12), the 10th seed, will play second-seeded Miami, a  
75-54 winner over Lafayette, in Sunday's second round at the 
FleetCenter. 
</P>
<P>
	In Friday's other doubleheader at the FleetCenter, third-seeded  
Cincinnati beat No. 14 George Mason 72-48 and sixth-seeded Temple 
defeated No. 11 Kent State 61-54. Those winners will meet in 
Sunday's other second-round game. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephens' shot gave him four points for the game and put the  
Boilermakers, who had entered the tournament having lost four of 
five, ahead 56-54. After a turnover by seventh-seeded Texas 
(19-13), Mayfield made two free throws with 4.1 seconds left for 
the final margin. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a hard-fought, grind-it-out game the way we thought it  
would be,'' Purdue coach Gene Keady said. ``We regrouped over the 
last 10, 12 days and got our attitudes right. Cam hit that shot, 
Tony made the free throws, we played good defense and we advance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Texas led 51-50 with 1:22 left on a driving layup by Ivan  
Wagner. Cornell hit a short jumper and made two free throws around 
a turnover by Wagner for a 54-51 lead. The Longhorns tied it with 
25 seconds left on a 3-pointer by William Clay, but those were 
their final points. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Mihm had 21 points and 14 rebounds for Texas, and he was  
almost the hero on Stephens' game-winner. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their guard drove. I came out and he kicked it out,'' the  
7-footer said. ``I actually got a piece of the ball. It was a good 
clutch shot. Sometimes it goes.'' 
</P>
<P>
                       *Miami 75, Lafayette 54    	
</P>
<P>
	Johnny Hemsley set a school record with nine 3-pointers and had  
31 points as the Hurricanes (23-6) won their first NCAA tournament 
game in their third appearance. Hemsley was 9-for-12 from long 
range, and two of his 3s accounted for half the points in Miami's 
12-0 run to open the second half, giving the Hurricanes a 46-29 
lead. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great feeling to have this kind of game in this caliber  
of game,'' Hemsley said. ``It just felt great to get our first NCAA 
win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hemsley made 3-pointer after 3-pointer and, after his  
career-high seventh early in the second half, he turned to the 
crowd and gave an imitation of Michael Jordan's famous shrug when 
he couldn't miss from long range in the NBA Finals. 
</P>
<P>
	``A tournament game, a full house, that's what you live for,''  
he said. ``When you play well in a packed gym, it's a great 
feeling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hemsley finished two shy of the NCAA tournament record set by  
Jeff Fryer of Loyola Marymount against Michigan in the second round 
in 1990. Hemsley broke the school record of eight set by Samarr 
Logan in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Ehlers, the Patriot League player of the year, had 14  
points for Lafayette (22-8), the 15th seed that was making its 
second NCAA appearance and first since 1957. 
</P>
<P>
                    *Cincinnati 72, George Mason 48    	
</P>
<P>
	The Bearcats (27-5) advanced to the second round for the fifth  
straight year with the easy win, holding the Patriots (19-11) to 
their worst shooting game of the season (18-for-66, 27.3 percent). 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're one of the best defensive teams in the  
country,'' Cincinnati coach Bob Huggins said. ``In the 10 years 
I've been here, this is one of the better halfcourt defensive teams 
we've had.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pete Mickeal had 18 points for the Bearcats, who closed the  
first half with a 26-6 run for a 41-17 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Jason Miskiri had 13 points for the Patriots, who had won 10  
straight games. 
</P>
<P>
                        *Temple 61, Kent St. 54    	
</P>
<P>
	Point guard Pepe Sanchez played 40 minutes and had 15 points,  
six rebounds, nine assists and no turnovers for the Owls (22-10), 
who will play Cincinnati in the NCAA tournament for the third time 
in five years. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems we're always in their neighborhood,'' Temple coach  
John Chaney said of the Bearcats, who have won the previous two 
meetings. ``Our chances are better to win against a team like that 
than they were against a team like Kent State.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rasheed Brokenborough also had 15 points for Temple, which led  
59-48 with 2:03 to play. 
</P>
<P>
	John Whorton had 13 points for the Golden Flashes (23-7), who  
were making their first NCAA tournament appearance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
