<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NY Speaker Urges Movie Ticket Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Despite a plunging crime rate, some New Yorkers  
say there's one place where they're still getting mugged -- at the 
movies. 
</P>
<P>
	Ticket prices have hit $9.50, and City Council Speaker Peter  
Vallone is calling for a movie boycott and a federal investigation 
into theater giant Loews Cineplex Entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's hit them where it hurts most,'' Vallone said Friday. He  
wants moviegoers to skip flicks on the first Friday of each month, 
and says they should bring their own munchies the rest of the time. 
</P>
<P>
	He's not alone. A New York Times columnist suggested that  
moviegoers bring their own paper cups into theaters to abuse the 
free refill policy. 
</P>
<P>
	New Yorkers tend to be resigned to paying a premium on just  
about everything. After all, Broadway tickets top off at $85 each, 
and a dinner for two in Manhattan can easily run $100. 
</P>
<P>
	But Vallone and others worry climbing movie prices will soon put  
a trip to the silver screen out of reach for some families. 
</P>
<P>
	The $9.50 price tag -- which the City Council says is the highest  
in the nation -- is just the latest benchmark. In the last five 
years, movie ticket prices in the city have risen by 27 percent, 
more than twice as fast as the cost of living. 
</P>
<P>
	In comparison, tickets in Oklahoma City and Honolulu cost $6.50;  
Omaha, Neb. $7; Detroit, $7.50; and Los Angeles, $8.50. 
</P>
<P>
	During his tenure in the 1980s, then-Mayor Edward I. Koch tried  
to organize a picket against rising movie prices, but the campaign 
had little success. 
</P>
<P>
	``Movies are the opiate of the people,'' he said. ``No picket  
line will succeed. The only thing that will succeed is 
competition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sony Corp. of America and Cineplex Odeon announced in 1997 that  
they would merge their theater businesses to form the world's 
largest movie theater company, with more than 2,600 screens in 
North America. The new company, Loews Cineplex, controls about half 
of the screens in New York City. 
</P>
<P>
	In letters to the Justice Department and the state attorney  
general, Vallone asked the government to look into Loews Cineplex 
in light of last month's 50-cent price increase to $9.50. He also 
said the Council would open hearings. 
</P>
<P>
	Loews Cineplex officials did not return several calls for  
comment Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside a Sony theater at Lincoln Square, some moviegoers  
shrugged at the price increase. Others bemoaned the high prices 
that are part of life in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's absolutely too high, especially for children. It used to  
cost $5 for them and now it's $6,'' said Liz Callahan, 32, who was 
taking her two nieces, aged 8 and 7, to a matinee. 
</P>
<P>
	``They shouldn't have raised prices without giving something in  
return, like free popcorn,'' said Levi James, 25, of Manhattan. 
</P>
<P>
	New York Times columnist Clyde Haberman recently noted that  
signs over the Sony food counters say, ``Free refills on all 
fountain drinks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They don't say that the refill has to be the same day,'' he  
wrote. ``Do you see theater owners patting down hundreds of people 
looking for cup smugglers? Just a question.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
