<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 00:41:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Holyfield Prediction Sets Tone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Evander Holyfield boxed himself into a corner  
even before he and Lennox Lewis enter the ring to unify the 
heavyweight title tonight at Madison Square Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	Holyfield put himself there with a promise of a third-round  
knockout -- and a claim that he has no backup plan if his prophecy 
doesn't come to pass. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have a Plan B, so Plan A has to work,'' Holyfield  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	If Holyfield finds Lewis still standing after the bell sounds to  
end the third round of the scheduled 12-round fight, he'll have 
only a minute or so to figure out what to do the rest of the night. 
</P>
<P>
	He doesn't seem terribly concerned that will happen.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not taking Lennox down. Lennox is good,'' Holyfield said.  
``You have the best of the best in this fight. Because you have the 
best of the best, a knockout has to take place. When you have two 
people truly trying to win, somebody is going to get knocked out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holyfield risks his WBA and IBF versions of the heavyweight  
title when he meets Lewis, holder of the WBC crown. The first 
unification of the sport's most prized crown will take place 
sometime around 11:30 p.m. EST before a sellout crowd of some 
20,000 people who paid anywhere from $100 to $1,500 for the right 
to witness a slice of history. 
</P>
<P>
	Holyfield, though, will need some cooperation from Lewis to  
fulfill his promise of ending the fight in the third round. That's 
what happened when Holyfield beat James ``Buster'' Douglas in 
October 1990 to capture the undisputed title, and it happened again 
later when Tyson bit him in the same round. 
</P>
<P>
	While Holyfield (36-3, 25 knockouts) will enter the ring with  
``Warrior'' stitched across the front of his trunks, Lewis has been 
more of a reluctant warrior at times. He might decide to fight 
cautiously early, hoping to catch Holyfield in the later rounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only way you can hit somebody is when they're trying to  
hit you,'' Holyfield conceded. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis will bring a big physical presence into the fight that  
will likely define a career that has been noted so far more for the 
fights he has missed out on than the ones he has been involved in. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis stands 6-foot-5 and weighed 246 pounds at Thursday's  
weigh-in, 31 more than Holyfield, who has always had problems with 
bigger heavyweights. 
</P>
<P>
	But Holyfield has fought -- and beaten -- the best of his era,  
winning fights with Mike Tyson, Riddick Bowe, Michael Moorer, 
George Foreman and Larry Holmes. A look at the record of Lewis 
(34-1, 27 knockouts) reveals the likes of Oliver McCall, Henry 
Akinwande and Andrew Golota at the top of the list. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a fight that has been eluding me a long time,'' said  
the 33-year-old Lewis, who won an Olympic gold medal for Canada in 
the 1988 Olympics, but claims British residency. ``It will be a 
great fight for me to make a mark and prove that I'm the best 
heavyweight on the planet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On a purely physical level the fight could turn on Holyfield's  
ability to get inside on Lewis, who possesses a heavy and active 
left jab, and Lewis' chances of landing his big right hand. 
</P>
<P>
	But what might be the key to the fight is which fighter can  
answer the questions posed of him. In Holyfield's case, it is his 
relatively advanced age of 36, which showed in a lackluster 
decision over Vaughn Bean his last time out. For Lewis, it is 
whether he has it inside of him to brawl with and beat one of the 
best heavyweights around. 
</P>
<P>
	``How dare they question my heart,'' Lewis said. ``Evander  
Holyfield doesn't have the monopoly on hearts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holyfield will make $20 million for the fight, bringing his  
earnings in four fights since upsetting Tyson in their first bout 
to some $80 million. Lewis will get $10 million for the chance to 
establish himself as the biggest heavyweight in town. 
</P>
<P>
	On the undercard, James Page (23-3, 18 knockouts) of Pittsburg,  
Calif., will defend the WBA welterweight title against Sam Garr 
(25-2, 23 knockouts) of Stone Mountain, Ga.; and Fernando Vargas 
(15-0, 15 knockouts) of Oxnard, Calif., will defend the IBF junior 
middleweight title against Howard Clarke (26-10-2, 8 knockouts) of 
England. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
