<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vicar Favored in Florida Derby </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HALLANDALE, Fla. (AP) -- It's sink or swim in the Florida Derby.  
</P>
<P>
	Vicar, the Fountain of Youth Stakes winner, heads a field of 10  
3-year-olds in today's $750,000 Florida Derby, one of several 
Kentucky Derby prep races this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's done well in the shallow end of the pool,'' Carl Nafzger,  
Vicar's trainer, said. ``Now it's time to jump into the deep end. 
With the way this horse has been training, I'd be surprised if he 
didn't like it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vicar is the 3-1 favorite in the 1 1/8-mile Florida Derby at  
Gulfstream Park, with Cat Thief considered his chief threat after 
losing by a neck to Nafzger's colt in the Fountain of Youth on Feb. 
20. 
</P>
<P>
	Nafzger revealed earlier this week that Vicar had a breathing  
problem after a dull fifth-place finish in the Holy Bull Stakes on 
Jan. 16, and that it was corrected by minor surgery a few days 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	Vicar came back strong to win the Fountain of Youth and improved  
his career record to three wins and a second in five starts. A win 
today and Vicar stamps himself as the best in the East. 
</P>
<P>
	Cat Thief, trained by D. Wayne Lukas, is one of five challengers  
from the Fountain of Youth. The others are the third and 
fourth-place finishers in Certain and Grits'n Hard Toast, as well 
as Aly's Alley and Casanova Star. 
</P>
<P>
	Also trying to run down Vicar was Valid Trefaire, a sprinter  
expected to set the pace; the Nick Zito-trained duo of Adonis and 
Wondertross; and First American. Adonis and Wondertross were not 
coupled in the wagering. 
</P>
<P>
	Three Ring, the impressive filly who was entered Wednesday, but  
drew an unfavorable outside post position, was to be scratched 
today, trainer Eddie Plesa Jr., said. Three Ring will run instead 
in the $200,000 Bonnie Miss Stakes for fillies Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the Florida Derby (ABC, post time 5:41 p.m.),  
there are four other races -- two each in California and Louisiana -- 
with Kentucky Derby implications. And trainer Bob Baffert has the 
horses to beat in all of them. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert saddles the current Kentucky Derby favorite Exploit and  
Prime Timber in the San Felipe Stakes today at Santa Anita and the 
filly Silverbulletday today in the Fair Grounds Oaks in New 
Orleans; on Sunday, he's got General Challenge in the Louisiana 
Derby and the filly Excellent Meeting in the Santa Anita Oaks. 
</P>
<P>
	General Challenge will be tested by Answer Lively, winner of the  
Breeders' Cup Juvenile, but looking for his first win as a 
3-year-old. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert nearly captured the Triple Crown the past two years,  
winning the Derby and Preakness with Silver Charm in 1997 and with 
Real Quiet in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	While Baffert is looking for an unprecedented third straight  
Derby win, Nafzger is looking for a second trip to Louisville on 
the first Saturday in May. In 1990, Unbridled won the Florida 
Derby, then went on to win the Kentucky Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	Vicar isn't alone in needing a big race to keep Derby dreams  
alive. 
</P>
<P>
	Cat Thief has been improving steadily, with a third-place finish  
in the Hutcheson Stakes followed by his strong effort in the 
Fountain of Youth. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he has moved forward since the Fountain of Youth,''  
Lukas said Friday of his main Kentucky Derby prospect. ``You'll 
hear some trainers say that horses never lie. Well, I'm here to 
tell you that they do lie, but he has given me every indication 
that he is moving forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leo Azpurua Jr., who trains Certain, also expects improvement.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's as ready as he can be,'' Azpurua said after Certain  
galloped at Calder Friday. Certain, to be ridden by Kent 
Desormeaux, entered the Fountain of Youth undefeated in four starts 
around two turns. 
</P>
<P>
	Also on the Florida Derby card is the $100,000 Swale Stakes,  
with Texas Glitter the 6-5 favorite in a field of six 3-year-olds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
