<DOCNO> APW19990313.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 14:42:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tulsa Facing Big Challenge in Duke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- There's more bad news for the rest of the  
NCAA tournament field attempting to knock off No. 1 Duke. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Mike Krzyzewski said 3-point ace Trajan Langdon will start  
Sunday against Tulsa in the second round of the East Regional. The 
senior and team's second-leading scorer had missed the last three 
games with a foot injury. 
</P>
<P>
	The top-seeded Blue Devils (33-1) didn't seem to miss a beat  
without Langdon, winning the Atlantic Coast Conference tournament 
before dusting off 16th-seeded Florida A&AMP;M 99-58 Friday night in 
the opening round of the NCAAs. 
</P>
<P>
	But Krzyzewski said Langdon's return is important to a team,  
that believe it or not, he thinks can get better. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason we want him back is obvious; he's good and we're a  
better team, but also you start picking up bad habits, primarily in 
pace,'' Krzyzewski said Saturday. ``You are playing hard but you're 
still pacing because you know there isn't a fifth perimeter guy. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can pick up bad habits when you pace, maybe you don't deny  
as hard or you don't pressure as hard because you know you have to 
be in there a few extra minutes. We want to get away from that 
because we attack through our defense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Duke has won 28 straight and is the prohibitive favorite  
to win the national title, No. 9 seed Tulsa (23-9) will be looking 
to advance to the round of 16 for the third time in the decade. 
</P>
<P>
	The Golden Hurricane played Duke tough in the Preseason NIT two  
seasons ago before losing 72-67, but Bill Self was not the team's 
coach and most of Duke's star players were still in high school. 
</P>
<P>
	``I remember the 11-point lead we had at halftime and at the end  
of the game Coach Krzyzewski said, `Man, can they guard,''' said 
Tulsa's Michael Ruffin. ``We matched their intensity at that time. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were in control throughout the entire game, but at the end  
we let their pressure get to us. On Sunday, we're going to have to 
come out there and execute against their pressure and take care of 
the ball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tulsa's downfall all season has been turnovers, and its  
first-round win over College of Charleston was no different. The 
Golden Hurricane coughed it up 25 times and almost blew a 26-point 
second-half lead before hanging on 62-53. 
</P>
<P>
	Self tried to diffuse the pressure of a matchup with powerhouse  
Duke, saying he likes the role of underdog. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, we're a huge underdog,'' he said. ``But I'll go to  
bed and I hope our players go to bed thinking it's going to be a 
special day and history will be made in a positive way for us. 
We've got nothing to lose and let's go let it all hang out and see 
what happens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Self admitted a victory over the high-scoring Blue  
Devils, who he called the best team in the post-Wooden era, would 
be extremely difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	``That D.U.K.E. on the front of their jerseys is worth about 10  
or 15 points,'' Self said. ``Hopefully, it will be a situation 
where our guys think they are playing in a park in Durham or a park 
in north Tulsa and we're playing shirts and skins. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has to be a special day for us to have an opportunity to  
win the basketball game. But there have been a lot of special days 
in this NCAA tournament for a lot of people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The second game at the Charlotte Coliseum will feature No. 4  
seed Tennessee (21-8) against 12th-seeded Southwest Missouri State 
(21-10). 
</P>
<P>
	The Volunteers were knocked out of the NCAAs a year ago in the  
first round by another Missouri Valley Conference school -- Illinois 
State. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, players for Southwest Missouri said they needed to  
``calm down'' following the team's first-round upset over No. 5 
seed Wisconsin. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Steve Alford relaxed his players by chest-bumping with  
them in practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was shocked to hear that more coaches don't chest bump,''  
said Alford, a star guard for Indiana's 1987 national championship 
team. ``We just have to relax and play. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're the 12th seed, and we weren't champions of the SEC and  
we haven't been ranked in the top 25 or 30 all year. But we've had 
an outstanding year. This has been a very consistent team, and one 
that has been able to play a lot of different styles.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
