<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Austrian Wins Women's Slalom Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SIERRA NEVADA, Spain (AP) -- Alexandra Meissnitzer of Austria  
claimed the World Cup season giant slalom title today, adding to 
the overall season crown she clinched last week and the season 
super-G title she sewed up on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	With Meissnitzer's three titles, and season titles to fellow  
Austrians Sabine Egger (slalom) and Renate Goetschl (downhill), the 
Austrians swept all five women's '99 discipline championships. The 
Swiss women were the last to achieve that in 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	The Austrian men won an unprecedented five titles last season,  
but can get no more than three this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Austrian Anita Wachter won today's World Cup Final slalom in a  
combined 2 minutes, 8.81 seconds. Second went to Anna Ottosson of 
Sweden (2:10.54), followed by Norway's Andrine Flemmen (2:10.59). 
</P>
<P>
	Meissnitzer finished eighth in today's season's finale (2:12.01)  
for women, picking up 32 points to give her 652 for the season. 
Wachter, with her fourth World Cup slalom win of the season, gained 
100 points to finish with 636. Meissnitzer also won four slaloms 
this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Three-time Olympic champion Deborah Compagnoni of Italy skied in  
the race and then confirmed her retirement, which was widely 
reported several days ago. The 28-year-old has been plagued by 
injury and serious illness in recent seasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
