<DOCNO> APW19990313.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 04:51:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> T'Wolves Blame Changes on Marbury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- When the final buzzer sounded in last  
season's playoff-ending loss to the Seattle SuperSonics, the 
Minnesota Timberwolves could take heart in a future that looked 
brilliant. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten months and one collective bargaining agreement later, the  
picture is very different, and for that the Wolves blame Stephon 
Marbury. 
</P>
<P>
	``The complexion of our team has changed drastically in the last  
three months because of Steph,'' coach Flip Saunders said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wolves believe Marbury's unwillingness to play in Minnesota  
not only cost them his considerable talents, but also those of 
former All-Star Tom Gugliotta and veteran guard Terry Porter, an 
important leader on a young team. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice president of basketball operations Kevin McHale said the  
Wolves were forced to trade Marbury to the New Jersey Nets on 
Thursday when the New York City native said he couldn't play on the 
same team as Kevin Garnett, who last year signed a $126 million 
contract, the richest long-term deal in sports history. 
</P>
<P>
	``Stephon Marbury expressed some real concern that he wouldn't  
be able to make the kind of money that Kevin Garnett makes, and 
that was kind of bothersome to him,'' McHale said. 
</P>
<P>
	Saunders said he tried to explain that the NBA's new collective  
bargaining agreement, ratified in January after a six-month 
lockout, strictly limits how much a player can earn. Marbury was 
unwilling to change his mind. 
</P>
<P>
	``I tried to explain to (Marbury) about the importance of  
winning and being in a good situation,'' Saunders said. ``He said, 
`Hey Flip, it's business. Right now, whether it is right or wrong, 
I have a tough time playing with (Garnett) and having to play where 
(Garnett) makes the amount of money he makes, and I'm only going to 
make $71 million.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Marbury signed a six-year, $70.9 million contract extension with  
the Nets on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	That's not the Wolves' only beef with Marbury, though. They  
believe they lost Gugliotta to Phoenix because he didn't want to 
play with Marbury. 
</P>
<P>
	``His agent made it very clear to me, if we would have agreed to  
trade Stephon, Tommy would agree to come back to Minnesota,'' 
Saunders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wolves were unwilling to trade Marbury because they thought  
there was a chance they could re-sign him, either during the season 
or in July, after his three-year rookie contract expired. 
</P>
<P>
	While waiting for Gugliotta to make up his mind, the Wolves lost  
Porter, who signed with Miami because the Wolves couldn't address 
his contract situation until Gugliotta's was resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	So instead of having Garnett, Marbury and Gugliotta, three of  
the NBA's best players, as the nucleus of a team poised to become 
one of the NBA's elite, they have Garnett surrounded by a virtually 
brand new supporting cast. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Smith took Gugliotta's place at power forward, a shrewd move  
the Wolves made quickly when it appeared Gugliotta would reject 
their contract offer and sign with Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	Malik Sealy, Bobby Jackson and Dean Garrett all were added  
before the start of the season, and now Terrell Brandon inherits 
Marbury's job at point guard after coming over from Milwaukee in 
Thursday's nine-player trade. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wolves also have two first-round draft picks from the Nets,  
one this year and one down the road, with which to continue 
building a Western Conference contender. 
</P>
<P>
	If keeping Marbury was as unlikely as the Wolves make it seem,  
they once again appear to have come through with a solid Plan B, as 
they did by replacing Gugliotta with Smith, the No. 1 overall pick 
in the 1995 draft. 
</P>
<P>
	But it remains to be seen how this latest shakeup will affect  
their immediate future. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of Saunders' confidence comes from what he expects from  
Brandon. 
</P>
<P>
	Brandon, who is averaging 13.5 points and 6.9 assists per game  
this season -- compared to Marbury's 17.7 points and 9.3 assists -- 
was an All-Star in 1996 and '97 when he played for the Cleveland 
Cavaliers. 
</P>
<P>
	He was traded to the Bucks in a three-team deal before last  
season. When approached by Bucks management to re-sign, Brandon 
made it clear he had little interest in staying in Milwaukee. 
</P>
<P>
	An eight-year veteran, Brandon will be a free agent after the  
season, but indications are he will re-sign with the Wolves. Bill 
Duffy, who was a teammate of McHale's at the University of 
Minnesota for two seasons in the late 1970s, said Brandon is 
excited about joining the Wolves. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had no reservations whatsoever,'' Duffy said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
