<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 03:11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                            *Les Barcus    	
</P>
<P>
	SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) -- Les Barcus, inventor of an electronic  
pickup that could be used on an array of instruments from acoustic 
guitars to flutes, died March 4 at age 89. 
</P>
<P>
	The Barcus-Berry pickup, first produced in the 1960s, allowed  
clear amplification of traditional non-electric instruments and led 
to new possibilities in performance. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1963, John Berry brought him a violin, hoping Barcus could  
improve its recorded sound. 
</P>
<P>
	Barcus built a small transducer that picked up the energy  
reverberating from the strings as it passed to the bridge of the 
instrument. The invention led to formation of Barcus-Berry Inc., 
which began operation in 1964. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Muriel Bentley    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Muriel Bentley, a leading dancer with the  
American Ballet Theatre for more than 15 years, died Monday of 
heart failure. She was 82. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Bentley was best known for her work in choreographer Jerome  
Robbins' ``Fancy Free'' and her role as Lizzie Borden's ill-fated 
stepmother in Agnes de Mille's 1948 ``Fall River Legend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She also won critical acclaim for her acting in Antony Tudor's  
``Pillar of Fire'' and ``Shadow of the Wind'' and Ms. DeMille's 
``Tally Ho.'' 

</P>
<P>
                           *Peter Franken    	
</P>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Peter A. Franken, a pioneering laser  
researcher, died March 11 of liver disease. He was 70. 
</P>
<P>
	Franken, former director of the University of Arizona Optical  
Sciences Center, is considered the father of non-linear optics for 
having discovered that the color of a laser beam can be changed by 
passing it through a crystal. 
</P>
<P>
	His research included use of lasers for burn treatments,  
disposal of radioactive waste and optical methods for early 
detection of breast cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	He taught physics at Stanford and the University of Michigan  
before coming to the University of Arizona in 1973. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Sydney Lewis    	
</P>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Sydney Lewis, who with his wife pioneered  
the catalog showroom business and became an internationally known 
art collector, died Friday at age 79. 
</P>
<P>
	The co-founder and former chairman of Best Products Inc. had  
been in ill health for a number of years. The company, founded in 
1958, grew to sales of more than $2 billion annually. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis and his wife, Frances, became known throughout the world  
for their art deco and art nouveau collections, now housed in the 
Virginia Museum of Fine Arts' Sydney and Frances Lewis Gallery. 
</P>
<P>
	During the 1970s, the Lewises gave more than $11 million to  
colleges, universities, museums and medical schools. The couple 
also gave $9 million to Washington and Lee University to build a 
larger law school. 

</P>
<P>
                          *William McCurdy    	
</P>
<P>
	HARVARD, Mass. (AP) -- William W. McCurdy, who coached Harvard  
University men's track and field and cross country teams for three 
decades, died March 11 at his home. He was 82. 
</P>
<P>
	McCurdy began his coaching career at Harvard in 1950. His tenure  
included a 201-62-1 record for cross country, with 10 Greater 
Boston Championship titles. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Yehudi Menuhin    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Violinist Yehudi Menuhin, whose astonishing  
youthful virtuosity grew into one of the great musical talents of 
the 20th century, died Friday of pneumonia and heart failure. He 
was 82. 
</P>
<P>
	Menuhin was both an American citizen and a British subject, and  
was made a baron in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Menuhin was only 7 when he amazed a San Francisco audience with  
a brilliant debut violin performance. Four years later, he played 
at New York's Carnegie Hall with the New York Symphony Orchestra. 
By 13, he had already won accolades in Berlin, Paris and London. 
</P>
<P>
	During World War II, Menuhin gave 500 concerts for U.S. and  
Allied troops and for Red Cross funds. He offended many Israelis, 
however, by performing for Germans in Berlin only two years after 
the war. 
</P>
<P>
	He founded the Yehudi Menuhin School of Music at Stoke  
d'Abernon, Surrey, in 1963 to combine scholastic and musical 
training from an early age. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Bidu Sayao    	
</P>
<P>
	LINCOLNVILLE, Maine (AP) -- Bidu Sayao, the Brazilian-born  
soprano whose pure, silvery voice and personal charm made her one 
of the most beloved opera singers of the 1930s and '40s, died 
Friday from complications of pneumonia. She was 94. 
</P>
<P>
	Sayao's crystalline voice enchanted conductor Arturo Toscanini,  
and he trained her for her U.S. debut in Carnegie Hall in 1934. She 
made a triumphant Metropolitan Opera debut during the 1936-37 
season singing the title role of Massenet's ``Manon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her Met career covered 236 performances in 12 roles and lasted  
until 1952. It included such lyric and coloratura soprano roles as 
Mimi in Puccini's ``La Boheme,'' Melisande in Debussy's ``Pelleas 
and Melisande'' and Susanna in Mozart's ``The Marriage of Figaro.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sayao also made extensive concert tours, performing in 49  
states. To show her gratitude for her adopted homeland, Sayao sang 
for wounded soldiers returning from World War II. She became a U.S. 
citizen in 1959. 

</P>
<P>
                       *Dr. Eugene R. Sullivan    	
</P>
<P>
	MILTON, Mass. (AP) -- Dr. Eugene R. Sullivan, who established a  
system of mobile blood banks credited with saving many lives during 
World War II, died March 3. He was 89. 
</P>
<P>
	Sullivan, a microbiologist and specialist in internal medicine,  
was awarded the Legion of Merit for establishing the blood bank 
system while he was an officer in the Army Medical Corps during the 
campaigns in North Africa and Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	The blood transfusion units collected more than 35 tons of blood  
and distributed it to hospitals without ``known error, mishap, or 
spoilage,'' said the citation accompanying the award. 
</P>
<P>
	After the war, Sullivan directed clinical laboratories and the  
blood bank at the Veterans Administration Hospital in Boston's 
Jamaica Plain section. 
</P>
<P>
	He did research in the laboratory of Nobel laureate John Enders  
at Harvard and worked on an influenza vaccine in the laboratory of 
Tom Francis at the University of Michigan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990313.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 16:11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cubs' Wood Gets Off to Wild Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- Kerry Wood wasn't looking to do much in his  
1999 debut and he didn't. 
</P>
<P>
	The NL Rookie of the Year, finally recovered from an upper  
respiratory and gastrointestinal illness that sidelined him for the 
early part of spring training, couldn't find the plate Saturday as 
a Chicago Cubs' split squad lost to the Anaheim Angels 6-5. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was good to be out there,'' he said, still sweating from  
his in-game laps across the outfield. ``It's been a while.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 21-year-old right-hander allowed three runs and three hits  
in 1 1-3 innings, walking two and striking out none. He threw to 
nine batters, and 16 of his 26 pitches were balls. 
</P>
<P>
	On a sun-spalshed 80-degree afternoon, he threw just one pitch a  
batter missed -- not surprising since it was known in advance he 
would be throwing 100 percent fastballs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm pleased I got accomplished what I wanted to get  
accomplished,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wood, 13-6 with a 3.40 ERA last season, gave up an RBI single to  
Tim Salmon in the first but generally had his command. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the second, he lost it, throwing 10 consecutive balls at  
one point and prompting manager Jim Riggleman to make a trip to the 
mound. Wood threw a run-scoring wild pitch and gave up a sacrifice 
fly to Luis Rivera. 
</P>
<P>
	``A little out of whack across the body at the end,'' he said of  
his problem. ``I was trying to throw strikes. They could have hit 
me out of the park, I wouldn't have cared.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Riggleman knows Wood is a big part of the Cubs' season -- and  
their hope to win the World Series for the first time since 1908. 
When Wood was sidelined last September by elbow soreness, Chicago 
struggled to a 14-11 record following a 14-14 August, nearly 
blowing the NL's wild-card berth 
</P>
<P>
	``He was a little jittery,'' Riggleman said. ``Basically, I just  
wanted him to throw his pitches, throw his fastball, show him arm 
is healthy. Just let it fly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wood, pitching in a game for the first time since the division  
series-ending loss to Atlanta, said he had 90-95 percent of his 
velocity, and he would start throwing breaking balls -- ``spinners'' 
he called them -- before his next start. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the illness, he'll probably get only three or four  
more starts before the Cubs start the season at Houston, the NL 
Central champion, on April 6. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, he thinks he'll be ready to throw 100 pitches by his  
first regular-season start. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's probably stretching it a little,'' Riggleman said,  
``but we'll see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wood burst on the scene with his 20-strikeout game against the  
Astros last May 6, tying Roger Clemens' record for a nine-inning 
game. He wound up with 233 in 166 2-3 innings, and has 573 in 445 
innings in his pro career -- allowing just 24 homers. 
</P>
<P>
	He was rewarded with a raise from $170,000 to $690,000 a record  
for a player with less than one year of major league service. A 
bunch of Cubs' fans in the crowd on 7,411 at Tempe Diablo Stadium 
wore jerseys with his No. 34. 
</P>
<P>
	With all that, some would feel pressure. Wood says there's none.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to go out and throw 30 in a row as hard as I  
can,'' he said. ``I'll take it slow.'' 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* Winner Ken Hill pitched 2 2-3 innings, allowing a pair of  
unearned runs, four hits and four walks. Wood was the loser, and 
Shigetoshi Hasegawa allowed two hits in 2 2-3 shutout innings for 
the save. ... Alan Zinter homered for the Cubs. ... Anaheim won for 
only the third time in nine spring games. ... Salmon was 3-for-3 
with two RBIs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
