<HEADLINE> NCAA Midwest Regional Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Kentucky coach Tubby Smith and his players  
were still having a difficult time Saturday expressing their 
thoughts about the death of Wildcats signee John Stewart. 
</P>
<P>
	The 7-foot Stewart, who was from Lawrence North High School in  
Indianapolis, signed with the Wildcats in November. He died Friday 
night after collapsing during a state tournament game. 
</P>
<P>
	Kentucky players weren't told about Stewart's death until after  
their 82-60 victory over New Mexico State in the NCAA Midwest 
Regional game Friday night. Smith knew before the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to move on, but certainly having to hear it is  
depressing,'' Smith said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	At times, Smith said, he began visualizing himself ``coaching  
John'' during Friday night's game. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the three Kentucky players taking part in an interview  
session Saturday, only Scott Padgett answered when asked about the 
situation. Wayne Turner declined comment and Heshimu Evans just sat 
there with a blank expression. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody is still kind of in disbelief,'' Padgett said. ``His  
parents said (Stewart) would want us to come out and play our best 
for him and ourselves, which we will try to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kentucky plays Kansas on Sunday in the Superdome.  
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *LONELY COLES:* Miami of Ohio coach Charlie Coles treasures  
every moment on the court with his players. And the NCAA tournament 
provides some extra time. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have got to remember that not everyone gets to go to the  
NCAA every year, but I coach every year,'' Coles said. ``By being 
here, it extends the time I'm coaching. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to keep the season going because the spring, summer and  
fall are the loneliest times of the year for me,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles, whose team plays Utah on Sunday, also is appreciative for  
other reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	During a Mid-American Conference tournament game on Feb. 28,  
1998, Coles suffered a cardiac arrest. Physicians worked on him for 
20 minutes before he was taken to a hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	He is fully recovered and back to normal on the sideline, from  
where he watched his 10th-seeded Red Hawks beat Washington 59-58 in 
the first round of the NCAA Midwest Regional on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DUKE INVITATIONAL:* Many have said that this year's NCAA  
tournament is a race to see who will play Duke in the national 
title game. 
</P>
<P>
	Utah coach Rick Majerus agrees that Duke ``has done everything  
and done it well'' and has a good chance to win another title. 
</P>
<P>
	``My sister in her pool picked Duke to win it all,'' Majerus  
said. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FAMILIAR BEGINNINGS:* Roy Williams and Tubby Smith now coach  
two of the winningest teams in college basketball. The two 
49-year-old coaches have come a long way from coaching at North 
Carolina high schools. 
</P>
<P>
	The first job for Kansas' Williams was at Swannanoa (N.C.) Owen  
High School from 1973-78. Smith, who won the national championship 
last year with Kentucky, spent two years during that same span at 
Hoke County High in Raeford, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BETTER FEELING:* Kansas forward T.J. Pugh is in better shape  
than he was the first time the Jayhawks played Kentucky this 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	When the two teams played Dec. 1, it was only his second game  
back from ankle surgery. He was held to three points -- all on free 
throws -- and missed all four field goals in the 63-45 loss. 
</P>
<P>
	Pugh said his health ``wasn't too good at the time. I hope it  
will be better for me'' when the two teams play in the second round 
of the NCAA tournament Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
