<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Harnisch Likely Will Open Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SARASOTA, Fla. (AP) -- Pete Harnisch is following a predictable  
path toward his probable Opening Day start for the Cincinnati Reds. 
</P>
<P>
	Harnisch knew that after strong outings in his first two spring  
training appearances, he was due to struggle the next time out. On 
Friday, he labored through four innings in a 5-2 loss to the Tampa 
Bay Devil Rays. 
</P>
<P>
	He had entered the dreaded ``dead-arm'' period all pitchers go  
through for about a week-to-10 days before the season begins. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been through it 10 times,'' Harnisch said of the spring  
routine. ``Those are things you live through and learn from. I know 
what to expect. It's not a panic situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harnisch, however, is critical of his performance. He allowed  
two runs on five hits while walking four in four innings. He had 
retired 24 of the previous 27 batters he faced over eight scoreless 
innings. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think I had the focus I should have,'' he said. ``If  
you relax your concentration level, you're not going to get 
anything accomplished.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Harnisch, who overcame shoulder injuries and clinical  
depression to go 14-7 for the Reds last season, can use a subpar 
game as motivation. 
</P>
<P>
	``You get right back in there and work on stuff,'' he said.  
``I'm not proud of the way I threw the ball. ... But it happens. 
I'm not worried about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harnisch's work ethic is one of the reasons pitching coach Don  
Gullett feels the 32-year-old right-hander will be ready when the 
season starts. 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Jack McKeon hasn't officially named Harnisch the starter  
for the April 5 opener with the San Francisco Giants at Cinergy 
Field, but lefty Denny Neagle's slow progress from a sore shoulder 
makes it virtually certain. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's one of the hardest workers as far as conditioning and  
what he needs to do to get ready,'' pitching coach Don Gullett said 
of Harnisch. ``He's a professional.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
