<HEADLINE> Bergoust Wins Freestyle World Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEIRINGEN, Switzerland (AP) -- American Eric Bergoust, competing  
on the skis he used to win Olympic gold a year ago, added the world 
championship to his Olympic aerials title Saturday, and two other 
U.S. skiers collected bronze medals at the World Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was huge for me,'' said Bergoust, who is refining a  
technique which he hopes will make him the first skier to complete 
five twists in a jump. ``I've been working all summer just for this 
event. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew, because of the changes I'm working on in my technique,  
that it wouldn't be a good season results-wise on the World Cup ... 
so I focused on being ready for this one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bergoust, 29, a two-time Olympian from Missoula, Mont., landed a  
perfect jump in the final round after posting the highest-scoring 
jump in the first round. He finished with 253.04 points to 245.04 
for Christian Rijavec of Austria. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Pack, a former world junior aerials champion from Park City,  
Utah, who missed the 1998 season with a knee injury, earned the 
bronze medal with 238.40. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacqui Cooper of Australia, the 1997 world champion who failed  
to reach the Olympic finals a year ago, took her second women's 
title in a row. She received 197.83 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Hilde Lid of Norway was the silver medalist with 185.15, and  
Olympic champion Nikki Stone of Westborough, Mass., was third with 
180.71. 
</P>
<P>
	Bergoust said he prepared for the finals by breaking with his  
training routine and taking Friday off. 
</P>
<P>
	``I took about twice as much as I normally would, and I jumped  
myself into the ground,'' he said of his practice Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	That paid off Saturday.  
</P>
<P>
	``I ended up jumping out of my mind,'' Bergoust said. ``My  
second jump was perfect. I couldn't have done it any better.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
