<HEADLINE> U.S. Sen. Mack Announces Retirement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) -- Now that he's not seeking a third term,  
Sen. Connie Mack said today he is ready to begin a new life outside 
of politics when he leaves office in January 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's natural for someone approaching the age of 60 ... to say  
`OK, where do I go with the rest of my life?''' said Mack, 58, a 
Republican who was first elected to the Senate in 1988 after 
serving six years in the U.S. House. 
</P>
<P>
	Mack made his resignation official Saturday; the Associated  
Press reported earlier this month that he intended to retire. Mack 
said his only specific plan for the future is to finish out his 
term. After that, he will wait to see what grabs his interest. 
</P>
<P>
	Mack made his announcement before about 150 supporters.  
</P>
<P>
	The future will not include a run for another office, even if he  
is asked to join a bid for the White House, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not looking for being on anyone's ticket,'' Mack said.  
``My political career has two more years to go. I will not seek 
another office.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His decision is expected to generate a stampede to replace him,  
with a handful of Republicans and Democrats already considering a 
run. 
</P>
</TEXT>
