<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Workers' Comp. Payments Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Workers' compensation benefits and costs  
declined between 1995 and 1996, continuing a four-year trend, the 
National Academy of Social Insurance reported Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In its survey of state-run workers' compensation programs, the  
academy found payments declined 2.4 percent from $43.4 billion in 
1995 to $42.4 billion in 1996. These benefit payments include cash 
benefits that partially replace lost wages and medical care for 
workers with job-related injuries or illnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The costs to employers, such as premiums they pay for insurance  
and the cost of administering benefits by self-insured employers, 
dropped by 3.3 percent. In 1996, these costs fell to $55.2 billion 
from $57 billion in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts say several factors account for the fall in benefits and  
costs. In response to rapid increases in workers' compensation 
payments during the late 1980s and early 1990s, employers placed 
greater emphasis on safety, said Daniel Mont, a senior research 
associate at the academy. 
</P>
<P>
	``This helped work-related injury and illness rates on the job  
go down,'' Mont said. 
</P>
<P>
	Employers also increasingly began using managed care for  
workers' compensation and improved the management of disability 
cases, he said. And at the same time, many states tightened their 
compensation and benefit levels. 
</P>
<P>
	``Workers are not getting the same levels of benefits,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers' compensation benefit payments peaked in 1992 at $45.2  
billion. Employer costs associated with the programs peaked in 1993 
at $60.8 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Each state has its own workers' compensation program. They  
differ in terms of benefits, financing, administration and 
eligibility. 
</P>
<P>
	Nationally, benefits paid for medical care totaled about 41  
percent or $16.8 billion of all payments. Cash benefits to replace 
lost wages accounted for the other 59 percent or $25.6 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
