<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Catholic Org Names Ex-Vatican Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Raymond L. Flynn, the former mayor of Boston and  
U.S. ambassador to the Vatican, is taking a new job as head of a 
national Catholic political organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning Wednesday, Flynn will head the Catholic Alliance, a  
nonpartisan political action group for Catholic voters that was 
founded in 1995 as a branch of the conservative Christian 
Coalition. It is based in Oakton, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's doing what I believe in and what is consistent with the  
social justice position of the Catholic Church,'' Flynn said. 
</P>
<P>
	Flynn's job will be to encourage Catholics to participate in  
politics and provide a voice for what he termed ``working-class 
Americans'' on issues of social welfare, economic parity and 
opposition to abortion and euthanasia, he said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The group, which claims 125,000 members, broke from the  
Christian Coalition two years ago. Its former president, Keith 
Fournier, recently stepped down and board members elected Flynn 
earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Flynn, a Democrat, was mayor from 1984 to 1993. He was U.S.  
ambassador to the Vatican from 1993 until 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year he ran unsuccessfully for the Democratic nomination to  
the House seat vacated by former U.S. Rep. Joseph P. Kennedy II, 
D-Mass. Flynn said his opposition to abortion played a role in his 
loss in that race to Michael Capuano, who won the general election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
