<DOCNO> APW19990313.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 01:23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iowa Prepares for Arkansas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Two years ago, Jess Settles could barely get out  
of bed, let alone dunk a basketball or shoot a 3-pointer. A 
debilitating back injury seemingly doomed a promising future. 
</P>
<P>
	Through determination, patience and the help of the NCAA,  
Settles has returned to the court with a fresh perspective as he 
and his Iowa teammates prepared for today's second-round game 
against Arkansas. 
</P>
<P>
	``As athletes, sometimes you enjoy it more after it's over,''  
Iowa coach Tom Davis said Friday. ``It was over for Jess, and all 
of a sudden he's got it back. He enjoys it more because of coming 
back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Settles averaged 15 points in each of his first three seasons  
with Iowa and nearly jumped to the NBA before back problems 
sidelined him for all but three games of the 1996-97 season and all 
of 1997-98. 
</P>
<P>
	Still hungry to play, Settles was granted a medical hardship  
last fall, and he gradually worked his way into the starting 
lineup. His 17 points in Iowa's first-round victory over 
Alabama-Birmingham in the NCAA West Regional reminded people why he 
was a three-time all-Big Ten selection. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't know if I'd get that second chance,'' Settles said.  
``You always dream as a kid of playing college basketball. I 
probably took it for granted. I just thank God for the second 
chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His longevity has made Settles easy fodder for his teammates,  
some of whom watched him playing for Iowa while they were still in 
junior high. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of rumors going around on how old he is,''  
junior Jacob Jaacks said. ``We call him 30-something like that old 
TV show. It's kind of like your mom or your grandma. You don't want 
to ask him what his age is. You might offend him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the record, Settles is 24, and he's treating his sixth  
season with the Hawkeyes like it was his freshman year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I needed basketball a whole lot more back then,'' he said. ``I  
was such a driven person trying to maximize my potential. To have 
it taken away from you, you're forced basically to deal with 
reality. I'm a lot more thankful. I'm as driven, but I don't need 
it as much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Arkansas coach Nolan Richardson remembers Settles as a talented  
sophomore on a team that the Razorbacks beat 101-92 in the 
championship game of the 1994 Rainbow Classic. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a great player,'' Richardson said. ``I remember him  
playing against our (defending) national championship team, so he's 
been around for a long, long, long time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While fourth-seeded Arkansas (23-10) and No. 5 seed Iowa (19-9)  
get reacquainted in the first of two games at McNichols Arena, 
ninth-seeded New Mexico (25-8) will try to derail top-seeded 
Connecticut (29-2). 
</P>
<P>
	It's a daunting task that Lobos coach Dave Bliss couldn't  
envision while watching Connecticut dismantle St. John's in the 
championship game of the Big East tournament last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``The start of the St. John's game is the most impressive 10  
minutes in college basketball I've seen this year,'' Bliss said 
Friday. ``If I'd have known we were going to have to play against 
them, I'd have thrown up on the spot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Connecticut coach Jim Calhoun knows the feeling. He missed the  
Huskies' first-round victory with virus-like symptoms, but hoped to 
return to the bench today. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just need to get a little more rest,'' Calhoun said Friday.  
``I'm going to get another shot so I can sleep a little better, but 
obviously I plan to be here at 12 o'clock to face a good New Mexico 
team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New Mexico is in the NCAA tournament for the seventh time in the  
last nine years, but will be playing a No. 1 seed for the first 
time. The Lobos aren't given much of a chance of beating the 
heavily favored Huskies. 
</P>
<P>
	``They probably play at the fastest speed of any team in the  
country,'' Bliss said. ``They have some very high-profile stars and 
they are on a mission to accomplish what a lot of very good teams 
try to accomplish.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That would be reaching the Final Four -- the only missing piece  
on a resume that in the '90s has been one of college basketball's 
most impressive. Connecticut has made three trips to the round of 
eight (1990, 1995, 1998) and three other times reached the round of 
16 (1991, 1994, 1996). 
</P>
<P>
	``With this team, we've been through the hard times,'' point  
guard Khalid El-Amin said. ``We're a lot more mature than last 
year. Once we play the way we're capable of playing, the Final Four 
should take care of itself.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
