<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fire Victims Sue Culkin's Mother </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Two survivors of a deadly high-rise fire that  
started in the home of Macauley Culkin's mother are suing for $20 
million each and the mother of a woman who died wants $40 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Lisa Percansky, 36, and her sister, Romy, 27, residents of the  
40th floor of the 51-story Manhattan building, made it down to the 
30th floor during the fire. A neighbor then pulled them into his 
apartment, where they waited to be rescued on an open-air terrace. 
</P>
<P>
	``As they walked down, they were literally tripping over people  
who were passed out in the stairwell,'' said their lawyer, Lawrence 
Wilson. ``Psychologically, it was very traumatic for them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also suing Culkin's mother and the building's owners in the  
joint filing is Sarah B. Chappell of Gates, N.C., whose daughter 
Wanda, 40, died in the Dec. 23 fire. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire, which killed four, started in one of two 19th-floor  
apartments occupied by Culkin children and their mother, Patricia 
Brentrup. The lawsuit accused Brentrup of negligence for allegedly 
leaving the door ajar as she fled the burning apartment, allowing 
smoke to fill spread through the building. 
</P>
</TEXT>
