<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Detroit Upset Focuses Ohio State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- There's going to be a reunion when Detroit  
and Ohio State clash in the second round of the NCAA South 
Regional. 
</P>
<P>
	Two Ohio State starters -- Ken Johnson and Jason Singleton -- are  
from Detroit. Both were unsuccessfully recruited by Detroit coach 
Perry Watson, who has four starters from the Motor City. 
</P>
<P>
	Jermaine Jackson, the Midwestern Collegiate Conference Player of  
the Year, was Johnson's host on a recruiting visit to Detroit. When 
he learned Johnson wanted to go to a larger Big Ten school and 
attend school away from his hometown, Jackson said that their teams 
would meet someday. 
</P>
<P>
	Today is that day, and a trip to Knoxville, Tenn., for the  
regional semifinals will be on the line in the RCA Dome when 
fourth-seeded Ohio State (24-8) seeks to uphold the prestige of the 
Big Ten against 12th-seeded Detroit (25-5) of the lightly regarded 
MCC. 
</P>
<P>
	Ninth-seeded Oklahoma State (23-10) plays top-seeded Auburn  
(28-3) in today's other second-round game. Today's winners will 
clash in the regional semifinal. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-11 Johnson is a far different player than the one  
Watson attempted to recruit. He finished second in the Big Ten in 
blocked shots and added five to his season total in Thursday's 
72-58 victory over Murray State. 
</P>
<P>
	``All my life, I was told I was a project,'' he said. ``I was  
tired of it. I went out to work on my game to prove I'm a player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson was a teammate of Singleton on an AAU team one summer,  
and Singleton's school, Southgate Aquinas, is near Detroit 
Southwestern, where Watson coached for 13 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Watson's team has produced an upset in the opening round of the  
tournament two consecutive years. Last year, the Titans ousted St. 
John's and then lost to Purdue of the Big Ten. This year, Detroit 
eliminated 11-time national champion UCLA. 
</P>
<P>
	Watson doesn't anticipate his team will be in awe of playing a  
Big Ten team. He says they've prepared for the physical game in 
summer workouts that include competing with NBA players from the 
area like Jalen Rose, Grant Hill, Jerry Stackhouse, Robert Traylor 
and Chris Webber. 
</P>
<P>
	``One thing about city kids, especially in our situation,''  
Watson said. ``They're not intimidated by playing against anybody. 
Playing with those guys -- not saying they beat them or anything -- 
but at least they get a chance to compete against them. We're 
willing to play anybody anywhere, and we've done that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, Detroit beat Big Ten champion Michigan State three  
consecutive years until the Titans came off the Spartans' schedule 
for this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Oklahoma State has no problem being cast as the  
underdog against Auburn, ranked No. 4 in the final Associated Press 
poll. 
</P>
<P>
	``We kind of like the role,'' guard Adrian Peterson said Friday.  
``It makes you go out and play loose, like to have nothing to lose. 
... Auburn, there is a team that has everything to lose, being the 
No. 1 seed. It's the kind of a role you can get some positive 
things out of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Peterson's coach Eddie Sutton isn't certain about that.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was a little surprised when I saw how much we were the  
underdog,'' Sutton said. ``But I can understand why after looking 
at them on film. Auburn is a terrific basketball team. We have a 
big task ahead of us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cowboys will have to slow down Auburn to produce the upset.  
The Tigers are averaging 81.8 points, and they're no slouches on 
defense, having produced an average of more than 20 turnovers per 
game while holding opponents to 60.9 points. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we've played a team as athletic as Auburn is or  
who thrives off its press like Auburn does,'' Peterson said. 
``We've played teams that press 40 or 50 percent of the game, but 
Auburn presses just about the whole game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sutton's teams play more of a halfcourt game and will likely try  
to slow the game down. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they slow it down, we are going to have to execute on both  
ends of the floor,'' Auburn guard Doc Robinson said. ``We like to 
play up-tempo, but we feel we can be a pretty good halfcourt team, 
too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``When you get into the NCAA tournament, every team is good or  
they wouldn't be here,'' said Sutton, who is in the tournament as a 
coach for the 18th time since 1974 and is 10th on the tournament 
victory list with 29. ``Somebody has to be a favorite and somebody 
has to be the underdog.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
