<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 01:23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arizona Exits Early Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Arizona coach Lute Olson doesn't want seniors  
A.J. Bramlett and Jason Terry getting stuck with the same ``early 
exit'' tag that so many of his Wildcats carried for their NCAA 
misadventures. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to make one thing clear: This group of seniors is 11-3  
in the NCAA tournament,'' Olson said after the fourth-seeded 
Wildcats were upset 61-60 by 13th-seeded Oklahoma on Friday. ``They 
can't do anything about what happened eight years ago or four years 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``These seniors have given us 11 wins and three losses. Most  
programs across the country would be happy with that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the Wildcats have made a habit of getting knocked out early.  
</P>
<P>
	Oklahoma (21-10) will play fifth-seeded North Carolina-Charlotte  
(23-10) in the second round. The fifth-seeded 49ers defeated 
12th-seeded Rhode Island 81-70 in overtime earlier Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Top-seed Michigan State (30-4), which survived a sluggish start  
to rout Mount St. Mary's 76-53, the Spartans' 19th straight win, 
plays Ole Miss on Sunday at the Bradley Center. The short and 
speedy Rebels (20-12) beat Villanova 72-70 for their third straight 
20-win season, a first in the program's 89-year history. 
</P>
<P>
	Four times in the 1990s, the Wildcats have strutted into the  
NCAA tournament as one of the top five seeds. And four times 
they've been sent packing in the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest one might be the toughest to swallow, though.  
Oklahoma's 61-60 upset came on a tip-in with 21 seconds left that 
may or may not have been offensive goaltending. 
</P>
<P>
	After Eric Martin missed a 3-pointer for Oklahoma (21-10),  
Eduardo Najera followed with a layup attempt. While Najera says his 
shot was good, Ryan Humphrey admits he got a hand on it, and it was 
Humphrey who got credit for the basket in the official 
play-by-play. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought I made the shot,'' said Najera, who led the Sooners  
with 17 points and 13 rebounds. ``It doesn't matter who touched it. 
</P>
<P>
	``All that matters is we won.''  
</P>
<P>
	And that the Wildcats (22-7) lost.  
</P>
<P>
	Arizona had one last chance to win the game, but Terry missed a  
fallaway 10-footer with about three seconds left. Then complete 
chaos set in. Freshman Richard Jefferson missed a one-handed 
tip-in, got the rebound and missed another shot as he fell in the 
lane at the buzzer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We put it in the hands of the guy that got us here,'' Olson  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sooners -- the last at-large team to get a bid -- stormed the  
court, hugging each other and jumping around. Terry, the Pac-10 
player of the year, was stunned. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was definitely disbelief,'' said Terry, who scored 15  
points. ``The last couple of seconds, I was reminiscing about all 
the good days. Today wasn't one of them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite winning a national title in 1997, there haven't been  
many good days in the first round for the Wildcats. They lost their 
first game as the No. 3 seed in 1992, No. 2 seed in 1993 and No. 5 
seed in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the Wildcats have been in the tournament every year  
since 1985, they've failed to get out of the first round seven 
times during that span. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't believe we went out like this,'' Terry said. ``I'm  
still thinking like we've got practice tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's tough to go out this way,'' Bramlett agreed. ``But we  
played our hearts out, right down to the last second.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The top-seeded Spartans started sluggish and finished sloppy.  
But in between they displayed enough talent to keep Mount St. 
Mary's, the smallest school in the NCAA tournament, from pulling 
off the biggest upset. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spartans won despite getting just eight points from  
All-American point guard Mateen Cleaves. 
</P>
<P>
	Mount St. Mary's (15-15), a school of 1,309 students in central  
Maryland -- or 32 times smaller than Michigan State -- stayed with 
the Spartans until Cleaves scored his first points with 7:25 left 
in the first half. 
</P>
<P>
	``They came out and made some big shots,'' Cleaves said. ``We  
didn't take them lightly, they just played well early. We knew if 
we wanted to pull away from them, we had to step up our defense.''	   They did, outrebounding the Mountaineers 46-22. 
</P>
<P>
	``We weren't sharp early, but there was a little nervousness,''  
Spartans coach Tom Izzo said. ``I've been saying all year there are 
new things we need to learn how to handle and deal with. I'm sure 
being a No. 1 seed was one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	North Carolina-Charlotte overcame yet another obstacle in a  
season of hurdles. The 49ers, who lost players to injury, illness 
and international paperwork problems this season, overcame Rhode 
Island and sophomore sensation Lamar Odom. 
</P>
<P>
	``They did a great job on me today,'' said Odom, who finished  
with 16 points and 12 rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Ole Miss, which lost in the first round the last two seasons,  
had never won an NCAA tournament game. 
</P>
<P>
	``It really felt good to get that monkey off our back,'' senior  
guard Michael White said. ``When the buzzer went off it was a 
feeling of relief. It's a great feeling.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
