<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bordick Plans To Steal More Bases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- Slick-fielding shortstop Mike  
Bordick added a new dimension to his game last year, recording 
career highs in homers and doubles while hitting a respectable 
.260. 
</P>
<P>
	This season he plans to do some damage with his legs, too.  
</P>
<P>
	Bordick spent a good deal of his offseason adhering to a  
torturous training program devised by Baltimore Orioles strength 
and conditioning coach Tim Bishop. Bordick was a regular at Camden 
Yards in January and February, spending hours each day working with 
weights and on the treadmill. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really focused on running this offseason,'' he said. ``Maybe  
I can help by stealing a few bases, scoring from second or going 
from first to third in a single. Hopefully I can give the team more 
speed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The results have been on full display this spring.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's in better shape and he's faster,'' Orioles manager Ray  
Miller noted. ``I expect him to be as good as he was last year, 
even better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cal Ripken's storied reign as Baltimore's shortstop ended when  
Bordick signed as a free agent before the 1997 season. He was 
acquired primarily because of his prowess in the field, and the 
Orioles figured any contribution Bordick made at the plate would be 
a bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	Last season, he gave them more than they bargained for. In  
addition to compiling a career-best .990 fielding percentage, 
second among AL shortstops behind Cleveland's Omar Vizquel, Bordick 
had 13 homers and 29 doubles. His 51 RBIs were three short of his 
career high. 
</P>
<P>
	In the process, Bordick dispelled the notion that he's a  
one-dimensional player. 
</P>
<P>
	Not that there's anything wrong with that.  
</P>
<P>
	``People are going to say what they want. As long as they say  
one good thing, I'm happy,'' Bordick said. ``My whole career, I've 
always felt that if I can't drive a run in, I can feel good about 
stopping a run from scoring. You take that approach, you're going 
to help your team win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bordick, 33, spent the first seven years as a slap-hitter,  
spraying the ball the opposite way whenever possible. Last year he 
decided to take aim at left field when given an inside pitch to 
hit. 
</P>
<P>
	He never before hit two homers in a game, but last year he did  
it twice. Bordick didn't always go deep, though -- he led the AL 
with 15 sacrifice bunts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think everybody wants to be a well-rounded player. I take  
pride in my defense and work hard at that, but I take pride in my 
offense, too,'' he said. ``I like bunting and setting things up for 
the other guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bordick is signed through this season, but if he reaches 500  
at-bats the Orioles will be obligated to sign him for the year 
2000. The point is moot; Bordick said he wants to finish his career 
in Baltimore, and Miller can't imagine what life would be like 
without having him in the middle of the infield. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously (shortstop Derek) Jeter and (Alex) Rodriguez get all  
the hype, but every manager you talk to will tell you Bordy is 
money in the bank. He just gets the outs for you. Plus, he's 
getting better and better offensively,'' Miller said. ``He can play 
for me as long as he wants.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990313.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 20:23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heavyweights Return to the Garden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Nothing quickens the pulse of Madison Square  
Garden quite like a heavyweight championship fight, and there was a 
rare air of extra electricity Saturday night for the Evander 
Holyfield-Lennox Lewis bout. 
</P>
<P>
	A celebrity-studded sellout crowd of 21,284, paying prices from  
$100 to $1,500, turned the Garden into the center of the boxing 
universe for the first time in a long time. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first undisputed heavyweight title fight at the arena  
since Muhammad Ali-Joe Frazier in 1971, and the first sellout for a 
fight of any type in the big arena since Roberto Duran fought Davey 
Moore in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	``Four hundred bucks will get you upstairs. Anything good  
downstairs, that's at least $1,500,'' a scalper said outside the 
``World's Most Famous Arena.'' There were plenty of takers, too, as 
would-be customers appeared to outnumber loose tickets by a wide 
margin. 
</P>
<P>
	Mick Jagger and Keith Richards of the Rolling Stones, John F.  
Kennedy Jr., Jack Nicholson, Jerry Seinfeld, Donald Trump, Sean 
``Puffy'' Combs, Bill Parcells, Patrick Ewing, Spike Lee and 
Michael Douglas were among the celebrities. 
</P>
<P>
	For each of them, there were legions of wannabees. Hipsters in  
thousand-dollar suits, glamorous women who turned dozens of heads 
at a time, actors and models complimenting each other on their 
looks. 
</P>
<P>
	This was not the cell phone and business suit crowd that  
frequents Knicks and Rangers games. This was more of a cash crowd, 
the type of people that pull out diamond-studded money clips of 
$100 bills when buying their hot dogs and popcorn. 
</P>
<P>
	A large and vocal contingent of Brits were in attendance, too,  
having made the trip overseas to cheer on Lewis, a Jamaican who 
grew up in Canada and fights out of England. 
</P>
<P>
	Even the scalper ranks were speckled with a few fellows whose  
roots were closer to York than New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any spares?'' a man with a cockney accents asked, which earned  
him little but quizzical stares. 
</P>
<P>
	New York and Madison Square Garden were once synonymous with  
championship boxing, but that was decades ago when the old Garden 
was located 18 blocks uptown. In the years since, the casinos in 
Las Vegas and Atlantic City have monopolized the sport's biggest 
bouts because of the type of high-rolling crowd it attracts. 
</P>
<P>
	The gambling for this fight was kept underground since wagering  
on sports is illegal everywhere except Nevada. In Las Vegas, 
Holyfield was a slight favorite. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the pre-fight hype recalled the 1971 Frazier-Ali fight,  
a classic that was photographed for Life magazine by Frank Sinatra. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're happy to get the opportunity to fight there,''  
Holyfield said of the Garden. ``That's how you become a part of 
what they call history.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990313.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 19:41:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Americans Win Skating Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLOOMFIELD HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- There was no doubting who were  
the most popular winners Saturday in final competition at the ISU 
Junior Grand Prix of Figure Skating. 
</P>
<P>
	Cheered on by a loud capacity crowd at their home Detroit  
Skating Club, Americans Jamie Silverstein and Justin Pekarek capped 
an outstanding season by winning the dance championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Vincent Restencourt of France overtook Russians Ilia Klimkin and  
Alexei Vasilevsky to win the men's gold. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's Viktoria Volchkova jumped from third to first among the  
women. 
</P>
<P>
	Ukranians Yulia Obertas and Dmitry Palamarchuk skated to the  
pairs title. 
</P>
<P>
	But the crowd came to see Silverstein and Pekarek, and they  
weren't disappointed. Probably skating as juniors for the last 
time, the duo added the Grand Prix title to the U.S. and world 
junior championships they already hold. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel very relieved because we've had such a good season, and  
I didn't want to spoil anything,'' said Silverstein, 15. ``I was 
especially nervous for this because it was here, but it went 
well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pekarek, 17, said he felt relaxed through the entire weekend,  
especially once he and Silverstein led following Friday's 
compulsory and original dances. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted a really good free dance to go out,'' Pekarek said.  
``The hometown crowd really helped.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both skaters said they were amazed at their improvement the past  
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just wanted to just move up as much as we could,'' Pekarek  
said. ``This far exceeded our expectations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Italians Federica Faiella and Luciana Milo finished second, and  
Natalia Romaniuta and Daniel Barantsev of Russia were third. 
</P>
<P>
	This was the last major international competition before the  
world championships begin March 22 in Helsinki, Finland. 
</P>
<P>
	Klimkin and Vasilevsky were 1-2 after Friday's men's short  
program, but both fell in Saturday's free skate. 
</P>
<P>
	Restencourt also fell landing a jump, but still had the highest  
marks from all seven judges. 
</P>
<P>
	Klimkin and Restencourt had finished 1-2, respectively, at the  
world junior championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Volchkova, who finished third in this year's world and European  
championships, performed a flawless free skate to the theme from 
``Gone With The Wind'' and won the women's gold. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirteen-year-old Sarah Hughes of Great Neck, N.Y., who will  
compete for the U.S. team in the world championships, held on to 
second place while reigning world junior champion Daria Timoshenko 
of Russia was third. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian Irina Nikolaeva, who led after Friday's short program,  
fell four times in her free skate and finished fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	Obertas and Palamarchuk added the Grand Prix pairs championship  
to the world junior crown they already hold. Americans Laura Handy 
and Paul Binnebose, second at the worlds, were runners-up again and 
Viktoria Maksiuta and Vladislav Zhovnirsky jumped from fourth to 
third. 
</P>
</TEXT>
