<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Celtics Sign Potapenko </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Two days after acquiring Vitaly Potapenko from the  
Cleveland Cavaliers, the Boston Celtics announced Saturday the 
signing of the center-forward to a long-term contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the deal were not disclosed, but The Boston Globe  
reported Saturday that the contract was expected be for around $33 
million over six years. 
</P>
<P>
	Potapenko, 23, was acquired by the Celtics on Thursday for  
Andrew DeClercq and a first-round draft choice. 
</P>
<P>
	``He gives us a work ethic and an inside presence that is very  
much needed, particularly on the defensive end,'' Celtics coach 
Rick Pitino said in a statement. ``Vitaly is a young, strong, big 
man with great upside.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-10 Ukrainian-born Potapenko played his first game  
with Boston on Friday, a 93-83 loss to Detroit. He had eight 
points, three rebounds and two assists in 21 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	In 17 games with Cleveland this season, he averaged 8.4 points  
and 5.5 rebounds. He was selected by Cleveland as the 12th pick 
overall in the 1996 draft. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the trade, Cleveland gets a first-round draft pick  
between now and 2001. The Cavs have the option of when to use the 
pick. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the terms of the deal, Cleveland's pick cannot be among  
the top three this year. A pick in the following two years would be 
unprotected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
