<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 00:41:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Night Slalom Called Off in Spain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SIERRA NEVADA, Spain (AP) -- Women World Cup slalom skiers called  
it taking a stand. Spanish World Cup organizers called it lack of 
motivation. 
</P>
<P>
	After a chaotic first slalom run disrupted by powerful winds and  
rutted snow at the World Cup finals, organizers -- faced with a 
boycott -- canceled the race altogether. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to say no sometimes because we had so many bad races  
this year, especially in slalom,'' said Sweden's Pernilla Wiberg, 
one of the four skiers with a chance to win the season slalom 
title. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even if I'm a little bit disappointed because I had the chance  
to win this cup, I know for the women's World Cup in general it's a 
good decision,'' Wiberg said. ``We have to say no to running in 
such bad and dangerous conditions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Slalom racers often complain they must ski in difficult  
conditions that would never be contemplated in the high-speed 
downhill or super-G. The women agreed that only two or three World 
Cup slaloms have been satisfactory all season. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's so sad,'' Spela Pretnar of Slovenia said. ``I had the  
impression they were playing with us. All year it's been bad, it's 
a bad commercial for skiing. And today was just plain dangerous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Race chief Eduardo Valenzuela, meanwhile, said a lack of  
motivation was behind the women's strike threat. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the women's teams are not interested in having more  
races because the (overall) World Cup title has already been 
decided,'' Valenzuela said. ``I feel they are not willing to run 
the races. 
</P>
<P>
	``On the men's side, they want to race. The overall rankings are  
not settled yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The women, however, insisted they are more than willing to race,  
and hoped the slalom could somehow be rescheduled. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not trying to be rude, we just want to run in better  
conditions,'' American Kristina Koznick said. ``And if not, we'll 
wait. We would rather it was postponed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	FIS -- the world governing body of skiing -- decided to cancel the  
race and not reschedule it, saying there was no time left in the 
season, which ends Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wiberg, chosen to speak for the other skiers, said the course  
was not well prepared. 
</P>
<P>
	Valenzuela, who insisted course conditions were adequate, said  
organizers followed FIS instructions on preparing the course and 
had been grooming the course for the past two months. 
</P>
<P>
	He said workers followed FIS instructions and mixed the new snow  
with the old, which he said should not have been done. 
</P>
<P>
	``In my opinion, we could have carried out the race,''  
Valenzuela said. ``Maybe not in prefect conditions, but good 
enough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Veteran French racer Florence Masnada said she could not recall  
a race being wiped out in this fashion. 
</P>
<P>
	FIS spokesman Christian Knauth said the decision had nothing to  
do with the skiers' threatened boycott. 
</P>
<P>
	``During inspection from the athletes and jury, the jury made  
the decision it's not OK for the second run,'' Knauth said. ``The 
cancellation was not about the activities of the athletes. It was a 
jury decision on the hill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The cancellation means Sabine Egger of Austria -- who entered as  
the overall point leader in slalom -- picks up her first World Cup 
season slalom title. Wiberg, just 10 points behind, settled for 
runnerup in the season standings. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the day, fellow Austrian Alexandra Meissnitzer  
claimed the season super-G title when similar weather wiped out 
that race. 
</P>
<P>
	FIS said it hoped to run today's races as scheduled -- the men's  
slalom and women's giant slalom. In the men's slalom, Norway's 
Lasse Kjus could wrap up the overall World Cup title, the most 
important of the season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
