<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Houston Bidder Promises NFL Sellout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Houston businessman Bob McNair has guaranteed  
sellouts at every home game for five years should he get an NFL 
expansion football team, a pledge that would prevent local 
television blackouts. 
</P>
<P>
	NFL officials, preparing to gather in Phoenix on Sunday for a  
meeting to decide their next expansion team, declined comment. 
</P>
<P>
	McNair's audacious promise, reported by Houston television  
station KRIV late Friday and the Houston Chronicle in Saturday 
editions, is aimed at gaining an upper hand over Los Angeles, which 
has more than a 3-1 edge in the number of TV households. 
</P>
<P>
	McNair said he would devise a system to give to charity any  
tickets not sold by the deadline for a blackout. NFL rules dictate 
that if a game is not a sellout 72 hours before kickoff, it is not 
televised within 75 miles. 
</P>
<P>
	However, network officials have said they would prefer that the  
NFL be in a town that can guarantee sellouts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm that confident we will succeed,'' McNair said. ``We're  
telling television that you're not going to suffer blackouts in 
Houston. That should be a big challenge to Los Angeles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two groups in Los Angeles are competing for a team. Hollywood  
dealmaker Michael Ovitz wants to build a new stadium in suburban 
Carson atop a waste dump. Real estate developer Ed Roski and 
billionaire Eli Broad want to remodel the L.A. Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	McNair has been stepping up his challenges to Los Angeles  
television market. 
</P>
<P>
	``You hear a lot of talk about the fact that Houston is the  
11th-rated media market and Los Angeles is the second-rated 
market,'' McNair told KRIV. ``That's very superficial. That doesn't 
tell the whole story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, he distributed a report to team owners  
showing that while Los Angeles has a larger base of viewers who 
watch NFL games, having a home team in that city does not produce a 
large gain over having a new team in Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	Using network records for the 1993 and 1994 seasons, the  
incremental gain of a Los Angeles Raiders game was only about 
28,000 more than the incremental gain of a Houston Oilers' game. 
</P>
<P>
	Both cities lost their NFL franchises in 1995, with Los Angeles  
also losing the Rams. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Texas' two U.S. senators and the region's seven House  
members have sent NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue a letter asking 
that he hold to his word. 
</P>
<P>
	Almost three years ago, Tagliabue stood in Houston's City Hall  
and said the city would likely get another football team if it put 
together a state-of-the-art stadium deal. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the group -- led by Republican Sens. Phil Gramm and  
Kay Bailey Hutchison -- implored the league to give Houston the 32nd 
franchise over Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	The letter reminded Tagliabue of his comments May 29, 1996,  
after meeting with Gramm, then-Mayor Bob Lanier, Harris County 
Judge Robert Eckels and others in wake of the Oilers' departure for 
Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	The letter said Houston's proposed $310 million,  
retractable-roof stadium ``meets all the requirements set by you.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990313.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 07:23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Samaranch Reputation on the Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- Juan Antonio Samaranch surveyed his  
booming Olympic empire and liked what he saw -- billions of 
television and sponsorship dollars, dozens of cities vying to stage 
the games, the five-ring logo spreading to all corners of the 
globe. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch figured all this was too good to give up. So rather  
than retire, he decided to stay for another term as IOC president 
until 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	``The happiest moments of my life are when I come to the  
headquarters of the IOC and open the door to my office,'' he said 
then. 
</P>
<P>
	That was two years ago.  
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch has a different perspective now.  
</P>
<P>
	His credibility, future and legacy will all be on the line when  
the International Olympic Committee holds a watershed meeting this 
week to deal with the biggest crisis in its 105-year history. 
</P>
<P>
	The 78-year-old Spaniard has become the lightning rod for  
criticism in the vote-buying scandal surrounding Salt Lake City's 
successful bid for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	While the Olympics have endured world wars, terrorism and  
political boycotts, the IOC is battling for survival against an 
onslaught of condemnation. 
</P>
<P>
	In the toughest challenge of his 19-year presidency, Samaranch  
is under tremendous pressure to deliver on his promises to clean 
house and enact major reforms. If he fails, his position will 
become untenable. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he is going to retain the presidency and remain in power,  
he has to resolve this,'' British IOC member Craig Reedie said. 
``The ball is in his court.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With critics outside the IOC clamoring for his resignation and  
some officials within the committee now speculating about a 
possible early departure, Samaranch knows the stakes are high. 
</P>
<P>
	``I consider (the session) one of the most important in our  
history, and the most important of my presidency,'' he said in a 
letter to IOC members last week. ``Our duty requires that we take 
concrete decisions, in some case painful ones, for the whole world 
will be watching.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC general assembly, which convenes Wednesday and Thursday  
after a two-day meeting of the executive board, will be asked to 
take the following steps: 
</P>
<P>
	-- Endorse Samaranch, either by secret ballot or, more likely, by  
public acclamation. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Ratify the expulsions of six IOC members accused of receiving  
cash payments or other improper inducements from Salt Lake bidders. 
Four other implicated members have resigned, 10 received warnings, 
three were exonerated and one died. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Set up an ethics committee, including outside members, and  
establish a code of conduct. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Create a reform commission including outside experts to study  
structural changes of the IOC. Samaranch has mentioned Henry 
Kissinger as a possible panel member. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Adopt a new Olympic bidding and site-selection process. For  
the 2006 Winter Games, member visits to bid cities would be banned 
and the general assembly would select the site after the field is 
narrowed to two finalists by a small panel. 
</P>
<P>
	There is little doubt that Samaranch will win a vote of  
confidence from the 90-plus members, most of whom he appointed to 
the IOC. 
</P>
<P>
	But the expulsions could pose a risk. Samaranch had hoped  
members would resign rather than be kicked out. 
</P>
<P>
	But six are fighting dismissal: Agustin Arroyo (Ecuador),  
Jean-Claude Ganga (Congo Republic), Gen. Zein El Abdin Ahmed Abdel 
Gadir (Sudan), Lamine Keita (Mali), Sergio Santander (Chile) and 
Seiuli Paul Wallwork (Western Samoa). 
</P>
<P>
	They will be given 20 minutes each to defend themselves in front  
of the assembly before facing expulsion votes. 
</P>
<P>
	Expulsion requires a two-thirds majority, and it's possible some  
of the six could find enough sympathy among the rank-and-file to 
defeat the motion. 
</P>
<P>
	In that case, Samaranch and members of the executive board would  
be under pressure to resign. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC avoided one potential crisis by deciding not to seek the  
expulsion of South Korea's Kim Un-yong, a powerful executive board 
member and the highest-ranking official implicated in the Salt Lake 
affair. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim, accused of using his influence to land jobs in  
telecommunications and music for his two children, escaped with a 
severe warning from the IOC's inquiry panel. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim has suggested he is the victim of a plot to undermine his  
chances of becoming IOC president. Had he faced expulsion, he could 
have provoked vicious infighting at the session. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if all of Samaranch's proposals are approved at the  
meeting, it's uncertain whether the actions will be enough to 
restore public confidence in the scandal-shaken IOC and its 
leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	The corporate sponsors who finance the Olympics are restless and  
putting pressure on the IOC to act decisively or risk a rebellion. 
One company, John Hancock insurance, has canceled negotiations with 
NBC for $20 million in Olympic advertising. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're telling the sponsors that we expect the completion of  
the cleaning of the house and the beginning of reforms,'' IOC 
marketing director Michael Payne said. ``We are saying there is no 
doubt in the IOC's resolve to go all the way on this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But IOC officials say the reform process will take time, that  
the world shouldn't expect an overnight revolution. 
</P>
<P>
	``We won't do it so fast that we will be destabilized by public  
opinion,'' executive board member Kevan Gosper said. ``You can't 
panic yourself to take changes. The problem is everyone thinks they 
own the Olympic rings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Samaranch took over in 1980, the IOC was virtually broke,  
the Olympics were torn by boycotts and few -- if any -- cities wanted 
anything to do with the games. 
</P>
<P>
	Under his leadership, the Olympics grew into a  
multibillion-dollar industry. The games became so successful that 
cities began waging fierce bidding wars for the right to stage 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	After years of rumors of bribery, the issue exploded into the  
open with revelations that Salt Lake officials paid more than $1 
million in cash, travel, gifts, scholarships, jobs and other 
inducements to IOC members and their families. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics say Samaranch must be held accountable for the scandals  
and should resign because the abuses happened on his watch. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Olympic Committee has backed off its previous  
unqualified support for Samaranch and now stops just short of 
calling for him to step down. 
</P>
<P>
	But Associated Press interviews with dozens of IOC members over  
the past month have found overwhelming support for Samaranch. 
International sports federations and national Olympic committees 
also have rallied around him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am absolutely adamant that Samaranch should stay until the  
end of his mandate,'' executive board member Jacques Rogge said. 
``We have to do what's best for the IOC. We don't have to do 
something just to please the critics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The question of Samaranch's departure is clouded because he has  
no obvious successor. If he resigned, it could lead to a divisive 
election that would drag the IOC further into crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	The list of presidential contenders includes Rogge, Gosper and  
vice presidents Dick Pound and Anita DeFrantz. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch hinted last week that he has an heir apparent in mind.  
</P>
<P>
	``In the IOC, there has historically been an Anglo-Saxon and a  
Latin bloc, which have managed to coexist correctly,'' he said. 
``For my successor, I see a person totally above the parties. But 
his name remains a secret in my mind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There has been increasing speculation that Samaranch might  
decide to step down early, perhaps later this year or early next 
year, once the crisis has died down, the reforms are in place and a 
stable transition has been assured. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Samaranch delivers the reforms, thereafter his only  
remaining duty is to arrange an orderly transfer of power,'' said 
Reedie, the British IOC member. ``It will be his call when he does 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One theory, floated last week in the Wall Street Journal, is  
that Samaranch is leaning toward stepping down in November and that 
he would remain in a leadership role -- possibly a transitional 
co-presidency -- through the 2000 Sydney Games. IOC officials denied 
the report. 
</P>
<P>
	Whenever Samaranch decides to leave, it probably will be on his  
own terms. He doesn't want to go down in history as the IOC 
president who resigned in disgrace. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's my job to lead the IOC out of the storm,'' he said. ``I  
want to walk out the front door with my head high.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990313.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 09:53:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Skiing Star Retires at 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SIERRA NEVADA, Spain (AP) -- Deborah Compagnoni, a three-time  
Olympic champion and winner of 16 World Cup races, retired from 
competitive skiing Saturday, driven from the sport by injury and 
illness. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement by the 28-year-old Italian was expected, but  
still drew a crush of reporters, skiers and autograph-seekers to 
the finish area after final giant slalom, in which she was seventh. 
</P>
<P>
	Near tears and her voice quivering, Compagnoni said she was  
calling it quits to preserve her health. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is where I end my career,'' Compagnoni said. ``It makes  
me unhappy to leave, but I must think of my health. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is because of my physical problems I am quitting, not  
because of my season's results. This is not a decision I wanted to 
take, but rather one I was forced to take.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Compagnoni missed several events this season and failed to win a  
single race. 
</P>
<P>
	Her World Cup career, which started in 1987, was plagued by  
chronic ailments. She has had numerous operations, suffered 
injuries to both knees and nearly died of an intestinal illness. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1989, Compagnoni had surgery to have a part of her intestine  
removed. 
</P>
<P>
	Compagnoni's most recent health woes included back problems and  
painful knees, which hampered her preparation for this season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Olympic giant slalom champion and slalom silver medalist in  
1998, she finished fourth overall in the World Cup standings last 
year -- an impressive feat considering she stopped racing both 
downhill and super-G in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Her gold in Japan, to go with gold in the giant slalom in 1994  
and another in super-G in 1992, made her the first Alpine skier to 
win gold at three Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, Compagnoni finished 22nd in the overall standings,  
and ninth in the giant slalom, her best discipline this season. 
</P>
<P>
	She won the gold in the slalom and giant slalom at the 1997  
world championships at her home base Sestriere, Italy, but failed 
to defend her titles in Vail, Colo., last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, she settled for seventh in the giant slalom and eighth  
in the slalom. 
</P>
<P>
	Compagnoni did not say what she planned to do next. Her recent  
projects have included a brief modeling career for bras and pasta 
advertising. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990313.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 16:11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jonrowe Quits Iditarod </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAGLE ISLAND, Alaska (AP) -- DeeDee Jonrowe, one of the pre-race  
favorites in this year's Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race, quit the 
trail Saturday after her 12-dog team stopped running along the 
frozen Yukon River. 
</P>
<P>
	Jonrowe, 43, of Willow, Alaska, scratched while running the  
60-mile stretch of trail between the checkpoints of Grayling and 
Eagle Island in Alaska's vast Interior. 
</P>
<P>
	``The dogs come first, and they just don't belong out here right  
now, for whatever reason,'' she told KNOM radio and the Alaska 
Public Radio Network while waiting for a plane to airlift her team 
from the trail. 
</P>
<P>
	Her team of young dogs stopped about 25 miles outside Eagle  
Island. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she played with them and tried to cajole them, but she  
said it was clear to her that the dogs didn't have the will to 
continue. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're creatures of habit, and they no longer trust what  
happening,'' Jonrowe said. ``It's mental -- it's not physical.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the time she was in fourth place behind Doug Swingley of  
Lincoln, Mont., Martin Buser of Big Lake, Alaska, and Rick Swenson 
of Two Rivers, Alaska. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she may have left Grayling too soon, without giving the  
team enough rest in the extremely cold conditions. Jonrowe spent 
only an hour in the checkpoint before setting out in pursuit of the 
leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Along the Yukon, temperatures early Saturday were reported at 30  
below zero, with a 20 mph headwind for mushers. 
</P>
<P>
	The scratch was the first ever for Jonrowe, who was competing in  
her 17th Iditarod. She has come close to winning several times, 
placing second last year and in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were two things I hadn't done: I hadn't won and I hadn't  
scratched,'' she said. ``I was hoping it was much more likely to 
win than to scratch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coming into the 1999 Iditarod, Jonrowe had 11 straight finishes  
in the top 10 that earned her more than $250,000 in prize money. 
</P>
<P>
	She was the seventh scratch among the 56 mushers who started the  
1,100-mile race March 6 in Anchorage. 
</P>
<P>
	Swingley, the 1995 winner from Lincoln, Mont., made it to Eagle  
Island at 5:27 a.m. (9:27 a.m. EST) Saturday with 13 dogs. 
</P>
<P>
	Buser, a three-time Iditarod winner, arrived second at 8:51 a.m.  
with 10 dogs, and Swenson, who has won the race five times, was 
third into the checkpoint an hour later with 13 dogs. 
</P>
<P>
	With Jonrowe's scratch, defending champion Jeff King of Denali  
Park, Alaska, moved up to fourth. King left Grayling at 7:02 a.m. 
after a five-hour rest. 
</P>
<P>
	Rounding out the top 10 were Alaskans Paul Gebhardt of Kasilof,  
Ramey Smyth of Big Lake, Vern Halter of Willow, Bill Cotter of 
Nenana and Charlie Boulding of Manley and race rookie Harald 
Tunheim of Norway. 
</P>
<P>
	Swingley has racked up a number of firsts so far in the race. He  
earned $3,000 by being first into the namesake checkpoint of 
Iditarod, and another $3,500 for being first to reach the Yukon 
River. 
</P>
<P>
	His success came despite breaking two sleds -- and quickly  
repairing them well enough to continue. 
</P>
<P>
	``My dogs are running fine,'' Swingley said Friday in Anvik.  
``I'm just having a good time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Barron from Sheep Creek, Alaska, declared himself out of  
the race overnight back at the midpoint Gold Rush ghost town of 
Iditarod. Barron -- the sixth scratch in the race -- said his young 
dogs simply were too tired to continue. He finished 12th in last 
year's race. 
</P>
<P>
	The winner gets $54,000 from the $450,000 purse. Prize money is  
paid to the first 20 finishers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
