<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Bombs Rock Kosovo Ahead of Talks  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Departing for peace talks in France,  
ethnic Albanian delegates said Saturday they were ready to sign a 
U.S.-backed Kosovo peace plan if the Serb-led government backs down 
on its opposition to allowing NATO troops to enforce it. Meanwhile, 
there was no letup in the fighting between government forces and 
ethnic Albanian rebels in the province in southern Serbia. Three 
bombs went off this afternoon in two government-controlled cities, 
killing at least six people and injuring more than 60. 

</P>
<P>
	13 People Die in Istanbul Fire  
</P>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- Attackers set a crowded six-story  
department store on fire Saturday, killing at least 13 people in 
one of Turkey's deadliest attacks in years. There were differing 
accounts what happened, with Istanbul's fire chief describing it as 
a methodical arson attack, while the Anatolia news agency cited 
witnesses who said assailants hurled firebombs into the store and 
fled. No one had claimed responsibility, and the identity of the 
attackers was unknown. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Thanks His Defenders  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- President Clinton, careful to express  
contrition and avoid gloating after his acquittal in the Senate 
impeachment trial, began this weekend to publicly show his 
gratitude to those who stood up for him throughout the impeachment 
process. On Saturday night, Clinton was the featured guest at an 
Arkansas state Democratic party salute to Dale Bumpers, who 
delivered the defense summation to the Senate impeachment trial. He 
mentioned that they had been through ``all kinds of adversity'' 
together, and saluted Bumpers for never forgetting ``the lessons of 
the past, beginning with the Constitution'' during his long Senate 
career. 

</P>
<P>
	Plains, Midwest Hit With Snowstorm  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A large storm system spread snow across the  
central Plains into the Midwest Saturday and produced thunderstorms 
in the South. Snow fell heavily in the central Plains during the 
night, with up to 14 inches closing Interstate 70 in western 
Kansas. A line of thunderstorms swept from eastern Texas through 
Louisiana into Mississippi, Alabama and eastern Tennessee. The 
National Weather Service issued a tornado watch for sections of 
Louisiana, Mississippi, Alabama and extreme northwestern Florida. 

</P>
<P>
	Bomb Explodes at Abortion Clinic  
</P>
<P>
	ASHEVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- A bomb planted outside an abortion clinic  
exploded Saturday, causing no injuries and little damage because it 
detonated only partially. The clinic, less than 75 miles from the 
mountainous area where serial bombing suspect Eric Rudolph is 
believed to be hiding, received no advance warning of the bomb. 
Police initially said two bombs had been planted at the Femcare 
clinic, but the FBI determined that a second device found in the 
vicinity was actually a piece of the exploded bomb. 

</P>
<P>
	Pakistan Tightens Nuclear Exports  
</P>
<P>
	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Pakistan has amended an old law to  
tighten control over the export of nuclear technology, Foreign 
Ministry spokesman Tariq Altaf said Saturday. Since India and 
Pakistan exploded underground nuclear devices last year, the 
international community has worried about the export of sensitive 
nuclear knowledge. Pakistan has promised it would not let its 
technology be sold. 

</P>
<P>
	Two Die in Fuel Tanker Explosion  
</P>
<P>
	FULLERTON, Calif. (AP) -- A tanker carrying 8,000 gallons of fuel  
overturned and exploded on a freeway, hurling fiery debris and 
killing a motorist and the trucker. The 44-year-old driver of the 
tanker succumbed to his burns Saturday. The motorist, burned beyond 
recognition, was found in the wreckage of a car more than an hour 
after the crash, authorities said. The car and tanker collided, but 
it was unclear whether that happened before or after the truck went 
out of control. 

</P>
<P>
	Heavyweights Return to the Garden  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Nothing quickens the pulse of Madison Square  
Garden quite like a heavyweight championship fight, and there was a 
rare air of extra electricity Saturday night for the Evander 
Holyfield-Lennox Lewis bout. A celebrity-studded sellout crowd of 
21,284, paying prices from $100 to $1,500, turned the Garden into 
the center of the boxing universe for the first time in a long 
time. 

</P>
<P>
	Gonzaga, Florida Auburn Win  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Gonzaga upset second-seeded Stanford 82-74,  
Florida put away upstart Weber State and Connecticut cruised into 
the Sweet 16 in the second round of the NCAA West Regional 
Saturday. Iowa beat Arkansas 82-72 with a 23-6 run. St. John's 
handed Indiana its worst NCAA tournament loss ever with a 86-61 
victory. Auburn ousted Oklahoma State 81-74 and Ohio State held 
Detroit scoreless for the opening 10 minutes and went on to rout 
the Titans 75-44. Maryland set a school record for victories with 
its 75-63 win over Creighton. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by STEPHANIE GASKELL  
</P>
