<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Residents of a town southeast of  
the Argentine capital searched the garbage dumps Saturday for a 
valuable statuette of the Virgin of Mercy which was stolen from the 
Roman Catholic cathedral. 
</P>
<P>
	The statue was made in Peru in the late 18th century and brought  
to Chascomus, 75 miles from Buenos Aires by town founder Pedro 
Escribano. 
</P>
<P>
	The 22-inch high porcelain statuette, valued at $10,000, has a  
silver crown, golden rings, earrings and brooches and a mantle 
covered with precious stones. 
</P>
<P>
	The robbers may have thrown away the statue after stripping it  
of its ornaments and mantle, cathedral notary Hugo Gezzi told the 
news agency Noticias Argentinas. 
</P>
<P>
	Police believe the statue was stolen late Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	HAVANA, Cuba (AP) -- Thirty Cuban railway guards who looted  
shipments of peas, rice, detergent and cigarettes they were 
supposed to protect have been sentenced to prison, the Communist 
Party daily Granma reported Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The chief guard at the rail depot, Norge Chacon Diaz, apparently  
oversaw the theft of shipments meant for communities in eastern 
Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper put the value of the stolen items at roughly  
$50,000. However, Cuban prices for such goods -- all part of state 
rations -- are a tiny fraction of those anywhere else in the world, 
often just a few cents per pound or package. 
</P>
<P>
	Granma said Chacon was sentenced to 14 years in prison and six  
guards each were sentenced to 12 years. The 23 others received 
terms between six and nine years. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Angry at the steep cost of surfing  
the net, Internet users in Brazil are going on strike, a newspaper 
reported Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	They will stay logged-off the Internet all-day Wednesday in  
protest, the Gazeta Mercantil daily said. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil has about 2.2 million Internet users who pay roughly $27  
a month for unlimited access -- slightly higher than typical U.S. 
rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet access providers were quoted as blaming their higher  
monthly rates on charges imposed by Brazilian telecommunication 
companies to connect users to the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) -- Panamanian politicians and students  
laid flowers Saturday at the tombs of 20 people killed by U.S. 
soldiers during a 1964 clash that broke out when students tried to 
hang Panama's flag in the canal zone ruled by the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The 35th anniversary of the clash comes in the final year of  
U.S. control of the canal. Panama will take charge of the canal and 
U.S. military property on Dec. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	On Jan. 9, 1964, hundreds of students attempted to hang the  
Panamanian flag in front of a high school in Panama City's Balboa 
section, which then was under U.S. administration. 
</P>
<P>
	The clash provoked a temporary disruption in relations between  
the two countries. In 1977, both sides signed accords that set the 
1999 handover date. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) -- Five Nicaraguan prison guards have  
been suspended and 20 detained for allegedly planning to spark an 
inmate riot to push their demands for salary increases and better 
conditions, a prison spokesman said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The guards planned to provoke unrest at the jail in Tipitapa, 15  
miles east of the capital, Managua, on Friday when they refused to 
allow families to visit the inmates, said national prison 
spokesman, Juan Ramon Huerta. 
</P>
<P>
	Riot police were called in to maintain order, and President  
Arnoldo Aleman ordered the government to fire any prison officials 
who had participated in the plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Prison guards complain their monthly salaries of roughly $50,  
are too low and that Nicaraguan prisons are overcrowded. 
</P>
