<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Six Children Dead in St. Louis Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The woman's screams shot out from her  
third-story window toward the busy intersection and Fire Station 8 
across the street. Save my children, she cried before plunging from 
her flaming apartment to the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	But the blaze, apparently sparked out of fury after a fight,  
moved too fast even for the neighboring firefighters. Six children 
were trapped and none survived. Three of them were found huddling 
together inside a closet. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a tragic waste of human life,'' said Fire Chief Neil  
Svetanics. 
</P>
<P>
	Hours after Friday's fire, authorities arrested a 23-year-old  
man -- police said he was the boyfriend of the frantic victim -- at 
his home just nine blocks away. 
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses said he and the woman had been fighting outside the  
brick apartment building earlier in the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Firefighters across the street also reported seeing a man  
outside the building with what may have been a red gasoline 
container. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was an altercation prior to the fire and that may have  
led to the fire,'' said Police Chief Ron Henderson. ``We're very, 
very sure that we have the person responsible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Names of the victims were not immediately released, but  
officials said the children ranged in age from 7 months to 9 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The woman, who apparently was the only adult inside the  
apartment, suffered a broken leg and head injuries after falling 
from her window. She had lost her grip while desperately shouting 
to firefighters, witnesses said, and continued her pleas even after 
falling. 
</P>
<P>
	``We saw the fire and then we saw a girl hanging out the window  
crying 'Help me, help me and my kids.''' said Selina Bailey, a 
neighbor. ``This is a sad day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neighbors said many, but not all, of the victims were related. A  
woman who lived in the apartment and was believed to be the mother 
of some of the children arrived home just as firefighters were 
extinguishing the blaze, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities did not reveal details on how the blaze may have  
started, but said there was little doubt it was arson. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any time you have a fire at 4:30 p.m. on one of the busiest  
intersections in St. Louis, 50 feet from the firehouse, and it is 
fully engulfed in flames within minutes, there's a pretty strong 
indication it was intentional,'' Svetanics said. 
</P>
<P>
	Firefighter Tim Dangos was among the first to encounter the  
fast-moving flames on the third floor. Through the smoke he saw a 
baby carriage and diapers. And in the confusion he thought he heard 
voices. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was thinking that I had to get those kids out of there,''  
Dangos told the St. Louis Post-Dispatch. Before he could, though, 
the fire intensified, forcing him to dive out a window. 
</P>
<P>
	The scene of the deadliest blaze in St. Louis since 1988 moved  
many firefighters to tears, according to Svetanics. 
</P>
<P>
	Said a drenched and soot-covered Dangos, ``This was bad ... I've  
been on for 14 years, and I've never seen one this bad.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990313.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 14:42:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Temple-Cincinnati Rivalry Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- For the third time in five years, Temple and  
Cincinnati will meet in the NCAA tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's second-round matchup at the FleetCenter will again be  
between teams that stress defense first and with experienced, 
successful coaches on both benches. 
</P>
<P>
	Temple coach John Chaney was asked Saturday about himself and  
Cincinnati's Bob Huggins. He sat at the table on the stage and 
laughed, his rugged 67-year-old face well-hidden with a black 
baseball cap pulled down tight to his eyes and the collar of a 
black trenchcoat turned up. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you look at Bobby and you look at me are there any  
similarities at all?'' he asked. 
</P>
<P>
	The laughter picked up around the room where the 45-year-old  
Huggins had just been, his attire a smart school warmup. With his 
well-groomed hair and wire-rimmed glasses, he looked like a 
businessman on a day off. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bobby's players even have names like `Levitate,''' Chaney  
said, playing off the name of Cincinnati guard Melvin Levett. ``My 
players are meek and young and I will challenge them and use all 
the blasphemous words I can. Bobby's able to generate a high level 
of aggressiveness from his players and he's always been able to do 
that. My players, I don't even want to call them what they are. You 
saw them yesterday. You aren't afraid of them. Those little boys 
were running around everywhere. Bobby's boys live in that paint and 
they just beat the hell out of you. Bobby's got that big old eraser 
he uses and the refs don't call the fouls. You know they commit 
more fouls than is on that piece of paper you guys got.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Obviously, Chaney felt he had to politic with the officials as  
he gets the sixth-seeded Owls (22-10) ready for the third-seeded 
Bearcats (27-5). 
</P>
<P>
	Temple advanced with a 61-54 victory over 11th-seeded Kent,  
while Cincinnati beat 14th-seeded George Mason 72-48. The Bearcats 
beat Temple in the first round in 1995 and in the second round the 
next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both teams are hard to score against,'' Huggins said. ``They  
play the matchup and three different zones. John does a great job 
of mixing them and makes them hard to recognize. We're a man-to-man 
team and we try to make every shot as tough as we can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That means don't expect a whole lot of offense Sunday and that  
could mean trouble for the Bearcats. In its five losses this 
season, Cincinnati scored 60 or less in each. Temple, a team that 
has struggled from the outside all season, averages 66.6 points. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to slow it down but they'll want to beat the zone down  
court so we can't set up,'' Temple's Quincy Wadley said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll have to speed things up and get them out of their game  
so their guards aren't comfortable,'' Cincinnati's Pete Mickeal 
said. ``We have to force turnovers and get them in transition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The same scenario will be true in the other game in the  
doubleheader when second-seeded Miami (23-6) faces 10th-seeded 
Purdue (20-12). 
</P>
<P>
	The Hurricanes advanced with a 75-54 victory over 15th-seeded  
Lafayette as Johnny Hemsley scored 31 points, including a 
school-record nine 3-pointers. 
</P>
<P>
	Purdue used quite a bit of zone defense in beating  
seventh-seeded Texas 58-54 in a first-round game that could only be 
described as ugly. 
</P>
<P>
	``People used to think they could shut us down with a zone but  
with Johnny being so hot, we'll take that,'' Miami center Mario 
Bland said. 
</P>
<P>
	The win was the first ever for Miami in its third NCAA  
tournament appearance. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Sweet 16 would be a tremendous feat for us,'' Hemsley  
said. ``But Purdue's a good team and they did a lot of good things 
against Texas. We'll have our hands full.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Boilermakers, who came into the tournament having lost five  
of six games, feel the same way. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are going to have to compete on the glass and we are going  
to have to get back on defense in transition,'' Purdue's Alan 
Eldridge said. ``When we get our shooters the ball it will have to 
be when they have an opportunity to score.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's winners advance to next week's East Regional at East  
Rutherford, N.J., along with the two winners from the subregional 
at Charlotte, N.C. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
