<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aamodt Nears Kjus; Maier Is Done </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SIERRA NEVADA, Spain (AP) -- Norway's Kjetil Andre Aamodt closed  
within 32 points of teammate Lasse Kjus today in the battle for the 
overall World Cup season title, which will be decided in Sunday's 
season-ending giant slalom. 
</P>
<P>
	Aamodt finished second in today's slalom in a combined time of 1  
minute, 50.67 seconds, just behind winner Thomas Stangassinger of 
Austria in 1:50.44. Third went to Italy's Marco Casanova (1:51.19). 
The win gave Stangassinger his first World Cup season slalom title 
after being runner-up the last two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Kjus finished 13th in 1:54.05.  
</P>
<P>
	Aamodt's second-place finish was worth 80 points, pushing his  
season total to 1,397. Kjus got 20 points for 13th, moving his 
total to 1,429 in one of the closest finishes of the decade. 
</P>
<P>
	Hermann Maier, last year's overall champion and the only other  
skier with a chance for the season title, finished 16th, got no 
points and was eliminated with 1,307 points. 
</P>
<P>
	``The pressure has been on the both of us,'' Kjus said of  
Aamodt. ``Tomorrow will be difficult, but I can only do my best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I would liked to have had this wrapped up a long time ago,''  
added Kjus, who predicted he might clinch the title today. ``But 
that's what's exciting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aamodt was more than happy with his slalom.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was hoping for a chance to gain some points on Lasse. This  
is more than I expected,'' Aamodt said. ``I've had pressure before 
to catch up and now the pressure is on both of us. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've both been skiing for 10 years. It will be a championship  
race tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maier made a joke about skiing in slalom, his worst event, after  
saying earlier in the week he would skip it. Maier wore a bright 
yellow wig and smiled broadly after he was eliminated. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm proud of my season and I'm not angry,'' he said. ``I've  
had a fabulous two years. I've got two Olympic golds, two golds 
from the world championships, the overall last year and so on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In giant slalom, Aamodt has a better season World Cup record  
than Kjus. Aamodt, the 1994 overall World Cup champion, has 
finished in the top four three times this season. Kjus, the '96 
overall winner, has yet to crack the top four. 
</P>
<P>
	Aamodt also has six World Cup wins in giant slalom, to Kjus'  
one. 
</P>
<P>
	Stangassinger, runner-up the last two seasons in slalom to  
injured teammate Thomas Sykora and the 1994 Olympic slalom 
champion, finished the season with 566 points. Of the season's nine 
races, he won two and was second three times. 
</P>
<P>
	The course -- still choppy and rutted -- was better prepared under  
sunny skies after women slalom skiers threatened a strike Friday 
and refused to ski the second leg of the race, forcing organizers 
to cancel the slalom event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
