<HEADLINE> Tanker Blast Kills One Motorist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUENA PARK, Calif. (AP) -- A tanker truck carrying thousands of  
gallons of fuel overturned and exploded on a freeway Friday night, 
killing a motorist, hurling flaming debris for 60 yards and 
stopping traffic for miles. 
</P>
<P>
	The tanker's driver sustained second- and third-degree burns on  
75 percent of his body, said California Highway Patrol Officer 
Denise Medina. He was airlifted to a hospital where he was in 
critical condition. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just saw this guy come out of the truck fully engulfed in  
flames and just running,'' said witness Vanessa Juarez. ``His whole 
body was on fire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The motorist was found in the wreckage of a car after  
firefighters had controlled the intense flames. The identity of the 
victim was not immediately known. 
</P>
<P>
	The truck overturned around 9 p.m. on northbound Interstate 5  
about 30 miles southeast of downtown Los Angeles. It was not clear 
what caused the tanker driver to lose control. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a bunch of burned vehicles and it's quite a mess out  
there,'' Medina said. ``The Fire Department is out there trying to 
disentangle the vehicles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Highway Patrol spokesman Mark Reeves said the interstate was  
expected to remain closed for several hours. 
</P>
<P>
	The force of the explosion hurled flaming pieces of the truck  
more than 60 yards, said Robyn Butler, a spokeswoman for the 
Anaheim Fire Department. 
</P>
</TEXT>
