<DOCNO> APW19990313.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 17:31:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pac-10 Packs up Early in Tourney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- The first reaction in the Stanford locker room:  
shocked silence. 
</P>
<P>
	Then came the tears.  
</P>
<P>
	``It hurts deeply,'' said Arthur Lee, the guard who ended his  
college career by leading the Cardinal with 24 points Saturday but 
couldn't stop the 3-point shelling by Gonzaga in an 82-74 upset. 
</P>
<P>
	This was a Stanford team led by four senior starters that had  
gone so far a year ago, reaching the Final Four before falling to 
the eventual champion, and had begun this season with every 
expectation of going farther. 
</P>
<P>
	Those expectations weren't based just on the polls that ranked  
them so high all year, or the boasts of their fans, who rocked 
their home court with all the spirit of championship contenders. 
</P>
<P>
	To a man, Stanford's players had written down in preseason  
practice the goal of winning the Pac-10 title and going back to the 
Final Four and taking it all. 
</P>
<P>
	They met the first challenge, but fell flat in the NCAA  
tournament against a smaller, quicker Gonzaga team that shredded 
them with 11-for-20 3-point shooting and outhustled them for a 
47-33 rebounding advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a Stanford team of experienced players losing to a tiny  
Jesuit school in Spokane, Wash., named for the patron saint of 
youth. 
</P>
<P>
	``Give them a lot of credit for the way they played and the  
heart they had on the inside,'' Stanford's Mark Madsen said. ``They 
may not have been the quickest players, but they had a lot of 
heart, and that goes a long way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Pac-10 packed up early this year, UCLA, Arizona and  
Washington bowing out in the first round, Stanford in the second. 
</P>
<P>
	All that proud tradition -- the 15 NCAA titles, the 30 Final Four  
appearances, the oh-so-close finish by Stanford a year ago -- meant 
nothing to the upstarts who quickly ambushed all four Pac-10 teams 
in the tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very surprised,'' Stanford coach Mike Montgomery said of  
the conference's collapse. ``If you asked us what happened, each of 
us would have our own little story to tell. And those four stories 
add up the fact that we're all out. We will certainly pay a price, 
and we'll be reading about this and hearing about this for a long 
time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Montgomery sought to ease the burden of expectations on his team  
all season, saying they came from other people. He tried to do the 
same thing after the loss Saturday, claiming ``the Final Four thing 
(from last year) is totally out of whack.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just because the team had come close to the championship last  
year, he said, didn't mean it would be able to do it again. 
Especially with four players injured. 
</P>
<P>
	``The expectations were difficult for us,'' he said.  
``Everything we did was not quite good enough. Today it's extremely 
disappointing, but it doesn't diminish what we accomplished.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Stanford players could, indeed, take pride in putting the  
school back on the basketball map the last two years after decades 
of trying. But there was no hiding how deeply this loss cut. 
</P>
<P>
	``We knew what we were capable of doing,'' senior Peter Sauer  
said, ``and we didn't do it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
