<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oregon Marks Day Ship Finally Sank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WALDPORT, Ore. (AP) -- The bow portion of the New Carissa has  
finally sunk to the ocean floor. Now attention turns to the last 
chunk of the ship that has been mired in the sands off the Oregon 
coast for more than a month. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. John Kitzhaber declared the day the freighter sank  
``Two-thirds of the New Carissa at the Bottom of the Ocean Day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The only thing more stubborn and uncooperative than Mother  
Nature was the New Carissa herself,'' Kitzhaber wrote in his 
declaration. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Coast Guard officials said that a Friday flyover of the  
site found that about 500 gallons of oil had spilled during the 
sinking the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	Navy demolitions experts first blew holes in the broken bow  
section of the New Carissa with explosives, then a destroyer 
riddled the wreck with 70 artillery rounds. 
</P>
<P>
	When the stubborn ship insisted on staying afloat, they had a  
nuclear submarine fire a torpedo. That provided the knockout blast. 
The ship now sits two miles down, where its remaining 130,000 
gallons of fuel oil can do no more harm. 
</P>
<P>
	The slight oil slicks on the surface were too small to skim and  
would likely never reach shore, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It'll just swirl out there,'' said Coast Guard Lt. Cmdr.  
Dawayne Penberthy. 
</P>
<P>
	The 639-foot New Carissa first washed ashore at Coos Bay on Feb.  
4 and began leaking oil four days later. Efforts to burn the 
400,000 gallons of fuel oil on board succeeded in burning only half 
of it away. The ship split in two and spilled 70,000 gallons on 
southern Oregon's beaches. 
</P>
<P>
	When salvage crews tried to tow it out to sea last week, it  
broke away from the tow line and again washed ashore. 
</P>
<P>
	The remaining third of the wreck is still stuck in the surf near  
Coos Bay. The Coast Guard, salvage officials and others plan to 
meet next Friday to consider their options. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Kitzhaber has said he wants a $25 million bond posted by  
the ship's Japanese owners to assure that the problem will be dealt 
with. 
</P>
<P>
	The state is worried about liability if someone gets hurt at the  
stern wreck, which is on property controlled by the Division of 
State Lands. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nor is it enthusiastic about the image of that ship on its  
shores,'' said Langdon Marsh, the head of the Oregon Department of 
Environmental Quality. 
</P>
<P>
	As of Friday, more than 774 dead birds have washed up on shore,  
351 of them splotched with oil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990313.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 02:21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nothing Found in Ex-Speaker Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A 20-month investigation by the FBI that spanned a  
dozen states and used electronically wired informants showed no 
political corruption by the late House Speaker Thomas O'Neill Jr., 
The Boston Globe reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The secret probe lasted from 1979 to 1981 when the House speaker  
was playing a major role in national affairs as an ally of 
President Jimmy Carter, said the newspaper, which obtained 
government documents through requests under the Freedom of 
Information Act. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI suspected O'Neill used his political clout to win about  
$3 million in federal loans and guarantees for projects in which he 
and his associates had financial interests. For a time, the FBI 
suspected that O'Neill had received $65,000 in kickbacks for his 
help. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI fitted an informant, who told investigators that O'Neill  
had received payoffs, with a transmitter and recording device to 
record conversations with O'Neill and his associates. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI suspected from three hours of recorded conversations  
that one or more of O'Neill's associates was involved in some 
unspecified ``illegal acts'' on behalf of the speaker. 
</P>
<P>
	At the peak of the investigation in February 1981, the FBI  
conducted 25 interviews. However, FBI records conclude the 
investigation met with ``negative results regarding allegations 
concerning Congressman O'Neill and the misuse of his office,'' the 
Globe said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990313.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 00:41:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smithers Wins NCAA Slalom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWRY, N.H. (AP) -- Jayme Smithers had to be consoled by his  
Denver teammates when he finished 25th in the giant slalom in the 
NCAA Ski Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	When he won the slalom Friday, his teammates tackled and jumped  
on him, the difference between losing and winning. 
</P>
<P>
	Smithers, a sophomore from British Columbia, came from fifth  
place to win his first collegiate race and keep alive Denver's 
slipping hopes for its first title since 1971. 
</P>
<P>
	In the women's race, Linda Wikstrom, skiing for her late  
roommate, won and helped move defending champion Colorado back into 
first place with only today's classical cross-country races 
remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	Wikstrom, second after the first run at Sunday River, overtook  
Dartmouth's Jennifer Collins to win in 1 minute, 45.08 seconds. 
Collins finished in 1:45.93. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was all for her,'' Wikstrom said of Lucie Hasunova, a  
member of the team who was killed in a snowmobile accident in 
January. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colorado team has dedicated these championships to her  
memory. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado, the defending champion, led after the first-day's  
giant slalom races, but Utah took a 1 1/2-point lead over the 
Buffaloes after Thursday's freestyle cross-country races. 
</P>
<P>
	By the end of Friday's races, Colorado was back on top with 514  
points. Utah had one of its women disqualified and fell back with 
494.5. 
</P>
<P>
	Vermont was third with 481, Dartmouth fourth at 434 and Denver,  
one of the favorites, fifth at 429. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a pretty good cushion,'' Colorado coach Richard Rokos  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Smithers started 17th in the first run of the slalom and was  
1.37 seconds behind Stefan Lanziner of New Mexico. But the hard, 
fast snow gave him a chance to make it up for his first college 
victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you start first, you have to go for it; it's a clean  
course,'' Denver coach Kurt Smitz said. ``He seized the moment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smithers won in 1:33.32, with Lanziner second in 1:33.39.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
