<HEADLINE> NCAA South Regional Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Auburn teammates Adrian Chilliest and Mark  
McGadney may want to stay away from one another next game. 
</P>
<P>
	That's because Chilliest punched his teammate midway through the  
second half of Auburn's second-round victory over Oklahoma State. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't a deliberate blow. Chilliest was just celebrating an  
Auburn basket and throwing a couple of punches in the air. 
</P>
<P>
	McGadney just happened to be standing nearby and the blow from  
the 6-foot-5, 235-pound Chilliest resulted in the 6-7, 215-pound 
McGadney keeping an ice pack on his chin for the rest of the game. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *LONG ABSENCE:* Auburn is in the NCAA tournament for the first  
time since 1988 and it's been even longer since the Tigers were 
among the final 16 teams competing for a championship. The last 
time they advanced past the second round was in 1986 when they lost 
to eventual national champion Louisville in the regional final. 
</P>
<P>
	Auburn's 81-74 victory over Oklahoma State gave it bragging  
rights in the state of Alabama. It was Auburn's 29th triumph, 
giving it more victories than any other college team in the state. 
The Crimson Tide of Alabama held the record at 28 until this 
month. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *ELLIS UNDEFEATED:* Auburn coach Cliff Ellis has an  
accomplishment that few college coaches can claim. He's never lost 
a game to a team coached by Eddie Sutton. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, Saturday was only the second time the two were on  
opposing benches. The previous meeting came when Ellis was coaching 
Clemson and his team upset No. 20 Oklahoma State 68-65 in the 1993 
Rainbow Classic. 
</P>
<P>
	Both coaches can boast of impressive success. Sutton is 632-252  
in 29 years and ranks third among active coaches in victories. 
Ellis heads to the regional semifinals with a 444-270 mark in 24 
years as a Division I coach. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MISSING BUCKEYE:* Big Ten runner-up Ohio State advanced to a  
regional semifinal date with top-seeded Auburn despite being 
without one of its top reserves for both games in Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	Neshaun Coleman arrived here with a strep throat and he remained  
in the team's hotel through its two games. 
</P>
<P>
	``He ran a temperature as high as 103,'' said coach Jim O'Brien,  
who is hoping Coleman can play in Thursday's game at Knoxville, 
Tenn. 
</P>
<P>
	Coleman is one of Ohio State's top 3-point shooters, having hit  
37 percent (32-of-86) this season. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *PENN'S REBOUNDS:* Scoonie Penn's shooting touch may not be  
there, but he's contributing in other ways. 
</P>
<P>
	Penn, Ohio State's 5-foot-10 guard, pulled down a career-high 12  
rebounds Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``If my shot is not on, I'm not going to worry about it,'' he  
said. ``That is the most rebounds in my life, college, high school 
or anywhere. ... I can be a floor leader or a rebounder like I was 
today, whatever it takes to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Penn's previous high in a game this season was seven and his  
career-high in college was 10 against Massachusetts when he was 
playing for Boston College in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	``He went into his rebounding game,'' O'Brien said. ``He figures  
he's going to get double-figure rebounds because he can't make the 
shot.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *HOPEFULLY NOT:* Oklahoma State point guard Doug Gottlieb had a  
tiring job on Saturday. The nation's leader in assists was guarding 
Auburn guard Scott Pohlman much of the game and was also defended 
by him. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pohlman ran me to death,'' said Gottlieb, who had 12 assists  
to finish the season with 288 and a school-record 500 in two 
seasons. ``He moved without the ball well, obviously, he was 
feeling it and he got some good looks. He hit big shots and every 
time he got open, it seemed like he hit the shot.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
