<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 11:11:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Exec: Utah Gov. Knew Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The former head of Salt Lake's bid  
committee says Gov. Mike Leavitt knew relatives of International 
Olympic Committee members were getting scholarships from Olympic 
boosters. 
</P>
<P>
	Former bid committee president Tom Welch said Leavitt even  
considered soliciting scholarships from local colleges on behalf of 
the bid committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Leavitt, whose Olympic role thus far has been righteous  
indignation at the scandal and who spearheaded the reform movement, 
denies the accusations. 
</P>
<P>
	Welch told The Salt Lake Tribune in a copyright story that he  
met with Leavitt in early 1993 to discuss how the new governor 
could help Salt Lake City land the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Scholarships to Utah schools for IOC children, Welch said,  
helped promote the state as a friendly place where foreign visitors 
could fit in. Welch said bid-committee vice president Dave Johnson 
and committee chairman Frank Joklik also were at that meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are a pretty Caucasian slice of America,'' Welch said  
Friday. ``There were questions about the kind of community we were. 
Our thinking was the best thing we could do is have (IOC members') 
kids come and have a good experience here. 
</P>
<P>
	``We said one of the things (Leavitt) could do is to get the  
schools to pay for the scholarships. He said he would look into it. 
I don't know that it was ever pursued.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leavitt has denied any knowledge of $1 million given to IOC  
members and their relatives for tuition, rent, health care, cash 
payments and other inducements. 
</P>
<P>
	Joklik also denied discussing scholarships with Welch or  
Leavitt. Neither Johnson nor his attorney, Max Wheeler, could be 
reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Welch's comments echo those of Ken Bullock, who said he alerted  
Leavitt, executive-committee members and reporters to the 
scholarships and lavish treatment of IOC members more than a year 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Bullock was appointed to the Salt Lake Organizing Committee  
board in 1995, after Salt Lake won the bid. He said he pieced the 
National Olympic Committee assistance program together by examining 
the budget and asking questions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't give you time, dates and locations,'' Bullock said.  
``I never in my wildest dreams thought that I needed to keep a 
diary. ... What the governor says is his business. But I know what 
I know and I know who I told.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, city officials learned the 2002 Winter Games will  
carry a $22.8 million price tag. Officials anticipate covering 
about $13.4 million of that total with grants, sponsorship revenue 
and other revenue. But that still leaves $9.4 million unfunded. 
</P>
<P>
	``That number is our worst-case scenario at this stage of the  
game,'' city Management Services director Roger Black said. ``This 
is our first stab at putting this on the table. ... There is a 
great deal of refinement that has to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Black also is a member of the Salt Lake Organizing Committee  
board of trustees. 
</P>
<P>
	The figures, in the preliminary ``Olympic Opportunities Master  
Plan'' released Friday, detail the city's cost for extra 
infrastructure, police and fire protection, street maintenance and 
other services. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the additional expenses forecast are increased airport  
security, downtown decorations and pageantry, visitor entertainment 
away from Olympic venues, beefed-up police and fire protection and 
Olympic-related library programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Policing the games alone will cost an additional $10.5 million,  
according to the report. Bracing for potential electrical fires at 
the media center at the Salt Palace will cost $3 million and 
additional, multilingual airport security could run $1.8 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The expenses in the report are separate from the $1.45 billion  
Salt Lake Organizing Committee budget, which only covers expenses 
related to the games themselves -- housing athletes and media, 
providing services at events, venues and opening and closing 
ceremonies. 
</P>
<P>
	City officials are working with SLOC officials to hammer out an  
agreement spelling out in detail the responsibilities of each. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
