<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Gopher Says He Did His Own Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Former University of Minnesota basketball  
player Courtney James has denied that a former school staffer wrote 
papers for him while he was a student, a published report said 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	James made the denial in a story published in the Star Tribune.  
He spoke to the newspaper Friday night following his team's CBA 
game in La Crosse, Wis. 
</P>
<P>
	His account contrasted with other recent reports about  
allegations from Jan Gangelhoff, a former secretary in the 
university's academic counseling unit, who has said she did course 
work for at least 20 current and former Gopher basketball players. 
</P>
<P>
	The Saint Paul Pioneer Press reported Wednesday that James  
confirmed that course work was prepared for him in possible 
violation of NCAA rules. The Pioneer Press quoted him as saying an 
assistant coach drove him and another player to Gangelhoff's 
residence for tutoring, another possible violation. 
</P>
<P>
	The St. Paul newspaper quoted James as saying he lied, saying  
``no,'' when an investigator asked whether Gangelhoff did papers, 
to protect Gangelhoff and coach Clem Haskins. 
</P>
<P>
	But James told the Star Tribune on Friday that Gangelhoff  
``never did nothing for me. She might have proofread something for 
me, but she never did any papers ... I wrote them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant professor Sander Latts told the Star Tribune earlier  
that James handed in a paper in March 1997 titled ``The Fair 
Housing Act and Black Americans,'' that was the best report ever 
submitted to him in nearly 40 years. Latts said James told him he 
wrote it in his hotel room ``while everybody else was out partying 
during their Final Four weekend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Latts also said didn't believe James had written the paper but  
gave him a passing grade because he couldn't prove otherwise. 
</P>
<P>
	James said Friday he didn't remember that paper, and also said  
he never went to Gangelhoff's house. ``Some players might have 
went; I don't know.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
