<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Creighton Seeks Second Upset </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Indiana has Bob Knight coaching on the  
sidelines. Maryland has Steve Francis starring on the court. St. 
John's has Lou Carnesecca cheering in the stands. 
</P>
<P>
	And Creighton? The Bluejays have high hopes.  
</P>
<P>
	``People don't know too much about us,'' top scorer Rodney  
Buford said Friday, ``but we feel we're going to be something 
special.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Creighton proved it belonged in the NCAA tournament by going 8-1  
against teams that made this March's field. Then, it upended 
Louisville 62-58 in the first round of the South Regional. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, the 10th-seeded Bluejays meet second-seeded Maryland. In  
the other second-round game, No. 3 seed St. John's takes on No. 6 
Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	Creighton and Maryland have met only once, with the Terrapins  
winning 83-79 in the 1975 NCAA tournament. At the time, Maryland 
was building up its basketball tradition while Creighton was 
starting a long slide in which did not win a postseason game until 
1991. 
</P>
<P>
	``I realize we've had a drought and we have to make a name for  
ourselves again,'' coach Dana Altman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet even a big name and tradition does not ensure success at  
this time of year -- North Carolina and UCLA learned that Thursday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not sure history is for everyone,'' Knight said. ``I'm not  
sure it makes a lot of difference to the kids.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Creighton overcame a 13-point deficit in the final 16 minutes to  
beat Louisville. Altman immediately began looking ahead, warily, to 
Maryland. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to have to play better than we have all season if  
we're going to have a chance,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a big win for us, but that's behind us,'' he said. ``We  
need to forget about it. But that can be tough to do when you 
haven't been in this situation before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maryland, expected by many to reach the Final Four, beat  
Valparaiso by 22 points in the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Louisville is a name when we go into the NCAA  
tournament that obviously gets everyone's attention, so I guess a 
lot of people are surprised that we're playing Creighton,'' 
Terrapins coach Gary Williams said. 
</P>
<P>
	``But when you look at the game (Thursday) and you watch how  
they played in terms of their intensity and in terms of their 
willingness to just hang in there when things weren't going their 
way, you can see why they're where they are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the highest scoring of their 74 NCAA tournament games,  
Indiana beat George Washington 108-88. Knight, however, noticed 
that his team gave up 57 points in the second half. 
</P>
<P>
	``Playing against St. John's that way will allow us to do one  
thing -- get beat,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	St. John's beat Samford by 26 points in the opening round. The  
Red Storm played Indiana once before in the tournament -- the 
Hoosiers won in 1976 on their way to the national title. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you play Indiana, you are playing against a system. And  
coach Knight is the master of that system,'' St. John's coach Mike 
Jarvis said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
