<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Weber State Has Coaching Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Weber State coach Ron Abegglen's feelings this  
week must be decidedly mixed. His Wildcats have just pulled off the 
biggest victory in the history of the school, and he's about to 
lose his job. 
</P>
<P>
	The diminutive 62-year-old coach with the world-weary eyes will  
be prowling the sidelines at least one more time. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wildcats, on the heels of their stunning upset of North  
Carolina, will try to become the first Big Sky Conference team in 
22 years to advance past the second round when they play Florida 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a great run,'' he said of his 38-year coaching  
career, the last eight of them at Weber State. ``How many coaches 
do you know that have lasted 38 years?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Abegglen would prefer to go out on his own terms. But last  
August, after his wife suffered a broken wrist in a heated argument 
with Abegglen and accused him of domestic abuse, the university 
suspended the coach for three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	When he returned to the job, he announced he would retire at the  
end of the coming season. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was by mutual agreement with the administration,'' Abegglen  
insists. 
</P>
<P>
	Given the lame-duck status of the coach, the Wildcats entered  
the season with modest expectations. But with spectacular Harold 
Arceneaux providing most of the offense, surrounded by a cast of 
solid role players, Weber State dethroned veteran-laden Northern 
Arizona as the Big Sky champion, then pulled off the stunning 76-74 
victory over North Carolina on Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Abegglen and his staff have tried to shield the players from any  
impact of the unusual coaching situation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd be lying to you if I said it's been easy,'' he said, ``but  
it's actually gone better than I thought it would.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His players seem to have been able to put the coaching issue  
aside. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was there in the back of our minds, but we didn't let it  
get to us,'' senior guard Marc Lawson said. ``We tried to block it 
out, and for the most part we've been able to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Abegglen will match wits with one of the country's up-and-coming  
young coaches, Florida's Billy Donovan. 
</P>
<P>
	The Gators' high-pressure style of play is a reflection of  
Donovan's intense personality. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a very demanding style of play,'' Donovan said. ``People  
watch it on television and it's obviously entertaining, but I don't 
think they understand the type of shape you have to be in to play 
40 minutes of that type of basketball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Today's first game at Seattle's Key Arena has Stanford, the only  
Pac-10 team still alive in the tournament, going against Gonzaga, 
which won its first NCAA tourney game ever when it beat Minnesota 
on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have gone into uncharted waters,'' Gonzaga coach Dan Monson  
said. ``If we win tomorrow, it would be even more uncharted waters. 
We'd like to get out in the ocean, and test all the waters out 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzaga's players and coach have seen Stanford all season on  
television and are not in awe of the matchup. 
</P>
<P>
	``The door is open. We need to go through it. We have the  
ability, if we play well, to win,'' Monson said. ``I know everybody 
wants to pit tiny Gonzaga against big Stanford, but to me it's two 
quality basketball teams.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stanford again will be without reserve forward Jarron Collins,  
who has missed the last two games with a sprained ankle. With 
Collins out, the Cardinal has gotten little help from its subs, and 
is counting on its veteran starting five -- four seniors and a 
junior -- to get the team back to the Final Four. 
</P>
<P>
	``Experience is definitely key right now,'' Lee said. ``We have  
been here before and we need to rely on our experience and history 
in these situations.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
