<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kansas, Kentucky To Square Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- There's a history that entwines Kansas,  
Kentucky and North Carolina, the three teams that have won more 
games than any others in the history of the game. 
</P>
<P>
	But only one of trio of big-time programs will have a chance to  
win the last national championship in the 20th century. 
</P>
<P>
	Kentucky (26-8) or Kansas (23-9), playing each other in the NCAA  
tournament for the first time, will be eliminated Sunday in the 
Midwest Regional. North Carolina is already out of the tourney 
after a stunning 76-74 first-round loss to 14th-seeded Weber State. 
</P>
<P>
	There are a combined 3,434 victories between Kentucky (1,746)  
and Kansas (1,688), but the coaches realize only one will be able 
to add to that total Sunday. History will have to step aside for 
the game at hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if it can add any more. ... We are just concerned  
with preparing and playing the game,'' Kansas coach Roy Williams 
said Saturday. ``To the coaches and players, it's a big game 
regardless. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact that it is in the NCAA tournament, and it is single  
elimination, adds to it. But I think that adds to it more than the 
fact that we are playing Kentucky or they are playing Kansas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Kentucky-Kansas winner advances to a round-of-16 game  
against either Utah (27-4) or Miami, Ohio (23-7), who meet in 
Sunday's other game. Utah would probably just as soon play Kansas, 
because the Utes have been eliminated by Kentucky four times in the 
last five years. Kentucky won the school's seventh national title 
by beating Utah in last year's final. 
</P>
<P>
	Kentucky, in its record 41st NCAA tourney, is the winningest  
team in history with 1,746 victories, followed by North Carolina 
(1,733) and Kansas (1,688) -- whose 286 victories in the 1990s are 
six more than the Wildcats this decade. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know it brings out the best in our players, and I know it  
will bring out best in their players,'' Kentucky coach Tubby Smith 
said. ``It's a measuring stick for each program.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But again, Smith insists, it's just the next game in Kentucky's  
attempt to play in a fourth straight NCAA championship game. 
</P>
<P>
	As for the connection among Kansas, Kentucky and North Carolina,  
it dates back to the beginning of the game itself. 
</P>
<P>
	James Naismith, the inventor of the game, was the first Kansas  
coach. One of his players was Phog Allen, who went on to coach the 
Jayhawks for 39 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Adolph Rupp won 876 games in 42 years as Kentucky's coach after  
playing at Kansas under Allen. Williams, in his 11th season at 
Kansas, is a North Carolina alumnus and former assistant there for 
Dean Smith, also a former player at Kansas under Allen and the only 
coach to win more games that Rupp. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1999, Williams is still looking for his first national  
championship. Tubby Smith is going for his second title in as many 
seasons at Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wildcats, who lost four straight road games to end the  
regular season with their most losses since 1990, have won their 
four postseason games by an average of 14 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Early this season in the Great Eight tournament in Chicago,  
Kentucky beat Kansas 63-45, holding the Jayhawks to a season-low 
15-of-51 shooing (29.4 percent). The Wildcats led 41-22 at 
halftime. 
</P>
<P>
	``I remember being embarrassed, especially the feeling in the  
locker room at halftime when we just simply got outplayed in every 
respect of the game,'' Kansas forward T.J. Pugh said. 
</P>
<P>
	To Eric Chenoweth, that first meeting ``is pretty much like a  
blur. It was up and down, up and down. We just couldn't get 
anything going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kentucky has an 18-3 series advantage after winning that Dec. 1  
meeting that was the first between the teams since 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	The teams earned the rematch with convincing first-round  
victories at the Superdome. 
</P>
<P>
	Heshimu Evans scored nine points in a 21-0 second-half spurt as  
Kentucky finally shook off New Mexico State and won 82-60. The 
defending national champs also won the title in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Kansas had five players in double figures and a 45-15 rebounding  
advantage in a 95-74 victory over Evansville. 
</P>
</TEXT>
