<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> City Settles Cop Sex Harass Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SHAWNEE, Kan. (AP) -- Three detectives who said a supervisor  
subjected them to unwelcome homosexual advances have settled their 
lawsuit against the city for $250,000. 
</P>
<P>
	If the cases had gone to trial, they would have been among the  
first since the U.S. Supreme Court ruled last March that sexual 
harassment can be illegal even when the offender and the victim are 
of the same sex. 
</P>
<P>
	Detectives Delbert Nicholas, Tom Carney and John Wells sued last  
year, alleging police Lt. Walter McDaniel subjected them to 
unwanted touching and requests for sexual favors in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	In court papers, McDaniel said he would unzip his pants, grab  
his crotch and show a lewd photograph of a boy as a way of breaking 
the ice with co-workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The detectives charged that the police chief considered the  
activity mere office horseplay and did not handle the complaints 
fairly. 
</P>
<P>
	The city contended that it had sexual harassment policies in  
place and that no inappropriate conduct took place once officials 
were notified. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
