<DOCNO> APW19990313.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-13 23:45:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spring Training Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	David Wells and Kerry Wood made belated spring debuts with very  
different results. 
</P>
<P>
	Wells, sidelined by back spasms earlier this month, pitched one  
perfect inning in his first outing since Game 1 of the World Series 
as the Toronto Blue Jays lost to Pittsburgh 7-5 Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The adrenaline was pumping out there,'' said Wells, who was  
traded from the New York Yankees to Toronto last month for Roger 
Clemens. ``It doesn't matter if it's preseason or postseason. The 
butterflies are there anytime you face major league hitters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wood, finally recovered from an upper respiratory and  
gastrointestinal illness that sidelined him for the early part of 
spring training, couldn't find the plate Saturday as a Chicago 
Cubs' split squad lost to the Anaheim Angels 6-5 at Tempe, Ariz. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was good to be out there,'' he said, still sweating from  
his in-game laps across the outfield. ``It's been a while.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year's NL Rookie of the Year allowed three runs and three  
hits in 1 1-3 innings, walking two and striking out none. He threw 
to nine batters, and 16 of his 26 pitches were balls. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point in the second inning, Wood threw 10 consecutive  
balls, prompting manager Jim Riggleman to make a trip to the mound. 
</P>
<P>
	``A little out of whack across the body at the end,'' Wood said  
of his problem. ``I was trying to throw strikes. They could have 
hit me out of the park, I wouldn't have cared.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Dunedin, Fla., Wells threw only 11 pitches in the sixth  
inning, retiring Ivan Cruz on a grounder to second, striking out 
Brant Brown and getting Al Martin on a weak popup to short. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't want to be out there all day,'' Wells said. ``My  
philosophy has always been strike one, strike two and whatever 
happens, happens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Phoenix, A misplay by country-music performer Garth Brooks  
contributed to the San Diego Padres' 2-1 loss to the Milwaukee 
Brewers. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks, playing left field in the ninth, stepped back, then  
sprinted forward and fell as a sinking drive by Milwaukee's Alex 
Ochoa fell off his glove. 
</P>
<P>
	Ochoa was credited with a double and scored moments later on a  
single to center by Todd Dunn, giving the Brewers the victory over 
the split-squad Padres. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like I let these guys down,'' said Brooks, hitless in  
two trips to the plate. ``I dropped that ball in the ninth with two 
out. It just kills me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Jupiter Fla., Marlins starter Brian Meadows allowed two runs  
in four innings, but was booed after walking Mark McGwire in 
Florida's 3-2 loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sorry they didn't get to see an 800-foot home run, but I  
didn't try to walk him,'' Meadows said. ``I like to see him hit 
home runs just as much as they do, but I don't want any to come off 
me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire was 0-for-2, including the fourth-inning walk. Darren  
Bragg homered for St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	In other games:  
</P>
<P>
                     *Devil Rays 3, Yankees (ss) 2    	
</P>
<P>
	At Tampa, Fla., David Cone gave up one run and four hits over  
four innings before Tampa Bay rallied to win with two runs in the 
seventh. 
</P>
