<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DuPont, Pioneer Hi-Bred Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DOVER, Del. (AP) -- Chemical giant DuPont Co., which wants a  
bigger presence in the life sciences industry, is discussing making 
a deal with Pioneer Hi-Bred International Inc., the world's largest 
seed corn company. 
</P>
<P>
	Although DuPont cautioned that there was no assurance any  
transaction will be concluded, the disclosure of the talks sent 
Pioneer stock up 40 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	DuPont already owns 20 percent of Pioneer Hi-Bred and indicated  
earlier this week it wants to expand in the areas of agriculture, 
biotechnology and pharmaceuticals. 
</P>
<P>
	In a brief announcement Friday, DuPont said it is in talks with  
Pioneer ``regarding a possible business combination.'' A 
spokeswoman for the Wilmington, Del.-based company said there would 
be no further comment until an agreement is reached or terminated. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials with Pioneer Hi-Bred, based in Des Moines, did not  
return a telephone call for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	But Pioneer shares rose $9.81 1/4 to $34.31 1/4 in trading on the New  
York Stock Exchange while DuPont shares fell $1.37 1/2 a share to 
$57.75. 
</P>
<P>
	DuPont has been the focus of much speculation in recent weeks  
with analysts predicting the company could be looking to buy 
Monsanto Co., a large life sciences company which last year failed 
in an effort to merge with drug maker American Home Products. 
</P>
<P>
	Monsanto makes Celebrex, a new arthritis pain medication and  
just one of the company's products that would make it an attractive 
target for DuPont. 
</P>
<P>
	Thom Brown, an analyst with Rutherford Brown &AMP; Catherwood in  
North Carolina, said even if a business venture with Pioneer is in 
the offing, it doesn't necessarily mean an agreement cannot be 
reached with Monsanto. 
</P>
<P>
	``It fits into DuPont's larger plan. Anything they can do to  
enhance that area (life sciences) is a plus,'' Brown said. ``(A 
deal with Pioneer) would be a plus for DuPont, but nothing like the 
plus of taking over Monsanto.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DuPont's business moves have been swift in the life sciences  
area the last few years. Two years ago, it spent $1.7 billion to 
buy 20 percent of Pioneer Hi-Bred, with the companies creating a 
joint venture for crop research. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, DuPont spent $2.6 billion to buy out Merck Co.'s  
share in a joint venture between the two, creating DuPont 
Pharmaceuticals. 
</P>
<P>
	DuPont's life sciences business totaled $4.3 billion in sales  
last year -- less than 20 percent of the company's total sales. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
