<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Prime Timber Wins San Felipe Stakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARCADIA, Calif. (AP) -- Prime Timber, wearing blinkers for the  
first time, handed stablemate and Kentucky Derby future book 
favorite Exploit his first loss Saturday, winning the $250,000 San 
Felipe Stakes at Santa Anita by two lengths. 
</P>
<P>
	Ridden by David Flores and carrying 116 pounds, Prime Timber  
covered 1 1-16 miles in 1:42, 4-5 of a second off the stakes record 
set by Pole Position 20 years ago. Prime Timber paid $7.20, $2.80 
and $2.80. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Timber's victory in the race for 3-year-olds, the final  
prep for the April 3 Santa Anita Derby, was his third in five 
starts. He was second on the other two, beaten a neck in the 
Hollywood Futurity and by one-half length in the San Rafael. He 
earned $150,000 to increase his career earnings to $308,200. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Timber collared 3-5 favorite Exploit and jockey Chris  
McCarron in midstretch and then drew away. 
</P>
<P>
	Flores had Prime Timber in fourth, within two lengths of  
Exploit, before making his move. 
</P>
<P>
	``He broke really good, and I just sat there comfortable in a  
good spot,'' Flores said. 
</P>
<P>
	High Wire Act set the pace until caught by Exploit at the head  
of the stretch, but was able to hold on for third, one-half length 
behind the runnerup. Finder's Gold finished fourth, 4 1/2 lengths 
behind High Wire Act. 
</P>
<P>
	Exploit, carrying 122 pounds, paid $2.20 and $2.10. High Wire  
Act, with Eddie Delahoussaye aboard at 116 pounds, paid $2.10 to 
show. 
</P>
<P>
	Exploit is the consensus favorite to win the May 1 Kentucky  
Derby. He was unbeaten in five starts and had won his only start of 
1999, the San Vicente Stakes at Santa Anita Feb. 6. 
</P>
<P>
	Historically, the San Felipe runners-up have had good luck. Real  
Quiet and Silver Charm, the runners-up the last two years, went on 
to win the Kentucky Derby. 
</P>
</TEXT>
